 end date index value as a future value and the number of years (or months) in between the two periods as the period in a financial calculation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The period that is used determines the basis of the rate that is calculated. &nbsp;<br>\r\nFor example,&nbsp;if yearly periods are used, a yearly inflation rate is calculated and if monthly periods are used, a monthly inflation rate is calculated. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The average annual inflation rate is the change in the average CPI for<br>\r\n		all items of&nbsp;one year compared with the average CPI for all items of<br>\r\n		the previous year expressed as a percentage.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(66,'Rebasing','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Rebasing</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rebasing of the consumer price index (CPI) refers to the process of resetting all of the actual indexes to a common starting point in a particular period, for example <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>.<br>\r\nThis is a bit like restarting a race, because by bringing all indexes to a common point, the historical divergences between indexes of different products are eliminated.<br>\r\nFailing to do this would inflate the effect of high-inflation items on the overall index and understate the effect of low-inflation items.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 16%;\"><span>Year</span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\">2008</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\">2009</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14%;\">2