mphasis_1\">December</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(102\\Ndp7\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(86\\Ndp2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(89\\Ndp2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(94\\Ndp6\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{100\\Ndp0}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Average</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{100\\Ndp0}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(84\\Ndp6\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(88\\Ndp2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(92\\Ndp6\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(97\\Ndp8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The CPI index is calculated from a base year which carries a value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>. &nbsp;All previous and subsequent periods are compared against the base year prices and expressed as a number in relation to the base index year value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Prices of products and services generally increase over time and periods before the base year, therefore these periods generally have values that are less than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>, while periods after the base year generally have values that are greater than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The second last rebasing of the CPI index occurred in January 2009 and was calculated based on the prices for products and services in 2008. &nbsp;These prices are therefore used as the base prices of the index -&nbsp;the average index value for the entire 2008 year was represented by an index value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{100}\\)</span>. &nbsp;The CPI of South Africa that was measured after 2008 is less than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>, and not more than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>&nbsp;as expected. &nbsp;This can be due to the fact that changes were made to the CPI in 2009 to bring it in line with international standards. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Traditionally, the South African CPI used the average of a year as the base period.<br>\r\nHowever, using a single month instead makes the linking in of the new weights and products much smoother than it would be using the yearly average. &nbsp;This single month method was used in December 2012. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The latest CPI weights were introduced in 2013 and are derived primarily from Statistics SA&#39;s household expenditure survey. &nbsp;The weights were price-updated to December 2012 (known as the weights reference period with an index value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{100}\\)</span>).<br>\r\nIn this case the prices of products and services generally increased over time.<br>\r\nSo&nbsp;periods before December 2012 therefore generally have values that are less than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>, while periods after December 2012 generally have values that are greater than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">International practice is to rebase the CPI periodically to avoid distortions that build up over time.</span> &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(67,'Real vs nominal','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Real vs nominal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The consumer price index is used in many applications. &nbsp;One of its most important implications is that of <span class=\"PalAa\">inflation adjustment</span> (also known as <span class=\"PalAa\">deflation</span>). &nbsp;The CPI can be used to adjust home prices, wages, salaries, pensions or any other amount to reveal their <span class=\"PalAa\">real </span>value. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you tell me your yearly salary is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 200 \\Tsp 000 \\Cdp00\\)</span>, you are referring to a <span class=\"PalAb\">current </span>rand or <span class=\"PalAb\">nominal </span>value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Nominal</span> or <span class=\"PalAb\">current </span>values are the amounts in rand received or paid.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Over time these <span class=\"PalAb\">nominal </span>values lose comparability unless they are <span class=\"PalAa\">adjusted</span> for <span class=\"PalAa\">inflation</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Real </span>values or <span class=\"PalAa\">inflation adjusted </span>values are <span class=\"PalAb\">nominal&nbsp;</span>values adjusted<br>\r\n		for changes in the CPI.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Suppose your <span class=\"PalAb\">nominal</span> income this year is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur 200 \\Tsp 000\\Cdp00 }\\)</span>. &nbsp;How does its purchasing power compare with your&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur 100 \\Tsp 000 \\Cdp00}\\)</span>&nbsp;income of&nbsp;ten years ago? &nbsp;<br>\r\nAre you better off or worse off?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If all prices also doubled, it would take twice as much money now to buy&nbsp;the goods you bought ten years ago and you would be no better off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How do I convert these <span class=\"PalAb\">nominal</span> rand values of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{100\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{200\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;to <span class=\"PalAa\">real</span> rand values?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The answer is: by <span class=\"PalAa\">deflating</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span><span class=\"PalAa\">Deflating</span>&nbsp;is the process of ensuring the comparability of&nbsp;</span><span><span class=\"PalAb\">nominal</span><br>\r\n		values by <span class=\"PalAa\">adjusting</span> them for <span class=\"PalAa\">inflation</span>. &nbsp;</span><span>This results in&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">real</span> values<br>\r\n		which can be compared.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The general formula for <span class=\"PalAa\">deflating</span> any variable is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{real value}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb{\\text{nominal value in rands}}}{\\text{CPI}}\\times100 \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(68,'Interpretation','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Interpretation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following&nbsp;table gives a&nbsp;man&#39;s <span class=\"PalAa\">inflation adjusted</span>/<span class=\"PalAa\">real</span> salary below. &nbsp;The base year is 2008 with a CPI of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 20%;\">Year</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Yearly salary<br>\r\n		in Rands</span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 20%;\">CPI</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Inflation adjusted salary</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\">2008</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur145\\Tsp720\\Cdp00}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100,0\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 9%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur145\\Tsp720\\Cdp00}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\">2011</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur160\\Tsp920\\Cdp00}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(92,6\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur173\\Tsp779\\Cdp70}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\">2012</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur178\\Tsp600\\Cdp00}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(97,8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur182\\Tsp617\\Cdp59}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The difference between his <span class=\"PalAb\">nominal</span> salary of 2011 and 2008 is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur160\\Tsp920\\Cdp00}-\\PalAb{\\Cur145\\Tsp720\\Cdp00}=\\PalAb{\\Cur15\\Tsp200\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The difference between his <span class=\"PalAa\">real</span> (<span class=\"PalAa\">inflation adjusted</span>) salary of 2011 and 2008 is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur173\\Tsp779\\Cdp70}-\\PalAa{\\Cur145\\Tsp720\\Cdp00}=\\PalAa{\\Cur28\\Tsp059\\Cdp70}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The conclusion is that although he received a <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur 15 \\Tsp 200 \\Cdp 00}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">increase</span> in salary from 2008 to 2011, the purchasing power of this money increased by more than that. &nbsp;The <span class=\"PalAa\">purchasing power</span> of this money <span class=\"PalAa\">increased</span> by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur 28 \\Tsp 059 \\Cdp 70}\\)</span>. &nbsp;<br>\r\nThis increase was because the CPI of 2011 was less than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>. &nbsp;The inflation rate dropped and the <span class=\"PalAa\">purchasing power</span> of a rand <span class=\"PalAa\">increased</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The difference between his&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">nominal</span>&nbsp;salary of 2012 and 2008 is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur178\\Tsp600\\Cdp00}-\\PalAb{\\Cur145\\Tsp720\\Cdp00}=\\PalAb{\\Cur32\\Tsp880\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The difference between his&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">real</span>&nbsp;salary of 2012 and 2008 is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur182\\Tsp617\\Cdp59}-\\PalAa{\\Cur145\\Tsp720\\Cdp00}=\\PalAa{\\Cur36\\Tsp897\\Cdp59}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The conclusion is that although he received a <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur 32 \\Tsp 880 \\Cdp 00}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">nominal increase</span> in salary from 2008 to 2012, the <span class=\"PalAa\">increase</span> in <span class=\"PalAa\">real</span> salary was <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur 36 \\Tsp 897 \\Cdp 59}\\)</span>. &nbsp;<br>\r\nThis<span class=\"PalAa\"> increase</span> was because the CPI of 2012 was less than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Please note that this comparison of salaries or any other monetary value can only be done between a value in the base year and the same value in some other year. &nbsp;In the first case the man&#39;s 2011 salary was adjusted&nbsp;to the rand value in 2008. &nbsp;Then the comparison between the 2008 salary and the inflation adjusted 2011 salary was made. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This comparison may never be done between any other two years. &nbsp;One of the years has to be the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">base</span> year. &nbsp;This means, the difference between his real salary of 2012 and his real salary of 2011&nbsp;does <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">not</span> represent the change in salary between 2011 and 2012.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We see that if the CPI is <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">less</span> than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>, then the <span class=\"PalAa\">increase</span> in the <span class=\"PalAa\">real</span> value of money is <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">greater</span> than the <span class=\"PalAb\">increase</span> in the <span class=\"PalAb\">nominal</span> value of the money.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\text{CPI} &amp;&lt; 100\\\\ \\text{increase in } \\PalAa{\\text{real}}\\text{ value}&amp;&gt;\\text{increase in }\\PalAb{ \\text{nominal}}\\text{ value} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(69,'Activity 1 info','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Activity 1 info</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>You are going to watch a video&nbsp;on the exchange rate. &nbsp;Watch with attention, because afterwards you will have to do the following activity:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Match the description in the first column of the table with the answer in the second column.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"4\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 55%;\">Description</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"4\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 45%;\">Answer</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">1</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 48%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Fall in the value of a currency in a floating exchange rate system.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">A</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 388px; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Forex market</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Operates 24 hours on weekdays.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">B</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Devaluation</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">3</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Interest rate, political stability and inflation rate.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">C</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Exchange rate</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">4</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Country makes a conscious decision to lower its exchange rate in a fixed or semi-fixed exchange rate system.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">D</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Depreciation</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">5</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The price for which the currency of a country can be exchanged for another country&#39;s currency.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">E</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Fixed exchange rate</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">6</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Government intervenes to keep the value of a currency at a certain level against other countries.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">F</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Appreciation</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">7</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Increase in value of currency, increase in value of exchange rate.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">G</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Factors influencing exchange rate</span><br>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(70,'Video 1','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the first part&nbsp;of this video on&nbsp;the exchange rate:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/351.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(71,'Video 2','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the second part&nbsp;of this video on&nbsp;the exchange rate:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/352.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(72,'Activity 1 info','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Activity 1 info</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You are going to watch a video&nbsp;on the fine ounce. &nbsp;Watch with attention, because afterwards you will have to do the following activity:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">State whether the statements are true or false.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">In March 1980 the fixed gold price was accepted.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The gold price is fixed every weekday in London at 10:30 and 15:00 London time.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The London fixings are reflected in contracts and official statistics.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">In South Africa, the Development Bank is the sole seller of gold bullion in the international gold market.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Gold bullion can be coins or bars.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Gold coins can be used as actual money.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(73,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Watch&nbsp;this video on&nbsp;the fine ounce:</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/353.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(74,'Activity 1 info','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Activity 1 info</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You are going to watch a video&nbsp;on the gross domestic product and growth rate. &nbsp;Watch with attention, because afterwards you will have to do the following activity:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Match the description in the first column of the table with the answer in the second column.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"4\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 58%;\">Description</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"4\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\">Answer</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">1</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 51%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Impact of inflation is removed from growth rate.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">A</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Growth rate</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Component of GDP that measures purchases of durable and nondurable goods as well as services.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">B</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Gross domestic product (GDP)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">3</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Year-to-year or quarter-to-quarter % change in value of GDP.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">C</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Government expenditures</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">4</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Component of GDP that measures civil servants, military personnel, roads and public buildings.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">D</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Personal consumption</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">5</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Measures the country&#39;s total output by including everything produced by all people and all companies in a country.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">E</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Real growth rate</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(75,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Watch&nbsp;this video on&nbsp;the gross domestic product and growth rate:</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/354.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(76,'Video - Measure','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Watch&nbsp;this video on how the gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate is&nbsp;measured:</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/355.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(77,'Measure growth rate','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">How is the GDP growth rate measured?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Statistics SA publishes different approaches to measure the growth of real GDP, according to</span>&nbsp;the publication <span class=\"PalAa\"><u>http://www.statssa.gov.za/articles/15%20Measuring%20GDP.pdf</u></span>. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">These approaches include:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The annual real growth rate</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The real GDP quarterly growth at a seasonally adjusted and annualised rate (Q/Q rate)</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The real GDP unadjusted year-on-year quarterly growth (Y/Y growth)</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(78,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition of a variable</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A variable can be considered as a box in which values can be placed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Sometimes there is only one value that can be placed in the box&nbsp;and you have to determine what that value is. &nbsp;At other times you get to pick a value that can be put into the box. &nbsp;These two different situations will be explained below.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Do you remember when you were in primary school&nbsp;and you were learning about addition? &nbsp;The teacher would hand you worksheets with&nbsp;instructions like the following:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Fill in the box:</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Box}+4=6\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Variables can be used to represent the box. &nbsp;Suppose we use an <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{x}\\)</span> to replace the box.<br>\r\nNow we can say:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Find the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>&nbsp;for which&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x+4=6\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Why did we switch from boxes to letters? &nbsp;We did this because letters are more practical.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For instance, the formula for finding the area of a square is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalBc A&amp;=\\PalAa\\ell \\times \\PalAa\\ell\\\\&amp;=\\PalAa\\ell^2\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The letter <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A\\)</span> represents the area and the letter <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\ell\\)</span>&nbsp;the length of a side of the square.<br>\r\nThis formula makes more sense than, for example:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc\\bigcirc=\\PalAa\\triangle^2\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The two formulae say exactly the same thing, but using <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc A\\)</span> for area and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\ell\\)</span>&nbsp; for length are&nbsp;more useful than using <span class=\"PalBc\">a circle</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"PalAa\">a&nbsp;triangle</span>. &nbsp;Boxes are fine, but letters are better.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(79,'Symbols','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Symbols</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A <span class=\"BodyText\">variable</span> is something which can assume any one of several numeric values.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The symbols most often used to represent variables are letters of the alphabet, both upper case such as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A,B,C\\dots\\)</span> and lower case such as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\dots x,y,z\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"BodyText\">symbol</span> or letter which is used to represent a variable is simply a label. &nbsp;Its specific value has to be assigned directly or be determined by calculation in each relevant instance.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Sometimes, we will choose a letter that reminds us of the quantity it represents, such as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(t\\)</span> for time, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(v\\)</span> for voltage&nbsp;or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span> for bacteria. &nbsp;Always choose a symbol that is short and that makes sense.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">How do we convert phrases to mathematical expressions?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert the following statement to a mathematical expression:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">&quot;The sum of a number and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span>.&quot;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">&quot;a number&quot; means a variable. &nbsp;Pick a letter, for example&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 12%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">&quot;the sum&quot; means you add.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 12%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">&quot;and&quot; means what you add comes next, namely 6.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 12%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">We can write this expression as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x+6\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the mathematical expression is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x+6\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(80,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert the following statement&nbsp;to a mathematical expression:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">&quot;The <span class=\"PalBc\">sum</span> of a&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">man&#39;s age</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">half</span> his <span class=\"PalAb\">son&#39;s age</span>.&quot;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">There are two variables here, because we do not know the man&#39;s age nor his son&#39;s. &nbsp;Let us use different variables than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>. &nbsp;Let us call the <span class=\"PalAa\">man&#39;s age</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa m\\)</span> and the <span class=\"PalAb\">son&#39;s age</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb s\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">The word &quot;<span class=\"PalBc\">sum</span>&quot; means we are <span class=\"PalBc\">adding</span> the two terms.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">son&#39;s age</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb s\\)</span>&nbsp;needs to be <span class=\"PalAb\">divided in half</span> before it gets into the expression.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">We can write this expression as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa m\\PalBc+\\PalAb{\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}s}\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the mathematical expression is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(m+{\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}s}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:54','2017-10-11 10:04:54','',NULL),(81,'Method 1','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Method 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The annual growth rate reflects the changes<br>\r\n		in the annual GDP&nbsp;between different years.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The formula for calculating the annual real growth rate is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{Annual growth rate}= \\left( \\left( \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP current year}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP base year}}}\\right)^\\frac{1}{\\PalBc n}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 22%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">where</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 6%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 560px; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the <span class=\"PalBc\">number of years</span> between the <span class=\"PalAa\">current</span> and the <span class=\"PalAb\">base</span> year.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you calculate the annual growth rate between two consecutive years, the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalBc\">one</span> and the formula reduces to:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{Annual growth rate}= \\left( \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP current year}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP base year}}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(82,'Method 2','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Method 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">It represents the quarterly growth at a <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">seasonally adjusted</span> and<br>\r\n		<span class=\"Emphasis_1\">annualised rate</span>. &nbsp;It reflects the changes in the real GDP from<br>\r\n		<span class=\"PalAa\">one quarter</span> to the <span class=\"PalAb\">next</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">It is calculated by raising the percentage </span>change<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> between the&nbsp;two quarters to the <span class=\"PalBc\">power of</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc4\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n<li>The quarters are seasonally adjusted to remove all seasonal effects&nbsp;before its annualised.</li>\r\n<li>It is assumed that the percentage change from the <span class=\"PalAa\">one quarter</span>&nbsp;to the <span class=\"PalAb\">following quarter</span> will be maintained for the entire year.</li>\r\n<li>It is called <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">annualising</span>&nbsp;and is used in South Africa as the official economic&nbsp;growth rate.</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\">The advantage is that the quarterly growth rates can directly be compared with previous annual movements.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\">The disadvantage is that sometimes the annualised data can be very volatile due to the effects of any irregular&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">occurrences during a specific quarter, for example, labour disputes.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The formula used to calculate the percentage change between two quarters at an annualized rate is given below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{(Q/Q) growth rate}= \\left( \\left( \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}}_{\\PalAa{\\text{current quarter}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}}_{\\PalAb{\\text{previous quarter}}}}\\right)^\\PalBc4-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Annualising</span> is to express the percentage change in the GDP between two consecutive quarters of a year in yearly terms, even though the percentage change does not directly apply to a year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The percentage change in GDP between two consecutive quarters has been mathematically converted to yearly terms in an annualised number.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The annualised percentage change in the GDP is often theoretical because there is no guarantee that the percentage change in the GDP will be maintained between the remaining quarters of the entire year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(83,'Method 3','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Method 3</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">It compares the quarterly level of the real GDP in a&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">specific</span><br>\r\n		<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">quarter</span>&nbsp;with the <span class=\"PalAb\">same quarter</span> of the <span class=\"PalAb\">previous year</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The quarters in this method are not seasonally adjusted or annualised.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">It removes the impact of seasonal variations.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">It looks at what happened to the economy over the entire previous year&nbsp;and not only at the last <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> months.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">This is not considered as the official method to calculate the economy&#39;s growth rate, but remains a very useful measurement.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The formula used to calculated the unadjusted year-on-year quarterly percentage change is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{(Y/Y) growth rate}= \\left( \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}}_{\\PalAa{\\text{specific quarter in current year}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}}_{\\PalAb{\\text{specific quarter in previous year}}}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(84,'Methods summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Methods summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following tables shows some of the GDP values as published by Statistics SA in</span><br>\r\n<span class=\"PalAa\"><u>http://www.statssa.gov.za/publications/P0441/P04414thQuarter2012.pdf</u></span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Annual real growth rate between consecutive years</h3>\r\n\r\n<table align=\"center\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 27%;\">Period<br>\r\n		Annual</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 46%;\"><span>Real annual&nbsp;</span><span>GDP<br>\r\n		(<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur\\)</span> million)</span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 27%;\"><span>Annual real<br>\r\n		growth rate</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px; text-align: center;\">2003</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp273\\Tsp129\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 205px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 11%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2004</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp330\\Tsp390\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2005</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp401\\Tsp066\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\Ndp3\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2006</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp478\\Tsp492\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">2007</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur1\\Tsp561\\Tsp076}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\Ndp6\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">2008</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur1\\Tsp619\\Tsp802}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{3\\Ndp8}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2009</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp598\\Tsp057\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-1\\Ndp3\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2010</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp646\\Tsp664\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp0\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2011</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp700\\Tsp826\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp3\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2012</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp741\\Tsp549\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The formula used to calculate the annual real growth rate between consecutive years&nbsp;is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{Annual growth rate}= \\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{current year}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{previous year}}}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the annual real growth rate from <span class=\"PalAb\">2007</span> to <span class=\"PalAa\">2008</span> is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 41%;\">\r\n		<p>Annual growth rate</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(= \\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{2008}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{2007}}}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\Cur1\\Tsp619\\Tsp802}}{\\PalAb{\\Cur1\\Tsp561\\Tsp076}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalBb{3\\Ndp8}\\% \\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Percentage change between two quarters at an annualised rate (Q/Q)</h3>\r\n\r\n<table align=\"center\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 20%;\">Quarters</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 30%;\">Annualised<br>\r\n		quarterly GDP<br>\r\n		(<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur\\)</span> million)</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 205px;\">Annualised percentage change.<br>\r\n		Quarterly growth rate as&nbsp;<br>\r\n		an annual rate (Q/Q)</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px; text-align: center;\">2011:1</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp688\\Tsp852\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">2011:2</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp695\\Tsp909\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Ndp7\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">2011:3</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp702\\Tsp846\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Ndp6\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">2011:4</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp715\\Tsp698\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp1\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">2012:1</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp726\\Tsp539\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Ndp6\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2012:2</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur1\\Tsp740\\Tsp329}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2012:3</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur1\\Tsp744\\Tsp988}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{1\\Ndp1}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">2012:4</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp754\\Tsp342\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The formula used to calculate the percentage change between two quarters at an annualised rate is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{(Q/Q) growth rate}= \\left(\\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{current quarter}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{previous quarter}}}}\\right)^4-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the percentage change between <span>quarter 2 of 2012</span> and <span>quarter 3 of 2012</span>&nbsp;at&nbsp;an annualised rate is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 39%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>Q/Q growth rate</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(= \\left(\\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{quarter 3 of 2012}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{quarter 2 of 2012}}}}\\right)^4-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 330px; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle= \\left( \\left( \\frac{\\PalAa{\\Cur1\\Tsp744\\Tsp988}}{\\PalAb{\\Cur1\\Tsp740\\Tsp329}}\\right)^4-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 330px; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalBb{1\\Ndp1}\\%\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Unadjusted year-on-year quarterly growth (Y/Y growth)</h3>\r\n\r\n<table align=\"center\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 20%;\">Quarters</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 40%;\">Quarterly value<br>\r\n		added to GDP<br>\r\n		(<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur\\)</span>&nbsp;million)</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 205px;\">Real GDP unadjusted<br>\r\n		year-on-year quarterly<br>\r\n		percent change (Y/Y)</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px; text-align: center;\">2011:1</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur410\\Tsp603\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 205px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2011:2</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur423\\Tsp026\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp4\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2011:3</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur428\\Tsp925\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp0\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2011:4</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur438\\Tsp273}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp1\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2012:1</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur419\\Tsp963\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Ndp3\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2012:2</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur435\\Tsp188\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2012:3</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur438\\Tsp296\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Ndp2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2012:4</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur448\\Tsp103}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{2\\Ndp2}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The formula used to calculate the unadjusted year-on-year quarterly percent change&nbsp;is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{(Y/Y) growth rate}= \\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{specific quarter in current year}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{specific quarter in previous year}}}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The year-on-year quarterly percentage change between quarter 4 of 2011 and quarter 4 of 2012&nbsp;is calculated as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 33%;\">\r\n		<p>(Y/Y) growth rate</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(= \\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{quarter 4 of 2012}}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{GDP}_{\\text{quarter 4 of 2011}}}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 330px;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{\\PalAa{\\Cur448\\Tsp103}}{\\PalAb{\\Cur438\\Tsp273}}-1 \\right) \\times 100\\)</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 330px;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalBb{2\\Ndp2}\\%\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(85,'Definitions','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definitions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The words are a mouthful, but the ideas are simple.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Commutative law of addition</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The sum of two numbers is unique. &nbsp;It does not matter&nbsp;which&nbsp;number<br>\r\n		is placed first and which is placed second, the result is the same.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose we use variables <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa A\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb B\\)</span>. &nbsp;Then this law can be written as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/616.JPG\" style=\"width: 590px; height: 108px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa A+\\PalAb B&amp;=\\PalAb B+\\PalAa A\\\\\\PalAa 5+\\PalAb 2&amp;=\\PalAb 2+\\PalAa 5\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Commutative law of multiplication</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The product of two numbers is unique.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>For variables&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa A\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb B\\)</span>&nbsp;this law can be written as:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/617.JPG\" style=\"width: 403px; height: 193px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa A\\times\\PalAb B&amp;=\\PalAb B\\times\\PalAa A\\\\\\PalAa 2\\times\\PalAb 3&amp;=\\PalAb 3\\times\\PalAa 2\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(86,'Comparison graph','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Comparison graph</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The figure below shows the relationship between the <span>quarterly growth</span> at a seasonally adjusted and annualised rate (<span>solid line - Q/Q</span>) and the unadjusted <span>year-on-year quarterly</span> growth rate (<span>dotted line - Y/Y</span>) for the first quarter of 2008 to the third quarter of 2012.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>growth rates (<span>bars</span>) are also added to show the comparison between the quarterly and annual growth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"420\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/441.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(87,'Examples','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Commutative law of addition</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa6+\\PalAa2&amp;=\\PalAb2+\\PalAb6&amp;\\text{because}&amp;&amp;\\PalAa8&amp;=\\PalAb8 \\\\ \\PalAa{3\\Ndp1}+\\PalAa{9\\Ndp3}&amp;=\\PalAb{9\\Ndp3}+\\PalAb{3\\Ndp1}&amp;\\text{because}&amp;&amp;\\PalAa{12\\Ndp4}&amp;=\\PalAb{12\\Ndp4}\\\\ \\PalAa{-7\\Ndp6}+\\PalAa{2\\Ndp3}&amp;=\\PalAb{2\\Ndp3}+\\PalAb{-7\\Ndp6}&amp;\\text{because}&amp;&amp;\\PalAa{-5\\Ndp3}&amp;=\\PalAb{-5\\Ndp3} \\\\ \\PalAa{-11\\Ndp1}+\\PalAa{-4\\Ndp4}&amp;=\\PalAb{-4\\Ndp4}+\\PalAb{-11\\Ndp1}&amp;\\text{because}&amp;&amp;\\PalAa{-15\\Ndp5}&amp;=\\PalAb{-15\\Ndp5} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Commutative law of multiplication</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa5\\times\\PalAa2&amp;=\\PalAb2\\times\\PalAb5&amp;&amp;\\text{because}&amp;\\PalAa{10}&amp;=\\PalAb{10} \\\\ \\PalAa{2\\Ndp2}\\times\\PalAa{3\\Ndp5}&amp;=\\PalAb{3\\Ndp5}\\times\\PalAb{2\\Ndp2}&amp;&amp;\\text{because}&amp;\\PalAa{7\\Ndp7}&amp;=\\PalAb{7\\Ndp7}\\\\ \\PalAa{-8\\Ndp1}\\times\\PalAa{9\\Ndp4}&amp;=\\PalAb{9\\Ndp4}\\times\\PalAb{-8\\Ndp1}&amp;&amp;\\text{because}&amp;\\PalAa{-76\\Ndp14}&amp;=\\PalAb{-76\\Ndp14} \\\\ \\PalAa{-11}\\times\\PalAa{-13}&amp;=\\PalAb{-13}\\times\\PalAb{-11}&amp;&amp;\\text{because}&amp;\\PalAa{143}&amp;=\\PalAb{143} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, the commutative laws say you can swop numbers around and still get the same answer.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(88,'Definitions','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definitions</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Associative law of addition</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The sum of three numbers does not depend on<br>\r\n		which two are added first, the result is unique.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For variables <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa A\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb B\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc C\\)</span> this law can be written as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} (\\PalAa A+\\PalAb B)+\\PalBc C&amp;=\\PalAa A+(\\PalAb B+\\PalBc C) \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/621.JPG\" style=\"width: 465px; height: 60px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} (\\PalAa 5+\\PalAb 2)+\\PalBc 3&amp;=\\PalAa 5+(\\PalAb 2+\\PalBc 3) \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Associative law of multiplication</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The product of three numbers does not depend on<br>\r\n		which two are multiplied first, the result is unique.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>For variables&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa A\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb B\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc C\\)</span>&nbsp;this law can be written as:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} (\\PalAa A\\times\\PalAb B)\\times\\PalBc C&amp;=\\PalAa A\\times(\\PalAb B\\times\\PalBc C) \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/622.JPG\" style=\"width: 507px; height: 173px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}(\\PalAa 3\\times\\PalAb 5)\\times\\PalBc 2&amp;=\\PalAa 3\\times(\\PalAb 5\\times\\PalBc 2) \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(89,'TAO_demo','<p>kokokok</p>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-12-15 09:18:34','',NULL),(90,'GDP omits','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">GDP omits</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">By now we know that the gross domestic product or GDP measures the total market value of all final goods and services produced within a country in one year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Economists believe that the GDP is not the best measure for a country&#39;s progress of well-being. &nbsp;The following internet&nbsp;site lists a few reasons why they feel the GDP must be replaced by a better measure:<br>\r\n<u>http://staffwww.fullcoll.edu/fchan/macro/2gdp_definition.htm</u></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Intermediate goods (goods that are inputs in the production of other goods) are not included in GDP to avoid double counting. &nbsp;In another words, only the value added is counted.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">GDP only counts the value of final products produced within a geographical boundary of a country. &nbsp;If South African citizens are working in Europe, they do not contribute to the South African GDP, but Europe&#39;s GDP.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">GDP sums the rand value of what has been produced in the economy over the year, not what was actually sold. &nbsp;For example, used car sales are not included.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">GDP was not designed to be a measure of well being of the society. &nbsp;GDP omits the following:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Non-marketable goods and services: tasks that do not involve market transactions, such as baby sitting, house cleaning, lawn mowing and so forth.<br>\r\nSome very useful output is excluded because it is unpaid employment.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Underground activities: illegal or cash transactions have no record.<br>\r\nGovernment&#39;s estimates on these transactions are not accurate.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Sales of used items: GDP measures only current output. &nbsp;Used car and thrift stores&#39; transactions are not counted.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Financial transactions: trading existing assets, such as stock or bond purchases.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Transfer payments: either government or private transfer payments are not included because goods and services are not produced in this process. &nbsp;Examples are social security benefits or kid&#39;s allowances.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Leisure: individuals consume leisure, just as they consume all the other tangible goods, which generate satisfactions. &nbsp;But leisure has no price tag, so it is not included in GDP.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Social costs: production processes may cause pollution. &nbsp;Polluted air and water may have social costs like bad air quality, and cancer patients. &nbsp;These social costs reduce our economic well-being. &nbsp;If money is not spent to clean up the oil spill or to cure the cancer patients, those expenses are not added to the GDP.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">GDP does not measure quality or nature of the product, which contributes to the satisfaction level of the consumers. &nbsp;Nominal GDP simply adds the dollar value of the product; it makes no&nbsp;differences if the product is a weapon, or a book.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(91,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Distributive law of multiplication over addition</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The product of a number with the sum of two other<br>\r\n		numbers&nbsp;is equal to the sum of the products of&nbsp;the<br>\r\n		first number with&nbsp;each of the other two numbers.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>For variables&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa A\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb B\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc C\\)</span>&nbsp;this law can be written as:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa A\\times(\\PalAb B+\\PalBc C)&amp;=\\PalAa A\\times\\PalAb B+\\PalAa A\\times\\PalBc C \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/618.JPG\" style=\"width: 643px; height: 113px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa 3\\times(\\PalAb 2+\\PalBc 4)&amp;=\\PalAa 3\\times\\PalAb 2+\\PalAa 3\\times\\PalBc 4 \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This means that&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span>&nbsp;lots of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb2+\\PalBc4)\\)</span>&nbsp;is the same as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span>&nbsp;lots of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb2\\)</span>&nbsp;plus&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span>&nbsp;lots of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\times\\)</span>&nbsp;can be <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">distributed</span> across the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb2+\\PalBc4\\)</span>&nbsp;into&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa 3\\times\\PalAb 2\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa 3\\times\\PalBc 4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(92,'Summary of laws','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary of laws</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Communicative laws: &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa A+\\PalAb B&amp;=\\PalAb B+\\PalAa A\\\\\\PalAa A\\times\\PalAb B&amp;=\\PalAb B\\times\\PalAa A\\end{align}\\)</span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Associative laws: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}(\\PalAa A+\\PalAb B)+\\PalBc C&amp;=\\PalAa A+(\\PalAb B+\\PalBc C)\\\\(\\PalAa A\\times\\PalAb B)\\times\\PalBc C&amp;=\\PalAa A\\times(\\PalAb B\\times\\PalBc C)\\end{align}\\)</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Distributive law: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa A \\times (\\PalAb B+\\PalBc C)=\\PalAa A\\times \\PalAb B+\\PalAa A\\times\\PalBc C\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">But be careful!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Commutative laws not for subtraction and division</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The commutative laws do&nbsp;not work for subtraction and division, for example:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa 7-\\PalAb 3&amp;\\neq\\PalAb 3-\\PalAa 7\\\\\\PalAa {10}\\div\\PalAb 2&amp;\\neq\\PalAb2\\div\\PalAa {10}\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equals sign with a line through is read as &quot;does not equal&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the subtraction calculation, commutation (changing the order)&nbsp;leads to the negative of the initial result,&nbsp;that is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-4\\)</span> instead of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa 7-\\PalAb 3=4\\)</span>&nbsp; while &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 3-\\PalAa 7=-4\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the division calculation, commutation leads to the inverse of the initial result,&nbsp;that is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\frac{1}{5}\\)</span> instead of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {10}\\div\\PalAb 2=5\\)</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;while &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb2\\div\\PalAa {10}=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{5}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">But we can transform expressions containing subtraction and division to ones containing only addition and multiplication.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To be specific, in the case of subtraction we <span class=\"PalAb\">change the sign</span> of the <span class=\"PalAb\">number being subtracted</span> and then add, for example:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa7-\\PalAb3=\\PalAa7+\\PalAb{-3}=\\PalAb{-3}+\\PalAa7=4\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the case of division we can replace the <span class=\"PalAb\">number being divided by</span> with&nbsp;its <span class=\"PalAb\">inverse</span> and multiply, for example:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10}\\div\\PalAb2=\\PalAa{10}\\times\\PalAb{2^{-1}}=\\PalAb{2^{-1}}\\times\\PalAa{10}=5\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Associative laws not for subtraction and division</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The associative laws do&nbsp;not work for subtraction and division, for example:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa {10}-(\\PalAb 5-\\PalBc 2)&amp;\\neq(\\PalAa {10}-\\PalAb 5)-\\PalBc2\\\\(\\PalAa {8}\\div\\PalAb 4)\\div\\PalBc2&amp;\\neq\\PalAa8\\div(\\PalAb {4}\\div\\PalBc2)\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We know that when you have more than one operation with the same priority you just operate from left to right. &nbsp;This means that an expression like <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\div4\\div2\\)</span> is highly ambiguous, because the result depends on the order in which the operations are performed. &nbsp;If you want a specific order you must enforce that using brackets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The conclusion is that, whereas for addition and multiplication we can change the order of the factors, for subtraction and division we cannot. &nbsp;Or rather, if we do, we must do so with care.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(93,'Identity properties','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Identity properties</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Four other fundamental rules that you must take notice of are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The product of any number with zero is zero: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A\\times\\PalAa0=\\PalAa0\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The product of any number with one is the number: &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A\\times\\PalAb1=A\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The sum of any number and its negative is zero: &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A+-A=\\PalAa0\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The product of any number and its inverse is one: &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A\\times A^{-1}=\\PalAb1\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(94,'Terminology','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Terminology</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In a fraction, the denominator tells us how many parts the whole is divided into&nbsp;and the numerator tells us how many of those parts we are dealing with, for example:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa3}{\\PalAb4}&amp;&amp;\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{numerator}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{denominator}}}\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Take note of&nbsp;some other important fraction terms to remember:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Proper fraction</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The numerator is less than the denominator, for example&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{3}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Improper fraction</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The numerator is greater than or equal to the denominator, for example <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{5}{3}\\)</span>&nbsp;or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{9}{9}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Mixed number/fraction</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A whole number and a fraction,&nbsp;for example&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{3}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{9}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Equivalent fractions</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Fractions that represent the same&nbsp;number,&nbsp;for example&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{6}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{3}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Reciprocal</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The multiplicative inverse of a number. For a fraction it means &#39;turn&nbsp;the fraction around&#39;,&nbsp;for example&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{10}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(95,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">One way to think of a fraction is as a division that has not been done yet. &nbsp;Why do we even use fractions? &nbsp;Why do we not just divide the two numbers and use the decimal instead? &nbsp;In this day of cheap calculators, this&nbsp;is a very good question.<br>\r\nFractions were invented long before decimal numbers&nbsp;as a way of showing portions less than one&nbsp;and they are still around. &nbsp;They are used in cooking, building, sewing, the stock market -&nbsp;they are everywhere&nbsp;and we need to understand them.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Remember, the number above the bar is called the numerator&nbsp;and the number below the bar is called the denominator.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa3}{\\PalAb4}&amp;&amp;\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{numerator}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{denominator}}}\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can read this fraction as &quot;three fourths&quot;, &quot;three over four&quot;&nbsp;or &quot;three divided by four&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Every fraction can be converted to a decimal by dividing. &nbsp;If you use a calculator to divide <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>, you will find that it is equal to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp75\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}=0\\Ndp75\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Remember, you can find the decimal equivalent of any fraction by dividing. &nbsp;Here are some other fractions and their decimal equivalents:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}=0\\Ndp5 \\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}=0\\Ndp25\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{8}=0\\Ndp125 \\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(96,'Mixed to improper','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Mixed number to improper fraction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>We can convert a mixed number to an improper fraction, using the following method:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p>Step 1</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Multiply the whole number by the denominator of the fraction.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 12%;\">\r\n		<p>Step 2</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Add the numerator of the fraction to the product.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 12%;\">\r\n		<p>Step 3</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write the sum over the original denominator.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Convert&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{3}\\)</span>&nbsp;to an improper fraction:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 65%;\">\r\n		<p>To convert the mixed number,</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc1\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa1}{\\PalAb3}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p>Step 1</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">multiply <span class=\"PalBc\">number</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc1\\)</span>&nbsp;with&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">denominator</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalBc1\\times\\PalAb3)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p>Step 3</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p>and add&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">numerator</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span>&nbsp;to product.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{(\\PalBc1\\times\\PalAb3)+\\PalAa1}{\\PalAb3}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p>Step 3</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p>Write <span class=\"BodyText\">sum over original <span class=\"PalAb\">denominator</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb3\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{\\PalAb3}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example, since three thirds is a whole, the whole number one is three thirds, plus one more third&nbsp;equals four thirds.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(97,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition of a reciprocal</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">When the product of two fractions equals one, the fractions are reciprocals.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Every non-zero fraction has a reciprocal. &nbsp;It is easy to determine the reciprocal of a fraction, because all you have to do is switch the numerator and denominator. &nbsp;That means,&nbsp;just turn the fraction around.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>To find the reciprocal of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}\\)</span>, just switch the numerator and denominator around. &nbsp;So the reciprocal of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}\\)</span>&nbsp;is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{3}\\)</span>.&nbsp; We know <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{3}}\\)</span>&nbsp;are reciprocals because:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}}\\times\\PalAb{\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{3}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{12}{12}=1\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To find the reciprocal of a whole number, just put one over the whole number. &nbsp;For example, the reciprocal of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}\\)</span>. &nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">We know </span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa2\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}}\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;are reciprocals because:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{1}}\\times\\PalAb{\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{2}=1\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(98,'GCF','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Greatest Common Factor</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">We reduce a fraction to lowest terms by finding an equivalent fraction in which the numerator and denominator are as small as possible.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, this means that when a fraction has been&nbsp;reduced, there is no number&nbsp;except one, that can be divided exactly into both the numerator and the denominator.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To reduce a fraction to its lowest terms, divide the numerator and denominator by their <span class=\"PalAb\">Greatest Common Factor</span> (<span class=\"PalAb\">GCF</span>).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The </span><span class=\"PalAb\">Greatest Common Factor</span><span class=\"BodyText\"> is the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">largest number that divides two or more numbers evenly.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is also called simplifying the fraction.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Simplify the fraction&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{20}{60}\\)</span>&nbsp;by reducing&nbsp;it&nbsp;to its lowest terms:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{20}{60}=\\displaystyle\\frac{20\\div\\PalAb{20}}{60\\div\\PalAb{20}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{3}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">GCF</span> of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {20}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(99,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A fraction is reduced to its lowest terms, or simplified, when its numerator and denominator have no common factors. &nbsp;It is easier to multiply, divide, add and subtract fractions when they are simplified. &nbsp;To simplify a fraction&nbsp;we find an equivalent fraction where the numerator and denominator have no common factors.<br>\r\nTo do this we need to use <span class=\"PalAa\">prime factors</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Prime factors</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">prime factors</span> of a number are the smallest divisors of that number.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, the <span class=\"PalAa\">prime factors</span> of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12\\)</span>&nbsp;are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12=\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa3\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\">By smallest divisors we mean that a prime factor has no divisors other than itself and one:</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 19%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa2\\)</span>&nbsp;can only be divided by itself, namely&nbsp;two, and one.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span>&nbsp;can only be divided by itself, namely three, and one.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Method to simplify fractions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Follow these steps to simplify a fraction:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rewrite both the numerator and denominator as the product of its <span class=\"PalAa\">prime factors</span>, respectively.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Find the factors common to both the numerator and denominator (that is the <span class=\"PalAb\">greatest common factor</span>), then&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">divide</span> by all the <span class=\"PalAb\">common factors</span>,&nbsp;called <span class=\"PalAb\">cancelling</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Find the products of the remaining factors, if more than one, in both the numerator and the denominator, respectively.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Reduce&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{6}{8}\\)</span>&nbsp;to its lowest terms.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Simplify the fraction:</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{6}{8}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rewrite each of the numerator and denominator as the product of its prime factors.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa3}{\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa2}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Divide by, or <span class=\"PalAb\">cancel</span>, the <span class=\"PalAb\">factor</span> of two that is <span class=\"PalAb\">common</span> to both the numerator and denominator, that is the <span class=\"PalAb\">GCF</span>. &nbsp;Since two divided by two equals one,&nbsp;the two&#39;s cancel each other out.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb\\not\\PalAb2\\times\\PalAa3}{\\PalAb\\not\\PalAb2\\times\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa2}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Left with only a <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> in the numerator. &nbsp;Multiply the remaining factors in the denominator to get <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(100,'Video - Factor','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video - Factor</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this&nbsp;video on the prime factors of a number to provide you with&nbsp;necessary background knowledge:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\">\r\n<video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/328.mp4\" width=\"500\">&nbsp;</video>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(101,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Reduce <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{30}{45}\\)</span>&nbsp;to its lowest terms.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Simplify the fraction:</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{30}{45}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rewrite each of the numerator and denominator as the product of its <span class=\"PalAa\">prime factors</span>. &nbsp;The prime factors of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(30\\)</span> are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa2\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa5\\)</span>. &nbsp;The prime factors of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span> are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa5\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAa5}{\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAa5}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Find the factors common to both the numerator and denominator, that is the <span class=\"PalAb\">greatest common factor</span>, then <span class=\"PalAb\">divide</span>&nbsp;by all these&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">common factors</span>,&nbsp;called&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">cancelling</span>. &nbsp;The greatest common factor&nbsp;of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(30\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{15}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac {\\PalAa2\\times{\\PalAb\\not}{\\PalAb3} \\times{\\PalAb\\not}\\PalAb5} {\\PalAa3\\times{\\PalAb\\not}{\\PalAb3}\\times{\\PalAb\\not}\\PalAb5}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Find the products of the remaining factors, if more than one, in both the numerator and the denominator, respectively.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{3}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, to simplify a fraction, we rewrite each of the numerator and denominator as the product of its <span class=\"PalAa\">prime factors</span>. &nbsp;The prime factors of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(30\\)</span> are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span>. &nbsp;The prime factors of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span> are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Then we divide the numerator and denominator by the <span class=\"PalAb\">greatest common factor</span> (<span class=\"PalAb\">GCF</span>). &nbsp;The greatest common factor,&nbsp;that is&nbsp;the largest integer that divides exactly into the numbers&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(30\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span>, is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span>.&nbsp; We can also say that we <span class=\"PalAb\">cancel</span> out the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span> on top of and below the line.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(102,'Video - Part','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video - Part</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on fractions as parts of a whole:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/329.mp4\" width=\"500\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(103,'Video - Multiplication','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video - Multiplication</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on multiplying fractions:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/330.mp4\" width=\"500\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(104,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are a few steps to follow when multiplying fractions. &nbsp;Let us use the following example&nbsp;to illustrate these steps.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate the following:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{3}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{9}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">First method</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simplify</span> the fractions by <span class=\"PalAb\">dividing</span> a numerator and a denominator by the <span class=\"PalAb\">same number</span>. &nbsp;Then <span class=\"PalAa\">multiply </span>the <span class=\"PalAa\">numerators</span> together and <span class=\"PalAa\">multiply </span>the<span class=\"PalAa\"> denominators</span> together.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate the following:</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{3}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{9}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert any mixed numbers to improper fractions.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{8}{3}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{9}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simplify</span>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">dividing</span>&nbsp;a numerator and a denominator by the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">same number</span>.<br>\r\n		Note that&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\PalAb{\\div3}=\\PalAb1\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\PalAb{\\div3}=\\PalAb3\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{8}{\\PalAb\\not3_\\PalAb1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb\\not9^\\PalAb3}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{8}{1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simplify</span>&nbsp;again by&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">dividing</span>&nbsp;a numerator and a denominator by the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">same number</span>. &nbsp;Note that&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\PalAb{\\div4}=\\PalAb1\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\PalAb{\\div4}=\\PalAb2\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb\\not8^\\PalAb2}{1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{\\PalAb\\not4_\\PalAb1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{1}\\times\\frac{1}{1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simplify</span>&nbsp;again by&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">dividing</span>&nbsp;a numerator and a denominator by the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">same number</span>. &nbsp;Note that&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\PalAb{\\div2}=\\PalAb1\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\PalAb{\\div2}=\\PalAb5\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb\\not2^\\PalAb1}{1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{\\PalAb\\not{10}_\\PalAb5}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{1}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{5}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 5</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Multiply</span> the <span class=\"PalAa\">numerators</span> and place the answer&nbsp;above the line. &nbsp;Then <span class=\"PalAa\">multiply</span> the <span class=\"PalAa\">denominators</span> and place the answer below the line.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa3}{\\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa5}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{5}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Second method</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Alternatively you could simply <span class=\"PalAa\">multiply</span> the<span class=\"PalAa\"> numerators</span> together and place the answer above&nbsp;the line; then <span class=\"PalAa\">multiply </span>the <span class=\"PalAa\">denominators</span> together and place the answer below the line. &nbsp;Then <span class=\"PalAb\">simplify </span>the fraction.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate the following:</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{3}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{9}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert any mixed numbers to improper fractions.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{8}{3}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\displaystyle\\frac{9}{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Multiply</span>&nbsp;the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">numerators</span>&nbsp;and place the answer&nbsp;above the line. &nbsp;Then <span class=\"PalAa\">multiply</span> the <span class=\"PalAa\">denominators</span> and place the answer below the line.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa8\\times\\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa9}{\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAa4\\times\\PalAa{10}}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{72}{120}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simplify</span> the fraction. &nbsp;Note that&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(72\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(120\\)</span>&nbsp;are&nbsp;both <span class=\"PalAb\">divisible</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">by</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">