td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Hundreds</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Tens</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Units</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">As we <span class=\"PalAa\">move left</span>, each position is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">times bigger</span>, and as we <span class=\"PalAb\">move right</span>, each position is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">times smaller</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">But what if we continue past hundreds&nbsp;as we <span class=\"PalAa\">move left</span> and continue&nbsp;past units as we <span class=\"PalAb\">move right</span>? &nbsp;What is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10\\times}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">bigger</span> than hundreds and what is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10\\times}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">smaller</span> than units?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Thousands</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\leftarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Hundreds</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\leftarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Tens</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Units</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Tenths</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\leftarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\leftarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{10}\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(10\\times\\text{ bigger})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(10\\times\\text{ bigger})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Thousands <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1\\Tsp000\\text{s})\\)</span>&nbsp;are&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10\\times}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">bigger</span>&nbsp;than hundreds and tenths <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{10}\\text{s})\\)</span>&nbsp;are&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10\\times}\\)</span>&nbsp;<br>\r\n<span class=\"PalAb\">smaller</span>&nbsp;than units.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(111,'Introduction 2','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We must write a decimal comma, so we know exactly where the units&#39; position&nbsp;is.<br>\r\nThe <span class=\"PalBc\"><strong>decimal comma</strong></span><strong> </strong>is written exactly to the right of the units&#39; position.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This can be&nbsp;illustrated with the number&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(634\\Ndp5\\)</span>&nbsp;as follows:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalBc\">decimal<br>\r\n		comma</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc,\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Hundreds</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Tens</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Units</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Tenths</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{10}\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can say &quot;six hundred and thirty four and five tenths&quot;, but we usually just say &quot;six hundred and thirty four <span class=\"PalBc\">comma</span> five&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Decimal comma</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBc\"><strong>decimal comma</strong></span><strong> </strong>is the most important part of a decimal number. &nbsp;It is exactly to the right of the units&#39; position. &nbsp;Without it, we would be lost and not know what each position meant.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Now we can continue with smaller and smaller values, from <span class=\"PalBc\"><strong>tenths&nbsp;</strong></span>to <span class=\"PalBc\"><strong>hundredths </strong></span>and so on. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This can be&nbsp;illustrated with the number&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(18\\Ndp692\\)</span>&nbsp;as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalBc\">decimal<br>\r\n		comma</span></span></td>\r\n		<td rowspan=\"1\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc,\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Tens</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\leftarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Units</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Tenths</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Hundredths</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Thousandths</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\leftarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{10}\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{100}\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\rightarrow\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{1\\Tsp000}\\text{s}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(10\\times\\text{ bigger})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 16%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(10\\times\\text{ smaller})}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(112,'Representation','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Representation</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Written as a&nbsp;whole number and fractions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A decimal number can be written as a whole number plus tenths, hundredths and so forth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, what is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp24\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">On the left side of the decimal comma is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span>, that is the whole number part.<br>\r\nThere are two digits on the right side of the decimal comma. &nbsp;The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span> is in the tenths&nbsp;position, meaning &#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span> tenths&#39;, and the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>&nbsp;is in the hundredths position, meaning &#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>&nbsp;hundredths&#39;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp24\\)</span> is &#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span> tenths and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span> hundredths&#39;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Written as a decimal fraction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A decimal number can also be written as a decimal fraction.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"BodyText\">A decimal fraction is a fraction where the denominator<br>\r\n		(the bottom number) is a number such as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span><br>\r\n		and so forth,&nbsp;in other words a power of ten.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The decimal number&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp24\\)</span>&nbsp;would look like&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{324}{100}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">And the decimal number&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\Ndp752\\)</span> would look like <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{24\\Tsp752}{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Written as a whole number and a decimal fraction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A decimal number can be written as a whole number and a decimal fraction. &nbsp;Or, you could think of a decimal number as a whole number plus a decimal fraction.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The decimal number&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp24\\)</span>&nbsp;would look like&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{24}{100}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\displaystyle\\frac{24}{100}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">And the decimal number&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\Ndp752\\)</span>&nbsp;would look like <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{752}{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\displaystyle\\frac{752}{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(113,'Decimals to fractions','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Decimals to fractions</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Method</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Follow these&nbsp;steps&nbsp;to convert a decimal to a fraction:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write down the decimal divided by one, like this:&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text{decimal}}{1}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Multiply both the numerator and denominator (top and bottom) by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span> for every number after the decimal comma.<br>\r\n		For example, if there are two numbers after the decimal comma, use <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>;&nbsp;if there are three then use <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span>, and so on.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Simplify (or reduce) the fraction.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Express&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp625\\)</span>&nbsp;as a fraction:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 57%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write down the decimal divided by one.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{0\\Ndp625}{1}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 57%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalBc\">Multiply</span> both the numerator&nbsp;and the denominator&nbsp;by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span>. &nbsp;There were <span class=\"PalBc\">three digits</span> after the <span class=\"PalBc\">decimal comma</span>, so that is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{10}\\times\\PalBc{10}\\times\\PalBc{10}=\\PalBc{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{0\\Ndp625}{1}\\PalBc{\\times}\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc{1\\Tsp000}}{\\PalBc{1\\Tsp000}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{625}{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 57%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simplify</span> the fraction by <span class=\"PalAb\">dividing</span> both the numerator&nbsp;and denominator&nbsp;by the <span class=\"PalAb\">common factor</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{25}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{625\\PalAb{\\div25}}{1\\Tsp000\\PalAb{\\div25}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{25}{40}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 57%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simplify</span>&nbsp;the fraction again by <span class=\"PalAb\">dividing</span> both the numerator and denominator by the <span class=\"PalAb\">common factor</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb5\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{25\\PalAb{\\div5}}{40\\PalAb{\\div5}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{5}{8}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the decimal <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp625\\)</span>&nbsp;expressed as a fraction is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{5}{8}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(114,'Fractions to decimals','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Fractions to decimals</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Method</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Follow these&nbsp;steps&nbsp;to convert a fraction to a decimal:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Find a number you can multiply by the denominator (bottom) of the fraction to make it <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span>, or any <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span> followed by zeros.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Multiply both the numerator and the denominator (top and bottom) by that number.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Then write down just the numerator (top number), putting the decimal comma in the correct place, that is&nbsp;one space from the right-hand side for every zero in the denominator (bottom number).</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Express&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{16}\\)</span>&nbsp;as a decimal:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We have to <span class=\"PalAa\">multiply</span> the denominator <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(16\\)</span> by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{625}\\)</span> for it to become <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{10\\Tsp000}\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(16\\PalAa{\\times625}=\\PalBc{10\\Tsp000}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Multiply</span>&nbsp;both the numerator and the denominator (top and bottom) by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{625}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3\\PalAa{\\times626}}{16\\PalAa{\\times625}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{1\\Tsp875}{\\PalBc{10\\Tsp000}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write down the numerator (top number) <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp875\\)</span> with the <span class=\"PalBc\">decimal comma</span> <span class=\"PalBc\">four spaces</span> from the right,&nbsp;because <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{10\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;has <span class=\"PalBc\">four zeros</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=0\\PalBc\\Ndp1875\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>So, the fraction&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{16}\\)</span>&nbsp;expressed as a decimal&nbsp;is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp1875\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Calculator method</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The example above was given to explain to you the mathematics behind the scenes. &nbsp;The good news is that there is an easier way to express a&nbsp;fraction as a decimal number:&nbsp;just use your calculator.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Using your calculator, key in</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\div16=\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp1875\\)</span>&nbsp;will be displayed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(115,'Rounding','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Rounding</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Rounding means reducing the digits in a number while trying to keep<br>\r\n		its value similar. &nbsp;The result is less accurate, but easier to use.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Method to round numbers</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Decide which is the <span class=\"PalBc\">last digit</span> to <span class=\"PalBc\">keep</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Leave it the <span class=\"PalAb\">same</span> if the <span class=\"PalAb\">next digit</span> is <span class=\"PalAb\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb5\\)</span>.&nbsp;&nbsp;This is called <span class=\"PalAb\">rounding down</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">But&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">increase</span>&nbsp;it&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">by one</span>&nbsp;if the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">next digit</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa5\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">or more</span>. &nbsp;This is called&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">rounding up</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If necessary, replace removed digits with zeros, for example when rounding whole numbers.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example of rounding whole numbers</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Round <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(74\\)</span> to the nearest <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We want to <span class=\"PalBc\">keep</span> the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc7\\)</span>&nbsp;as it is in the <span class=\"PalBc\">tens&#39; position</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc74\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">next digit</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span> which is <span class=\"PalAb\">less than </span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb5\\)</span>, so <span class=\"PalAb\">no change</span> is needed to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc7\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc7\\PalAb4 \\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\approx\\PalAb{70}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Replace the removed digits with zeros, so the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span> is replaced by a <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb0\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb7\\PalAb0\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(74\\)</span>&nbsp;was&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">rounded down</span> and the answer is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(70\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example of rounding to units</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Round <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\Ndp6\\)</span> to the nearest unit.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We want to <span class=\"PalBc\">keep</span> the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc8\\)</span>&nbsp;as it is in the <span class=\"PalBc\">units&#39; position</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc8\\Ndp6\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">next digit</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa6\\)</span> which is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa5\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">or more</span>, so <span class=\"PalAa\">increase</span> the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc8\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">by one</span> to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa9\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc8\\Ndp\\PalAa6\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\approx\\PalAa9\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Since the removed digits came after the decimal comma, it is not necessary to replace them with zeroes.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa9\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>So,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\Ndp6\\)</span>&nbsp;was&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">rounded up</span>&nbsp;and the answer is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example of rounding to different&nbsp;digits</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Rounding&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(238\\Ndp7\\PalBc2\\PalAb48\\)</span></span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 43%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>to the nearest&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBc\">hundredth&nbsp;</span><span>gives</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(238\\Ndp7\\PalAb2\\)</span><span>.</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Rounding&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(238\\Ndp\\PalBc7\\PalAb248\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>to the nearest&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBc\">tenth&nbsp;</span>gives</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(238\\Ndp\\PalAb7\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Rounding&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(23\\PalBc8\\Ndp\\PalAa7248\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>to the nearest <span class=\"PalBc\">unit </span></span>gives</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(23\\PalAa9\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Rounding&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\PalBc3\\PalAa8\\Ndp7248\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>to the nearest <span class=\"PalBc\">ten </span></span>gives</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\PalAa{40}\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Rounding&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(238\\Ndp72\\PalBc4\\PalAa8\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>to <span class=\"PalBc\">three decimal places</span> gives</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(238\\Ndp72\\PalAa5\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Rounding&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc2\\PalAb38\\Ndp7248\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>to <span class=\"PalBc\">hundred</span> gives</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{200}\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(116,'Three types','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Three types</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Non-terminating decimal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert the fraction <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{22}{7}\\)</span>&nbsp;to a decimal number and round off your answer to three decimal&nbsp;places.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 18%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The fraction</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{22}{7}\\)</span>&nbsp;converted to a decimal number is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp1428571\\dots\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">and</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp1428571\\dots\\approx3\\Ndp143\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The symbol <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\approx\\)</span>&nbsp;is read as &quot;approximately equal to&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The decimal <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Ndp1428571\\dots\\)</span> is an example of a <span class=\"BodyText\">non-terminating</span> decimal because the answer goes on and on and is never completed.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Terminating decimal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert the fraction <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{8}\\)</span>&nbsp;to a decimal number and round off your answer to one decimal place.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 18%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The fraction</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{8}\\)</span>&nbsp;converted&nbsp;to a decimal number is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp375\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">and</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp375\\approx0\\Ndp4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The decimal <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp375\\)</span> is an example of a <span class=\"BodyText\">terminating</span> decimal because it is exact and complete.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Recurring decimal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert the fraction&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{7}{11}\\)</span>&nbsp;to a decimal number and round off your answer to two decimal&nbsp;places.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 18%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The fraction</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{7}{11}\\)</span>&nbsp;converted to a decimal number is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp636363\\dots\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">and</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp636363\\dots\\approx0\\Ndp64\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The decimal <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp636363\\dots\\)</span> is an example of a <span class=\"BodyText\">recurring</span> decimal because there are repeating digits.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This decimal <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp636363\\dots\\)</span> can also be written as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp\\dot{6}\\dot{3}\\)</span>&nbsp;and is pronounced as &quot;naught comma six three recurring&quot;. &nbsp;The dots on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span> and the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> tell us that the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span> and the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> are recurring.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The above recurring decimal can also be written as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp\\overline{63}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(117,'Population vs sample','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Population vs sample</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/418.jpg\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 282px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">A&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> is a&nbsp;collection of all items of interest or under investigation</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Typically there are too many items in a <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>&nbsp;to consider every one. &nbsp;<br>\r\nExamples of populations include the following:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class=\"Image\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Names of all registered voters in South Africa.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"Image\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Incomes of all families living in Cape Town.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"Image\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Annual returns of all stocks traded on the&nbsp;Johannesburg Stock Exchange.</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"Image\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Semester marks of all the students at&nbsp;Unisa.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">A <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> is the observed subset of a population.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is very important&nbsp;that this <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> must&nbsp;be representative of the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>. &nbsp;How does one manage this? There are several methods to choose&nbsp;a representative group.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(118,'Sampling','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Sampling</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Sampling</span> is the process of choosing a number of individuals for a study in such a way that the&nbsp;individuals represent the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> from which they were chosen.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/377.svg\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 450px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The theory of <span class=\"PalAb\">sampling</span> is as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Researchers want to gather information about a whole group of people -&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Researchers can only observe a part of the population -&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span>.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The findings from the sample are <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">generalised</span>, or extended, back to the population.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(119,'3 Types','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">3 Types</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The types of sampling methods that will be discussed are given in the diagram below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/652.JPG\" style=\"width: 601px; height: 217px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">There are several more types of sampling techniques but they fall outside the scope of this module.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(120,'Video 1','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video&nbsp;1</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the first part&nbsp;of this video on simple random sampling:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/364.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(121,'Video 2','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the second part of this video on simple random sampling:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/363.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(122,'Sample','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Sample</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/378.jpg\" style=\"width: 80%; height: 80%;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The method of simple random sampling can be explained as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> is all <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\Tsp000\\)</span> students from the FBN1501 class.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Participants are chosen randomly, either through a random number table or a random number generator.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> is made up of those <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(200\\)</span> students&nbsp;randomly chosen from the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(123,'Random selection','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Random selection</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A political candidate wants to determine the opinions of the voters in his ward.<br>\r\nHe&nbsp;decides on a sample of size <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span>. &nbsp;Using random numbers he chooses <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span> telephone&nbsp;numbers from the telephone directory for a telephonic survey. &nbsp;Is this procedure correct to find a random sample? &nbsp;Why not?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Not all residents may have telephones&nbsp;and all the numbers of those who do have telephones&nbsp;may not be included in the telephone directory. &nbsp;Therefore such a sample cannot be considered to be random.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Randomly choosing the members of a sample is important because it helps prevent <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">bias</span> in your results. Random selection allows <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">impersonal choice</span> to choose the sample, rather than the individual performing the poll (the sampler) to choose his/her own participants, or self-selection of respondents as in a voluntary response poll. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If a sampler does not use random selection, the sample will <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">favour</span> the selection of <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">certain groups</span>, possibly without the sampler even realising it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Difficulties and cautions&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the real world, a truly random sample is difficult to achieve, but you can come&nbsp;close. &nbsp;One of the most difficult steps is obtaining a <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">complete list</span> of every member&nbsp;in the population from which&nbsp;you want a sample.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">telephone book</span> for a city is often used for sampling. &nbsp;Some of the problems associated with using a telephone book are that it excludes those who do not have a telephone, those who have unlisted numbers, and more recently relevant, those who use mobile&nbsp;phones instead of land lines.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A second barrier to purely random samples is that it may be difficult or impossible to <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">locate</span> some people in the population. &nbsp;For example, people who work unusual hours or who travel a lot may be chosen to be included in the sample, but are not available when you attempt to contact them.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(124,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch&nbsp;this video on stratified random sampling:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/365.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(125,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(44\\)</span>&nbsp;employees at a consulting firm. &nbsp;There are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span>&nbsp;male and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(29\\)</span>&nbsp;female employees. &nbsp;A&nbsp;sample of seven employees is to be taken to obtain their views on the quality of service that&nbsp;they deliver.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate the number of male and female employees that should be included in&nbsp;the sample.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> is the group of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{44}\\)</span>&nbsp;employees at the firm. &nbsp;The <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size is given as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb7\\)</span>. &nbsp;Stratum 1 is the group of female employees and stratum 2 is the group of male employees of the firm.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To draw a <span class=\"PalAb\">proportional sample</span> of size <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb7\\)</span>, the size of the sample that should be taken&nbsp;from each stratum and the proportions are calculated as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 20%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Stratum 1<br>\r\n		sample size</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text{number of observations in stratum 1}}{\\PalAa{\\text{number of observations in population}}} \\times \\PalAb{\\text{size of sample}}\\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{29}{\\PalAa{44}}\\times\\PalAb7\\\\ &amp;=4\\Ndp6 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Stratum 2<br>\r\n		sample size</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text{number of observations in stratum 2}}{\\PalAa{\\text{number of observations in population}}} \\times \\PalAb{\\text{size of sample}}\\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{15}{\\PalAa{44}}\\times\\PalAb7\\\\ &amp;=2\\Ndp4 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Stratum 1<br>\r\n		proportions</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\text{Stratum 1 size}&amp;:\\PalAa{\\text{Population size}}\\\\ 29&amp;:\\PalAa{44}\\\\ \\text{Size of sample in stratum 1}&amp;:\\PalAb{\\text{Size of total sample}}\\\\ 4\\Ndp6&amp;:\\PalAb7 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Stratum&nbsp;2&nbsp;<br>\r\n		proportions</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\text{Stratum 2 size}&amp;:\\PalAa{\\text{Population size}}\\\\ 15&amp;:\\PalAa{44}\\\\ \\text{Size of sample in stratum 2}&amp;:\\PalAb{\\text{Size of total sample}}\\\\ 2\\Ndp4&amp;:\\PalAb7 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">One cannot choose <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\Ndp6\\)</span>&nbsp;females and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Ndp4\\)</span>&nbsp;males. &nbsp;The number <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\Ndp6\\)</span>&nbsp;rounded to the nearest integer is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Ndp4\\)</span> rounded to the nearest integer is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, randomly choose <span class=\"PalAb\">five female employees</span> from stratum 1 and <span class=\"PalAb\">two male employees</span> from stratum 2 to be included in the <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Population</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 45%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Sample</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Stratum 1: females</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Stratum 2: males</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 45%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/374.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 45%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/375.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(126,'Method','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Method</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Systematic sampling</span> starts at a randomly chosen starting point in the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.<br>\r\nThen each subsequent <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{k^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span> element is chosen.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">Step 1</th>\r\n		<td>Define the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">Step 2</th>\r\n		<td>Determine the desired <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">Step 3</th>\r\n		<td>Obtain a list, preferably a randomised list of the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">Step 4</th>\r\n		<td>Determine what <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb k\\)</span>&nbsp;is equal to by dividing the size of the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> by the desired <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">Step 5</th>\r\n		<td>Start at some random place at the top of the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>&nbsp;list.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">Step 6</th>\r\n		<td>Starting at that point, take every&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{k^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">name</span>&nbsp;on the list until the desired <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size is reached.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">Step 7</th>\r\n		<td>If the end of the list is reached before the desired&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span>&nbsp;is reached, go&nbsp;back to the top of the list.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/409.svg\" style=\"width: 650px; height: 400px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">In this case, every <span class=\"PalAb\">third</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">item</span> from the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> is systematically selected.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(127,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose you want a sample of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span> houses from a street with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span>&nbsp;houses.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Systematic sampling</span>&nbsp;starts at a randomly chosen starting point in the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.<br>\r\nThen each subsequent&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{k^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span>&nbsp;element is chosen. &nbsp;Use the following method for systematic sampling to determine the <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 45%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Define the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> is the group of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{64}\\)</span>&nbsp;houses.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine the desired&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span>&nbsp;size.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size is given as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb9\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Obtain a list, preferably a randomised list of the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">population</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The list will be the group of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{64}\\)</span>&nbsp;houses on the street.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To determine the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb k\\)</span>, divide the size of the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> by the <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb k&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{64}}{\\PalAb9}\\\\&amp;=\\PalAb{7\\Ndp11} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So,&nbsp;each&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{7^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">house</span>&nbsp;will be chosen.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 5</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Start at some random place at the top of the <span class=\"PalAa\">population</span> list.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Here we started at <span class=\"PalAb\">house number two</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 6</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Starting at that point, take every&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{k^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">element</span>&nbsp;on the list until the desired <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size is reached.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Starting at the <span class=\"PalAb\">second house</span>, take every <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{7^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">house</span> on the list until the desired <span class=\"PalAb\">sample</span> size of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb9\\)</span> is reached.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/376.svg\" style=\"width: 650px; height: 300px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(128,'Dis- and -advantages','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Dis-&nbsp;and -advantages</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A political candidate wishes to determine the opinions of the voters in his ward. &nbsp;He has a list of voters available. &nbsp;He could, for example, start with voter number&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span>&nbsp;and thereafter choose each tenth voter to complete a questionnaire.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Disadvantage of systematic sampling</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What is the disadvantage of such a method? &nbsp;If the variable being considered is periodic in nature, systematic sampling may lead to misleading results.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The disadvantage is that the system may interact with some hidden pattern in the population, for example every third house along a&nbsp;street might always be the middle one of a terrace of three. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Or if, for example, we are to estimate a shop&#39;s sales and use a&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>-in-<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(7\\)</span> systematic sampling design, it could happen that only sales figures for Saturdays are chosen.<br>\r\nSales will then be overestimated.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Advantage of systematic sampling</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The advantage of systematic sampling is that the sample is spread evenly over the population. &nbsp;It is convenient, especially when the size of the population is not known.<br>\r\nIt is also easier to conduct than a random sample.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(129,'Presentation','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Presentation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the tyre company&nbsp;Radial again.&nbsp; It took a sample of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(80\\)</span>&nbsp;out of the population of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\:600\\)</span>&nbsp;sets of tyres that were sold during the previous six months.<br>\r\nRadial is happy that its sample is representative. &nbsp;The variable in this sample is the number of thousands of kilometres that a customer had driven until one of the four tyres no longer met the minimum safety requirements. &nbsp;In short, the variable is the number of kilometres driven. &nbsp;The sample is given below.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table align=\"center\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:80%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(61\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(19\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(58\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(66\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(72\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(66\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(75\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(42\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(77\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(70\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(56\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(69\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(46\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(59\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(59\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(72\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(46\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(78\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(66\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(75\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(66\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(67\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(98\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(72\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(59\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(88\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(75\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(67\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(55\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(61\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(61\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(77\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(29\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(26\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(62\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(80\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(22\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(61\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(53\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(51\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(82\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(16\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(78\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(34\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(70\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(69\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(83\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(78\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(77\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(62\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(58\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(90\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(86\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(62\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(56\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(58\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(51\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(32\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(86\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(62\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(70\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(67\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(80\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(66\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What do we do now with these numbers?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Unfortunately, we cannot make any deductions about the<br>\r\n		data from the form in which the numbers are presented.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If we could now envisage the data, we would be able to form a better idea of what is going on.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Before we try doing something with these numbers, let us first consider the different types of data one may get.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(130,'Data types','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Data types</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Data are facts, such as values or measurements. &nbsp;Data can be numbers, words, measurements, observations or even just descriptions of things.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are two main groupings of data &mdash; qualitative and quantitative. &nbsp;Qualitative data is characterised by categorical answers such as yes or no, male or female, and so forth. &nbsp;Quantitative data is characterised by numerical values.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/410.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(131,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Qualitative data are data that are not given numerically,&nbsp;for example your favourite colour, place of birth, favourite food and type of car.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Quantitative data are numerical. &nbsp;There are two types of quantitative data:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span>Discrete data</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> can only be </span><span>specific</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> numeric values. &nbsp;They include everything that&nbsp;can be considered as separate units because of their nature, for example&nbsp;shoe size, number of brothers and number of cars in a car park.</span></li>\r\n<li><span>Continuous data</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> can be </span><span>any</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> numerical values, for example&nbsp;height, mass and length.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(132,'Bar graph','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Bar graph</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Now it is time to envisage the data to form a better idea of what is going on. &nbsp;Graphs and charts are great because they communicate information visually.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose Radial also asked their customers in the sample which brand of tyre they had before they switched to the <em>XXX</em>&nbsp;tyres. &nbsp;The results are listed in the table.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note: The variable under investigation is the brand of tyre.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\">Brand of tyre</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Number of customers</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">BF Goodrich</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(7\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Dunlop</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(17\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Continental</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(22\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Good Year</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Bridgestone</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Firestone</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(11\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This information is presented in a bar graph:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"510\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/424.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(133,'Histogram','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Histogram</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the first variable that Radial examined, namely the number of kilometres driven with a set of <em>XXX</em> tyres. &nbsp;The data are grouped into a set of intervals, with each interval of equal length. &nbsp;The results are listed in the table.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note: The variable under investigation is the number of kilometres driven.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 60%;\">Number of thousands of kilometers driven</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Number of customers</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(13\\Ndp5 - 24\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\Ndp5 - 35\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\Ndp5 - 46\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(46\\Ndp5 - 57\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(11\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(57\\Ndp5 - 68\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(25\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(68\\Ndp5 - 79\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(17\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(79\\Ndp5 - 90\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(90\\Ndp5 - 101\\Ndp5\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This information is presented in a histogram:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"510\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/425.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(134,'Comparison','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Comparison</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What is the difference between a bar graph and a histogram?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are two differences; one is in the type of data that is presented and the other is the way in which they are&nbsp;drawn.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Bar Graph</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">Displays categorical data,&nbsp;that is data that fits into categories.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"550\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/426.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">The bars are usually drawn with spaces between them.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\">Histogram</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n		<p><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">Presents continuous data,&nbsp;that is data that represents a measured&nbsp;quantity. &nbsp;The numbers can take on any&nbsp;value in a certain range.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"550\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/427.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n		<p><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255,\r\n 255,\r\n 255);\">The bars are never drawn with spaces between them because there should not be any gaps between the intervals.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(135,'Frequency table','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Frequency table</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Did we miss something in Radial&#39;s case?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">How did we get from