 center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35,5 - 46,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(46,5 - 57,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(11\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(57,5 - 68,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(25\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(68,5 - 79,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(17\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(79,5 - 90,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(90,5 - 101,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</tbody>\r\n		</table>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We identified Radial&#39;s data as quantitative and continuous.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If we could now only envisage the data, we would be able to form a better idea of what is going on.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The histogram is one of the most common ways to visually represent data. &nbsp;A histogram is a graphical presentation of a frequency table.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A frequency table is an organised count of items or values. &nbsp;The <span>raw data</span> are organised into <span>intervals</span> and counted to show how many of the raw data lie in each interval.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">These tables are often useful for discovering basic statistical information about a data set.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(136,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on powers and exponents:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\">\r\n<video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/337.mp4\">&nbsp;</video>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(137,'Add exponents','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Add exponents</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Look at a simple multiplication problem:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa4\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({32}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Another way to write this is:</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa2\\times\\PalAa2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb2\\times\\PalAb2\\times\\PalAb2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({32}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Or it can be written as:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^\\PalAa2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^\\PalAb3\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({32}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Or as:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^\\PalAa2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^\\PalAb3\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^{\\PalAa2+\\PalAb3}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">When we multiply powers that have the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">same</span> base,<br>\r\n		we can add the exponents to get the product.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^\\PalAa m\\times a^\\PalAb n = a^{(\\PalAa m+\\PalAb n)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}2^\\PalAa4\\times2^\\PalAb5&amp;=2^{\\PalAa4+\\PalAb5}\\\\&amp;=2^9\\\\&amp;=512\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(138,'Multiply exponents','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Multiply exponents</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 85%; text-align: left;\">Consider the simple exponential expression:</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(2^\\PalAa3 \\right)^\\PalAb2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 70%; text-align: left;\">Follow the order of operations (BEMDAS). &nbsp;Start by doing what is in the brackets. &nbsp;Raise two to the <span class=\"PalAa\">third power</span>:</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((8)^\\PalAb2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 70%; text-align: left;\">And remove the brackets:</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8^\\PalAb2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 70%; text-align: left;\">Apply the exponent:</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 70%; text-align: left;\">Which can also be written as:</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^6\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 70%; text-align: left;\">Which can furthermore be written as:</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^{\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAb2}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>So, the simplified form of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(2^\\PalAa3 \\right)^\\PalAb2\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span>. &nbsp;And <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span> can be written as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^6\\)</span>, which is the same as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^{\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAb2}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a quicker method:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The power of a power property states that to simplify a power&nbsp;raised<br>\r\n		to a power, multiply the exponents and remove the brackets.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(a^\\PalAa m\\right)^\\PalAb n=a^{(\\PalAa m\\times\\PalAb n)}=a^{\\PalAa m\\PalAb n}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:55','2017-10-11 10:04:55','',NULL),(139,'Product of factors','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Product of factors</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The power of a product property states that a product raised to a&nbsp;power<br>\r\n		&nbsp;is equal to&nbsp;the product of its factors raised to the same power.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa a\\PalAb b)^n=\\PalAa a^n\\PalAb b^n\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You can use the power of a product property to separate factors or to group them together.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 70%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, consider the number:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Which can be written as the product of its factors:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAb4\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Thus the square of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12\\)</span>&nbsp;can be written as:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12^2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa3\\times\\PalAb4)^2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Applying the power of a product property:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12^2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3^2\\times\\PalAb4^2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If we apply the exponents, we find that:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12^2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(144\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3^2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa9\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4^2\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{16}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">And it is true that:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(144\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa9\\times\\PalAb{16}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(140,'Same power','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Same power</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The power of a fraction property allows us to separate or combine the numerator and denominator of a fraction if they are both raised to the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">same power</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left( \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa a}{\\PalAb b}\\right)^n=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa a^n}{\\PalAb b^n}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{xy^2}}{\\PalAb{z^3}}\\right)^4&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa x^4\\left(\\PalAa {y^2}\\right)^4}{\\left(\\PalAb {z^3} \\right)^4}\\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa x^4\\PalAa y^8}{\\PalAb z^{12}} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(141,'Subtract exponents','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Subtract exponents</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">If the numerator and denominator of a fraction are&nbsp;powers<br>\r\n		with the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">same base</span> you subtract the exponents.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{x^\\PalAa a}{x^\\PalAb b}=x^{\\PalAa a-\\PalAb b}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{x^\\PalAb 5}&amp;=x^{\\PalAa1-\\PalAb 5}\\\\ &amp;=x^{-4}\\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{x^4} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(142,'Negative exponent','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Negative exponent</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">If a power has a negative exponent, it is equal to one divided<br>\r\n		by the base raised to the corresponding positive exponent.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}a^{\\PalAb{-n}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb1}{a^\\PalAb n}&amp;&amp;a\\neq0\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Consider:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^{\\PalAb{-1}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb1}{a^\\PalAb 1}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The number <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^{\\PalAb{-1}}\\)</span>&nbsp;is now a symbol for the reciprocal, or multiplicative inverse, of any number <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\times a^{\\PalAb{-1}}=a \\times \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb1}{a}=1\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(143,'Negative powers','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Negative powers</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Using the negative power property, we know that:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x^{\\PalAb{-4}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb1}{x^\\PalAb4}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">From this, we can deduce the following:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">If the numerator and denominator of a fraction have&nbsp;negative<br>\r\n		&nbsp;powers, you make them positive by moving them up or down.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\displaystyle\\frac{x^{\\PalAa{-a}}}{y^{\\PalAb{-b}}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{y^\\PalAb{b}}{x^\\PalAa a}&amp;&amp;x\\neq0 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(144,'0 and 1 exponents','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span> exponents</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span> exponent property</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Any power having a non-zero base and an exponent of <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">zero</span>, is equal to <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">one</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}a^\\PalAa0=\\PalAa1,&amp;&amp;a\\ne0\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Simplify the following expression:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left[\\left(3x^4y^7z^{12} \\right)^5\\left(-5x^9y^3z^4 \\right)^2 \\right]^\\PalAa0\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We do not have to worry about the complicated expression inside the square brackets, because the <span class=\"PalAa\">zero exponent</span> on the outside means that the value of the entire expression is <span class=\"PalAa\">one</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, this&nbsp;expression simplified is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left[\\left(3x^4y^7z^{12} \\right)^5\\left(-5x^9y^3z^4 \\right)^2 \\right]^\\PalAa0=\\PalAa1\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span> exponent property</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Any power with exponent of <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">one</span>, is equal to the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">base</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^\\PalAb1=\\PalAb a\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Simplify the following expression:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left[\\left(3x^4y^7z^{12} \\right)^5\\left(-5x^9y^3z^4 \\right)^2 \\right]^\\PalAb1\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We do not have to worry too much about the complicated expression inside the square brackets, because the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">one exponent</span>&nbsp;on the outside means that the value of the entire expression is the same as the <span class=\"PalAb\">base</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, this&nbsp;expression simplified is:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left[\\left(3x^4y^7z^{12} \\right)^5\\left(-5x^9y^3z^4 \\right)^2 \\right]^\\PalAb1=\\PalAb{\\left(3x^4y^7z^{12} \\right)^5\\left(-5x^9y^3z^4 \\right)^2 }\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(145,'Like terms','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Like terms</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Powers can only be added or subtracted if they<br>\r\n		have the <span class=\"PalAa\">same base</span> and the <span class=\"PalAb\">same exponent</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\PalAa a^\\PalAb n+2\\PalAa a^\\PalAb n=5\\PalAa a^\\PalAb n\\)</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;and &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\PalAa a^\\PalAb n-2\\PalAa a^\\PalAb n=\\PalAa a^\\PalAb n\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 6\\PalAa y^\\PalAb3+2\\PalAa y^\\PalAb3&amp;=8\\PalAa y^\\PalAb3&amp;&amp;\\text{and}\\\\ 6\\PalAa y^\\PalAb3-2\\PalAa y^\\PalAb3&amp;=4\\PalAa y^\\PalAb3\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(146,'Properties summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Properties summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Below is a list of the properties of exponents:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^{\\PalAa m}\\times a^{\\PalAb n}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^{(\\PalAa m+\\PalAb n)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^{\\PalAa m+\\PalAb n}\\)</span></p>\r\n		<