)</span> (five hundredths).&nbsp;</span>Calculate&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span>:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td rowspan=\"3\" style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p style=\"margin-left: 0px;\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/646.JPG\" style=\"width: 288px; height: 208px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{5}\\PalAb{\\%}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">of</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr><!--	<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td> -->\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">is</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa5}{\\PalAb{100}}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr><!--	<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td> -->\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(173,'Case 1','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Case 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( x\\)</span>&nbsp;percent of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\( y\\)</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\( z\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To determine the percentage of a number, we write &quot;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">percent</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&quot; as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}\\times \\PalAb y=\\PalBc z\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({80\\%}\\)</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({300}\\)</span>? &nbsp;In this case <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;equals <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{80}\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span> equals <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{300}\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span> is unknown. &nbsp;So, the answer is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z=\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}\\times \\PalAb y=\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{80}{100}}\\times \\PalAb {300}=\\PalBc{240}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A salesman receives a commission that is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;of his sales. &nbsp;If his sales for the&nbsp;month total <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur320\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>, what is his commission? &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, we need to calculate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;of his sales of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur320\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;to determine his commission.<br>\r\nIn this case&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{2\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}}\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{320\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&nbsp;is the unknown commission.<br>\r\nHis&nbsp;commission&nbsp;is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalBc z&amp;=\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}\\times \\PalAb y\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{2\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}}{100}}\\times \\PalAb {320\\Tsp000}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{2\\Ndp5}{100}}\\times \\PalAb {320\\Tsp000}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{0\\Ndp025}\\times \\PalAb {320\\Tsp000}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalBc{8\\Tsp000}\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">His commission is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur8\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What we basically did was to change the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\frac{1}{2}\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;percentage to a decimal:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{2\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}}{100}}=\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{2\\Ndp5}{100}}=\\PalAa{0\\Ndp025}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">And then multiply the decimal&nbsp;with his total sales of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur320\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;to determine his commission:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0\\Ndp025}\\times\\PalAb{320\\Tsp000}=\\PalBc{8\\Tsp000}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(174,'Case 2','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Case 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;percent of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( y\\)</span><span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(z\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What percentage is one number of another? &nbsp;To determine one number as the percentage of another number, we write &quot;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">percent</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&quot; as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}\\times \\PalAb y=\\PalBc z\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And solve for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}\\times \\PalAb y&amp;=\\PalBc z\\\\ \\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc z}{ \\PalAb y}\\\\ \\PalAa{x}&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc z}{ \\PalAb y}\\times \\PalAa{100} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>What percent is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({44}\\)</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({11}\\)</span>? &nbsp;In this case&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{44}\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{11}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;is unknown. &nbsp;So, the answer is calculated as:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{x}&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc z}{ \\PalAb y}\\times \\PalAa{100} \\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc {15}}{ \\PalAb {44}}\\times \\PalAa{100}\\\\ &amp;=0\\Ndp625\\times\\PalAa{100}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{62\\Ndp5\\%} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Pumi invited <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\)</span> people to his birthday party. &nbsp;Only <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span> people showed up.<br>\r\nCalculate the percentage of people that showed up.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, we need to calculate the number of people&nbsp;that showed up&nbsp;as a percentage of the total number invited.&nbsp; In this case&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{24}\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{15}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;is the unknown percentage. &nbsp;The&nbsp;percentage is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa x&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc z}{ \\PalAb y}\\times \\PalAa{100} \\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc {15}}{ \\PalAb {24}}\\times \\PalAa{100}\\\\ &amp;=0\\Ndp625\\times \\PalAa{100}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{62\\Ndp5} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The percentage of people that showed up at Pumi&#39;s birthday party is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(62\\Ndp5\\%\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Alternatively, we&nbsp;can say that the ratio that showed up is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15:24\\)</span> which reduces to:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{15}{24}:\\displaystyle\\frac{24}{24}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp625:1\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Multiplying by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span> gives <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(62\\Ndp5\\%\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(175,'Case 3','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Case 3</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;percent of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( y\\)</span><span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(z\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The percentage and final number is known. &nbsp;What is the base or initial number? &nbsp;To determine the base number, we write &quot;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">percent</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&quot; as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}\\times \\PalAb y=\\PalBc z\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">And solve for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{100}}\\times \\PalAb y&amp;=\\PalBc z\\\\ \\PalAb y&amp;=\\PalBc z\\times \\PalAa{\\displaystyle\\frac{100}{x}}\\\\ \\PalAb y&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc z}{\\PalAa x}\\times \\PalAa{100} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({30\\%}\\)</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;what number? &nbsp;In this case&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{30}\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{60}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;is unknown. &nbsp;So, the answer can be&nbsp;calculated as:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc z}{\\PalAa x}\\times \\PalAa{100} =\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc{60}}{\\PalAa{30}}\\times \\PalAa{100}=2\\times{100}=\\PalAb{200}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A DVD player is offered as a special for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp600\\Cdp00\\)</span> and it states that this is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(75\\%\\)</span> of the usual price. &nbsp;What was the price before the discount?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, we need to calculate&nbsp;the usual price of the DVD player if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(75\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;of this price is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp600\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;In this case&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{75}\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc z\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{3\\Tsp600}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>&nbsp;is the unknown price. &nbsp;The price can be&nbsp;calculated using the formula as above, or by dividing with the percentage written as a decimal number.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Writing the percentage as a decimal number gives <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0\\Ndp75}\\)</span>. &nbsp;Divide <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{3\\Tsp600}\\)</span> by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0\\Ndp75}\\)</span>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa{75\\%}\\text{ of the} \\PalAb{\\text{ price}}&amp;=\\PalBc{\\Cur3600\\Cdp00}\\\\ \\PalAa{0\\Ndp75}\\times\\PalAb{\\text{ price}}&amp;=\\PalBc{\\Cur3600\\Cdp00}\\\\ \\PalAb{\\text{ price}}&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc{\\Cur3600\\Cdp00}}{\\PalAa{0\\Ndp75}}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAb{\\Cur4\\Tsp800\\Cdp00} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The normal price is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur4\\Tsp800\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To check the answer, calculate the ratio of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\Tsp600:4\\Tsp800\\)</span> which reduces to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\Ndp75:1\\)</span>.<br>\r\nMultiplying by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span> gives <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(75\\%\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(176,'% Change','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;Change</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Percentage change is calculated as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\%\\text{ change}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text{change}}{\\text{original}}\\times 100\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The change can be an increase or a decrease.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Mandile buys a handbag on a sale. &nbsp;It is marked down from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur780\\Cdp00\\)</span> to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur655\\Cdp20\\)</span>.<br>\r\nCalculate the percentage decrease in price on the handbag.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">original price</span> was <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur780\\Cdp00}\\)</span> and the <span class=\"PalBc\">new price</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{\\Cur655\\Cdp20}\\)</span>. &nbsp;The <span class=\"PalAa\">decrease</span> in price is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{\\text{decrease}}&amp;=\\PalAb{\\text{original price}}-\\PalBc{\\text{new price}}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAb{\\Cur780\\Cdp00}-\\PalBc{\\Cur655\\Cdp20}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{\\Cur124\\Cdp80} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">decrease</span>&nbsp;in price is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur124\\Cdp80}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">percentage</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">decrease</span>&nbsp;in price is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa{\\%\\text{ decrease}}&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{decrease}}}{\\PalAb{\\text{original}}}\\times 100\\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\Cur124\\Cdp80}}{\\PalAb{\\Cur780\\Cdp00}}\\times 100\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{16\\%} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The handbag was marked down <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(16\\%\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(177,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on permutations and ways&nbsp;of ordering objects:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/359.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(178,'Video 1','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the first part of this video on permutations versus combinations:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/360.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(179,'Video 2','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the second part of this video on permutations versus combinations:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/361.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(180,'Video - Frequency table','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on how to construct a&nbsp;frequency table:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/366.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(181,'Video - Interval size','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on frequency tables and interval size:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/367.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(182,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on calculating the mean of quantitative data:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/368.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(183,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on the distribution of data:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/369.mp4 \" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(184,'Video 1','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on the standard deviation:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/370.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(185,'Video 2 - Scores','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video 2 - Scores</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on calculating the standard deviation:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\">\r\n<video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/371.mp4\" width=\"650\">&nbsp;</video>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(186,'Signs','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Signs</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are signs in Mathematics&nbsp;without which we cannot live.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 12%; vertical-align: top;\"><span>Sign</span></th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align: left; width: 65%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">In a statement...</span></th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 10%; vertical-align: top;\"><span>Example</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left; width: 65%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We use the <span class=\"PalBc\">equal</span>&nbsp;sign if the two values are equal.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\times2\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc\\ne\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left; width: 65%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We use the <span class=\"PalBc\">not equal to</span>&nbsp;sign if two values are definitely not equal.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc\\ne\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left; width: 65%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We use a<span class=\"PalAa\"> less than</span>&nbsp;sign if the value on the left is smaller than the one on the right.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left; width: 65%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">we use a <span class=\"PalAb\">greater than</span>&nbsp;sign if the value on the left is bigger than the one on the right.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\le\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left; width: 65%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">less than or equal to</span>&nbsp;sign is used if the value on the left is less than or equal the one on the right. &nbsp;In the example, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> can be any value <span class=\"PalAa\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>. &nbsp;It can also be <span class=\"PalAa\">equal to</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa\\le\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\ge\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left; width: 65%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">greater than or equal to</span>&nbsp;sign is used if the value on the left is bigger than or equal the one on the right. &nbsp;In the example,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span> can be any value <span class=\"PalAb\">bigger than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span>. &nbsp;It can also be <span class=\"PalAb\">equal to</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\ge\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">less than</span>&nbsp;sign and the <span class=\"PalAb\">greater than</span>&nbsp;sign look like a V&nbsp;on its side, does it not?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To remember which way around the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&lt;\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&gt;\\)</span> signs go, just remember:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb{\\text{BIG}}&amp;\\PalAb&gt;\\PalAa{\\text{small}}\\\\ \\PalAa{\\text{small}}&amp;\\PalAa&lt;\\PalAb{\\text{BIG}} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">small&nbsp;end</span> always points to the <span class=\"PalAa\">smaller</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">number,</span> like this:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/401.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(187,'Histogram','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Histogram</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Now we can graphically represent the frequency table by drawing the interval lengths on a horizontal axis and the frequencies on a vertical axis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/419.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">(Notice that the horizontal axis starts at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span> and that the zigzag line is there to break the line in order to prevent a large space from appearing to the left of the actual graph.)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(188,'Repetition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Repetition</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the lock below which uses three digits for its code:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/400.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose it has a code of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(461\\)</span>. &nbsp;Order is important because <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(614\\)</span> differs from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(461\\)</span> and the lock will not open. &nbsp;It has to be <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4-6-1\\)</span>. &nbsp;Therefore, we can say the lock uses a permutation of numbers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For a lock like this, you can use <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(222\\)</span> as a code as well. &nbsp;Therefore, we say that repetition is allowed. &nbsp;Once the two is used, you can use it again.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For permutations with repetition:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">When you have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> things to choose from and repetition is allowed,<br>\r\n		you have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> choices each time.<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		When choosing <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span> of them, the number of permutations is:<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n \\times \\PalBc n \\times \\ldots \\times\\PalBc n \\)</span>&nbsp;(<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span>&nbsp;times)<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		It is easier to write it&nbsp;by using an exponent of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span>&nbsp;as follows:<br>\r\n		Write&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n \\times \\PalBc n \\times \\ldots \\times\\PalBc n \\)</span>&nbsp;<span>(</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span><span>&nbsp;times) as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n^\\PalAb r\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In other words, there are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> possibilities for the first choice, then&nbsp;there are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> possibilities for the second choice, and so on, multiplying each time.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the lock above again. &nbsp;For each of the <span class=\"PalAb\">three</span> positions in the code, we can choose from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{10}\\)</span> different digits, namely&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0,1,\\ldots9\\)</span>. &nbsp;Thus there are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{10}\\times\\PalBc{10}\\times\\PalBc{10}=\\PalBc{10}^\\PalAb3=1\\Tsp000\\)</span>&nbsp;permutations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In this case <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> (the number of things to choose from) is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{10}\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span> (the number of times you choose a digit) equals <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb3\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We see <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">repetition</span> is allowed and <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">order</span> matters.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(189,'Lengths in SI system','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Lengths in SI system</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The standard unit for length is the metre.<br>\r\n		The SI abbreviation for metre is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore we write <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span> metres as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\text{m}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"6\" style=\"width: 20%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Lengths in the SI system:</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>&nbsp;millimetre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{mm})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>&nbsp;centimetre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{cm})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>&nbsp;centimetre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{cm})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>&nbsp;decimetre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{dm})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>&nbsp;decimetre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{dm})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>&nbsp;metre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{m})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>&nbsp;metre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{m})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>&nbsp;decametre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{dam})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>&nbsp;decametre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{dam})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>&nbsp;hectometre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{hm})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>&nbsp;hectometre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{hm})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>&nbsp;kilometre</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{km})\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We normally use <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{km}\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{mm}\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\:\\text{km}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 9%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\:\\text{m}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\:\\text{m}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 9%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\:\\text{cm}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\:\\text{mm}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\:\\text{cm}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 9%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\:\\text{mm}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the textile industry where, among other things, clothes are manufactured, centimetres are used for technical reasons. &nbsp;Due to this all body lengths are measured in centimetres.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/406.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 110px;\"></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This ruler measures in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This ruler measures in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{mm}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A metre is about the length of a person&#39;s stride. &nbsp;You could measure longer things like a room or&nbsp;a garden using metres.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Distance is another word for length and it is convention that distances between places are measured in kilometres.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(190,'In practice','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">In practice</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Perimeter</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The perimeter is the length of the outline of a shape.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To find the perimeter of a rectangle or square you have to add the lengths of all the four sides. &nbsp;In this case, illustrated below,&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(l\\)</span>&nbsp;is the length of the rectangle, while&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(w\\)</span>&nbsp;is the width.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The perimeter&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>&nbsp;is:</p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} P&amp;=l+l+w+w\\\\ &amp;=2l+2w \\\\ &amp;=2(l+w) \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/407.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 250px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Scale drawings</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A map cannot be of the same size as the area it represents. &nbsp;So, the measurements are scaled down to make the map of a size that can be conveniently used by users such as motorists, cyclists and bushwalkers. &nbsp;A scale drawing of a building (or bridge) has the same shape as the real building (or bridge) that it represents, but a different size.<br>\r\nBuilders use scaled drawings to make buildings and bridges.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A ratio is used in scale drawings of maps and buildings. &nbsp;The ratios are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\text{scale of drawing}&amp;=\\PalAa{\\text{drawing length}}:\\PalAb{\\text{actual length}}\\\\ \\text{map scale}&amp;=\\PalAa{\\text{map distance}}:\\PalAb{\\text{actual distance}} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A scale is usually expressed in one of two ways:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">using units as in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\text{cm}\\)</span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\text{km}\\)</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">without explicitly mentioning units as in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1:100\\Tsp000\\)</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A scale of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1:\\PalAb{100\\Tsp000}\\)</span> means that the <span class=\"PalAb\">real distance</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{100\\Tsp000}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">times</span> the length of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">unit</span> on the <span class=\"PalAa\">map or drawing</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A particular map shows a scale of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1:\\PalAb{5\\Tsp000}\\)</span>. &nbsp;What is the <span class=\"PalAb\">actual distance</span> in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{km}}\\)</span> if the <span class=\"PalAa\">map distance</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{8\\:\\text{cm}}\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The scale indicates that <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{cm}}\\)</span> on the <span class=\"PalAa\">map </span>represents a <span class=\"PalAb\">real distance</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{5\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}}\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 65%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Scale</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 10%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 2%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(:\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{5\\Tsp000}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Multiply both sides with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\times8\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(:\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{5\\Tsp000}\\times8\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa8\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(:\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{40\\Tsp000}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The actual distance is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{40\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To convert <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}\\)</span> to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{km}\\)</span>, divide by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\Tsp000\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb{40\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}}}{100\\Tsp000}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{0\\Ndp40\\:{\\text{km}}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{40\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}}\\)</span> is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{0\\Ndp40\\:{\\text{km}}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">actual distance</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{0\\Ndp40\\:{\\text{km}}}\\)</span>&nbsp;if the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">map distance</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{8\\:\\text{cm}}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(191,'Percentages','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Percentages</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Another way to present the frequencies is with percentages. &nbsp;Because relative frequencies have decimals, it is easier to interpret percentages. &nbsp;If we use percentages instead of relative frequencies we can work with whole numbers. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A percentage is basically a proportion, except we multiply by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>&nbsp;and we call that &quot;percent&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The proportion of the first interval converted to a percentage is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0,05 \\times 100 = 5 \\%\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(192,'Convert large to small','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Convert large to small</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can describe&nbsp;length as being one dimensional and area as two dimensional.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/408.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">How would you write square kilometres? &nbsp;Easy, we write it as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{km}^2\\)</span>.&nbsp;&nbsp;How do we convert units of area? &nbsp;The process involves a little more thinking.<br>\r\nWhen converting from a large unit <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{m})\\)</span> to a smaller unit <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{cm})\\)</span> the number of units will increase.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>Convert&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{cm}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}}=\\:\\PalAb{100\\:\\text{cm}})\\)</span><span>:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa1&amp;=\\PalAa1&amp;&amp;(\\PalAa{\\text{m}} \\times \\PalAa{\\text{m}}=\\PalAa{\\text{m}^2} )\\\\ \\PalAb{100}\\times\\PalAb{100}&amp;=\\PalAb{10\\Tsp000}&amp;&amp;(\\PalAb{\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAb{\\text{cm}}=\\PalAb{\\text{cm}^2} ) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>Therefore&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}^2}\\)</span></span><span>.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span s=\"\">Convert&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{mm}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}}=\\:\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000\\:\\text{mm}})\\)</span><span>:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa1&amp;=\\PalAa1&amp;&amp;(\\PalAa{\\text{m}} \\times \\PalAa{\\text{m}}=\\PalAa{\\text{m}^2} )\\\\ \\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\times\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}&amp;=\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000\\Tsp000}&amp;&amp;(\\PalAb{\\text{mm}} \\times \\PalAb{\\text{mm}}=\\PalAb{\\text{mm}^2} ) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span><span>Therefore&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\:\\text{mm}^2}\\)</span></span><span>&nbsp;or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10^6\\:\\text{mm}^2}\\)</span>.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>Convert&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{cm}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{mm}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{cm}}=\\:\\PalAb{10\\:\\text{mm}})\\)</span><span>:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa1&amp;=\\PalAa1&amp;&amp;(\\PalAa{\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAa{\\text{cm}}=\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^2} )\\\\ \\PalAb{10}\\times\\PalAb{10}&amp;=\\PalAb{100}&amp;&amp;(\\PalAb{\\text{mm}} \\times \\PalAb{\\text{mm}}=\\PalAb{\\text{mm}^2} ) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span><span>Therefore&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{cm}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{100\\:\\text{mm}^2}\\)</span></span><span>.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>Convert&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{km}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{cm}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{km}}=\\PalAb{100\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}}=\\PalAb{10^5\\:\\text{cm}})\\)</span><span>:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa1&amp;=\\PalAa1&amp;&amp;(\\PalAa{\\text{km}} \\times \\PalAa{\\text{km}}=\\PalAa{\\text{km}^2} )\\\\ \\PalAb{10^5}\\times\\PalAb{10^5}&amp;=\\PalAb{10^{10}}&amp;&amp;(\\PalAb{\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAb{\\text{cm}}=\\PalAb{\\text{cm}^2} ) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span><span>Therefore&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{km}^2}\\)</span><span s=\"\">&nbsp;equals&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10^{10}\\:\\text{cm}^2}\\)</span></span><span>.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>Convert&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{km}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{m}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{km}}=\\:\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000\\:\\text{m}})\\)</span><span>:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa1\\times\\PalAa1&amp;=\\PalAa1&amp;&amp;(\\PalAa{\\text{km}} \\times \\PalAa{\\text{km}}=\\PalAa{\\text{km}^2} )\\\\ \\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\times\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}&amp;=\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000\\Tsp000}&amp;&amp;(\\PalAb{\\text{m}} \\times \\PalAb{\\text{m}}=\\PalAb{\\text{m}^2} ) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span><span>Therefore&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\:\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{km}^2}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\:\\text{m}^2}\\)</span></span><span>&nbsp;or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10^6\\:\\text{m}^2}\\)</span>.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Notice that the use of the exponential form for&nbsp;writing large numbers improves readability:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\Tsp000=10^\\PalAb6\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\Tsp000=10^\\PalAb{10}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Conversion table</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\"><span class=\"BodyText\">From large unit</span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\"><span class=\"BodyText\">To smaller unit</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 19%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{km}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\:10^6\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 19%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{km}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\:10^{10}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 19%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\:10\\Tsp000\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 19%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\:10^6\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{mm}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 19%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\:100\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{mm}^2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:56','2017-10-11 10:04:56','',NULL),(193,'Three dimensions','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Three dimensions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can&nbsp;describe&nbsp;length as being one dimensional and area as two dimensional. &nbsp;But for an object to take up space in the real world, it needs a third dimension. &nbsp;Volume is a way of measuring three dimensional spaces.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/402.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The standard way to measure liquid is as volume. &nbsp;Volume can be in litres.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Questions such as&nbsp;&quot;How much water is in that cup, that aquarium, or that pool?&quot; are examples of volume problems. &nbsp;Volume is the space an item or substance occupies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We generally measure liquids in litres <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\ell)\\)</span> or millilitres <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{m}\\ell)\\)</span>. &nbsp;And for solids we generally measure volume in cubic metres <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{m}^3)\\)</span> or cubic centimetres <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{cm}^3)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The area&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(V\\)</span>&nbsp;is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}V&amp;=l\\times w\\times h\\\\ &amp;=lwh \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/403.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The SI unit for volume is the cubic metre or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}^3\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The volume of a cube where each side is one metre in length is one cubic metre. &nbsp;A cube with a volume of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}^3}\\)</span> can hold a <span class=\"PalAa\">thousand litres</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}^3}=\\PalAa{1\\Tsp000\\:\\ell}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Actual size of cube with&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{m}^3}\\)</span>&nbsp;volume:</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/404.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/405.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(194,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If the mayor is asked to provide a single value which best describes the income level of the city, he or she would answer with a measure of central tendency.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The mean (or average) is the most popular and well known measure of central tendency. &nbsp;It can be used with both discrete and continuous data.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The mean is equal to the sum of all the values in the data set<br>\r\n		&nbsp;divided by the number of values in the data set.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is called the arithmetic mean. &nbsp;To calculate the arithmetic mean, sum the values and divide by their quantity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The first three examples illustrated below show higher values dragging the mean upward. &nbsp;The final example piles on some low values to drag the mean downward.<br>\r\nWhat you see is characteristic of the arithmetic mean. &nbsp;Any value added above or below the mean will move the mean in the direction of the new value. The move may be slight, or it may be large, but it will be non-zero.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/382.svg\" style=\"width: 650px; height: 400px;\"></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(195,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The mode <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((Mo)\\)</span> of a data set is that value which occurs most often.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A survey of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14\\)</span> employees&#39; performance scores out of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span> had these results, ordered from lowest to highest:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(33\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(33\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(42\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us look at the data in a different way:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/379.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">mode</span> of the data is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span> because <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span> occurs <span class=\"PalAb\">three times</span>, which&nbsp;is more than any other score.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(196,'Example - None','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example - None</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A data set may have no mode.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A survey of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14\\)</span>&nbsp;employees&#39; performance scores out of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span>&nbsp;had these results, ordered from lowest to highest:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(32\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(33\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(34\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(41\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(42\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(43\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(44\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us look at the data in a different way:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/380.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">No value occurs more than any other value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(197,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Another way of representing data is a pie chart. &nbsp;Look at this record of traffic travelling down a particular road.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Traffic survey 31 January 2012</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Type of vehicle</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Number of vehicles</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Cars&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(140\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Motorbikes&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(70\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Vans&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(55\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Buses&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Total Vehicles</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(270\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To draw a pie chart, we need to represent each part of the data as a proportion of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(360\\)</span>,&nbsp;because there are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(360\\)</span>degrees in a circle.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate the degrees that each type of vehicle will take up. &nbsp;For example, if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{55}\\)</span> out of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(270\\)</span> vehicles are <span>vans</span>, we will represent this on the circle as a&nbsp;segment with an angle of:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc{55}}{270} \\times360=\\PalBc{73}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{73}\\)</span>&nbsp;degrees out of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(360\\)</span>, will be represented by the <span>vans</span>. &nbsp;This will give the following results:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Traffic survey 31 January 2012</h3>\r\n\r\n<table align=\"center\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Type of vehicle</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align: center;\">Number of vehicles</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align: center;\">Calculation</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align: center;\">Degrees of a crircle</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Cars</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{140}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{140}}{270} \\times 360\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{187}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Motorbikes</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{70}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb{70}}{270} \\times 360\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{93}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Vans</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{55}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc{55}}{270} \\times 360\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{73}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Buses</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{5}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBb{5}}{270} \\times 360\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{7}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Before you draw the pie chart, remember to check that the angles which you have calculated add&nbsp;up to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(360\\)</span>degrees. &nbsp;This data set is represented in the pie chart below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/420.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(198,'Example - Sensitivity','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example - Sensitivity</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The mode is not sensitive to extreme scores.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Compare the modes of the following two similar&nbsp;ordered data sets. &nbsp;The two sets are the same, except for the highest score in each case. &nbsp;In&nbsp;the first set the highest score is not extreme, but in the second it is&nbsp;extreme.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the first instance, a&nbsp;survey of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14\\)</span>&nbsp;employees&#39; performance scores out of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span>&nbsp;gave&nbsp;the following&nbsp;results, ordered from lowest to highest, with&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({45}\\)</span>&nbsp;as&nbsp;the highest score:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(33\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(33\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(42\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/379.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">mode</span>&nbsp;of the data is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span>&nbsp;because&nbsp;it&nbsp;occurs&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">three times</span>, which&nbsp;is more than any other score.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the second&nbsp;instance, a&nbsp;survey of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14\\)</span>&nbsp;employees&#39; performance scores out of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span><br>\r\ngave&nbsp;the following&nbsp;results, ordered from lowest to highest, with the highest score of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{50}\\)</span>&nbsp;as an&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">extreme score</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(33\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(33\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(42\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{50}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/381.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">mode</span>&nbsp;of the data is still&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In any case, the mode is a quick and dirty measure of central tendency.<br>\r\nQuick, because it is easily and quickly computed. &nbsp;Dirty, because it is not very useful,&nbsp;meaning it does not give much information about the data.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It may happen that there is no value that occurs more than any other value, or that there is more than one value with the same maximum number of occurrences. &nbsp;The only thing counting in the mode&#39;s favour is that it is easy to understand.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(199,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">In a data set, the cumulative frequency for a value is the total number&nbsp;of scores that are less than or equal to that value.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The charts below illustrate the difference between frequency and cumulative frequency. &nbsp;Both charts show scores for a test administered to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(300\\)</span>&nbsp;students.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"line-height:1.5;width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\">Graphical presentation of frequency table&nbsp;(Histogram)</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Cumulative frequency chart</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 45%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Column height shows frequency &ndash;&nbsp;the number of students in each test score grouping.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 45%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Column height shows cumulative frequency &ndash;&nbsp;the number of students up to and including each test score.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\)</span>&nbsp;students received a test score between <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(51\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(25\\)</span> students received a test score of at most <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span>. &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(49\\)</span> students received a score of at most <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span>.&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(109\\)</span>&nbsp;students received a score of at most <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(70\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/606.jpg\" style=\"width: 80%; height: 80%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/607.jpg\" style=\"width: 90%; height: 90%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The total frequencies of all intervals less than the upper class boundary of a specified interval is&nbsp;called the cumulative frequency of that interval.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top; width: 45%;\">\r\n		<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n		<thead>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<th scope=\"col\"><br>\r\n				Interval</th>\r\n				<th scope=\"col\"><br>\r\n				Frequency</th>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</thead>\r\n		<tbody>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40,5 - 50,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(25\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50,5 - 60,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60,5 - 70,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(70,5 - 80,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(92\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(80,5 - 90,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(64\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(90,5 - 100,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(34\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</tbody>\r\n		</table>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n		<thead>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<th scope=\"col\">Upper<br>\r\n				limit</th>\r\n				<th scope=\"col\">Cumulative<br>\r\n				frequency</th>\r\n				<th scope=\"col\">Cumulative means<br>\r\n				&quot;added up&quot;</th>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</thead>\r\n		<tbody>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt; 50,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(25\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt; 60,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(49\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((25 + 24 = 49)\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt; 70,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(109\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((25 + 24 + 60 = 109)\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt; 80,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(201\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((25 + 24 + 60 + 92 = 201)\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt; 90,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(265\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((25 + 24 + 60 + 92 + 64 = 265)\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt; 100,5\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(300\\)</span></td>\r\n				<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((25 + 24 + 60 + 92 + 64 + 35 = 300)\\)</span></td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</tbody>\r\n		</table>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(200,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Problems can occur when we work with a measure of central tendency only.<br>\r\nWithout knowing something about how data is spread out, measures of central tendency may be misleading.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, a residential street, say&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">Street A</span>,&nbsp;with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({20}\\)</span> homes on it having a mean value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur950\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> with little variation from the mean, would be very different from a street, say&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">Street B</span>, with the same mean home value, but with three homes having a value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;and the other <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(17\\)</span> clustered around <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Measures of dispersion provide a more complete picture.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\"><span>Street A</span></th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\"><span>Street B</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 49%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/383.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{20}\\)</span>&nbsp;homes&nbsp;at around&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur950\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{20}\\times\\PalAa{\\Cur950\\Tsp000\\Cdp00} = \\PalAa{\\Cur19\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/384.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{17}\\)</span>&nbsp;homes at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{17}\\times\\PalAb{\\Cur500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00} = \\PalAb{\\Cur8\\Tsp500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/385.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb3\\)</span>&nbsp;homes&nbsp;at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur3\\Tsp500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{3}\\times\\PalAb{\\Cur3\\Tsp500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00} = \\PalAb{\\Cur10\\Tsp500\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 49%; vertical-align: bottom;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Total value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{20}\\)</span>&nbsp;homes&nbsp;is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur19\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{8\\Tsp500\\Tsp000}+\\PalAb{10\\Tsp500\\Tsp000}= \\PalAb{19\\Tsp000\\Tsp000}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p>Total value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{20}\\)</span>&nbsp;ho<span>mes&nbsp;is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur19\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span><span>.</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 49%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalAa{\\Cur19\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\div\\PalAa{20}=\\PalAa{\\Cur950\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Mean</span><span>&nbsp;value of homes&nbsp;is&nbsp;<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur950\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalAb{\\Cur19\\Tsp000\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\div\\PalAb{20}=\\PalAb{\\Cur950\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Mean</span><span>&nbsp;value of&nbsp;homes&nbsp;is&nbsp;<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur950\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span><span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(201,'Range','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Range</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A measure of location, such as the mean or the median, only describes the centre of the data. &nbsp;It is valuable from that standpoint, but it does not tell us anything about the spread of the data.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The arithmetic mean, even though it uses all the values in the data set, does not give much information about what the data set really looks like.<br>\r\nWhat we also need is information on the spread of the data around the mean.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The range is the simplest measure of spread. &nbsp;It is the difference between the largest and the smallest values in the data set.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{range}=\\text{largest value}-\\text{smallest value}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This measure of spread does not take into account anything about the distribution of the data other than the extremes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/396.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/397.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">range</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15-10=\\PalAa5\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">range</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15-10=\\PalAb5\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The range ignores how the data is distributed.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(202,'Variance - Scores','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Variance - Scores</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Compare the standard deviations for the scores of two classes, <span class=\"PalAa\">A</span> and<span class=\"PalAb\">&nbsp;B</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 50%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Class A</span></td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Class B</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/399.jpg\" style=\"height: 90%; width: 90%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/398.jpg\" style=\"width: 90%; height: 90%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 28%; text-align: right;\">Mean: &nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\overline{x}=\\PalAa{15\\Ndp00}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 28%; text-align: right;\">Mean: &nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\overline{x}=\\PalAb{15\\Ndp00}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: right;\">Standard deviation: &nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=\\PalAa{1\\Ndp15}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">Standard deviation: &nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=\\PalAb{2\\Ndp71}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Although the mean scores of the two classes are&nbsp;the same, the scores of <span class=\"PalAb\">Class B</span>&nbsp;are clearly <span class=\"PalAb\">more spread out</span>. The standard deviations give the teacher some idea about the spread of the marks of these two classes. Although the two classes have the same average scores, the teacher cannot conclude that the levels of understanding are&nbsp;the same for the two classes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is even more visible when we consider the variance of each&nbsp;data set.<br>\r\nThe variance is simply the square of the standard deviation and the standard deviation is the positive square root of the variance.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Variance is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S^2\\)</span><br>\r\n		Standard deviation is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\sqrt{S^2}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Variance for scores of <span class=\"PalAa\">Class A</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Variance for scores of <span class=\"PalAb\">Class B</span></span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S^2=\\PalAa{1\\Ndp15}^2=\\PalAa{1\\Ndp32}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S^2=\\PalAb{2\\Ndp71}^2=\\PalAb{7\\Ndp34}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(203,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Some presentations incorporate&nbsp;all the original data observed, while others only use certain statistics.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A&nbsp;very useful presentation which does not use all the data, is the box-and-whiskers diagram. &nbsp;It shows only certain statistics rather than all the data. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The box-and-whiskers diagram&nbsp;uses only five observations from a data set, namely:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">smallest value</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">first quartile</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">median</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalBc\">third quartile</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalBc\">largest value</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Min}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Q_1}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{Me}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Q_3}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Max}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the diagram below&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAb\">median</span>, <span class=\"PalAa\">first quartile</span> and <span class=\"PalBc\">third quartile</span> gives the <span class=\"PalAb\">box</span> portion. &nbsp;It shows the range of the <span class=\"PalAb\">middle</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{50\\%}\\)</span> of the data values:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/386.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This plot allows people to explore the data and to draw informal conclusions when two or more variables are present. &nbsp;Compared to a normal distribution, the box aligns with the middle portion of the data.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/387.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(204,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Draw a box-and-whiskers diagram for the data below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Order the data&nbsp;in ascending order. &nbsp;There are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{11}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">values</span> in the data set, so <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{n}=\\PalAa{11}\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1^{\\text{st}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{2^{\\text{nd}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{3^{\\text{rd}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{4^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{5^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{6^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{7^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{8^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{9^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{11^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Then, determine the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(Q_1\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(Me\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(Q_3\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p>For&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({Q_1}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Q_1}\\)</span>&nbsp;is the value of the&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\frac{1}{4}(\\PalAa n+1)^{\\text{th}}}\\\\\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\frac{1}{4}(\\PalAa {11}+1)\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\frac{12}{4}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalAa{3^{\\text{rd}}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p>observation.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>So,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Q_1}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalAa4\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p>For <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(Me\\text{/}Q_2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{Me\\text{/}Q_2}\\)</span> is the value of the</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\frac{1}{2}(\\PalAa n+1)^{\\text{th}}}\\\\\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\frac{1}{2}(\\PalAa {11}+1)\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\frac{12}{2}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalAb{6^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p>observation.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>So,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{Me}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalAb 8\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p>For&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(Q_3\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Q_3}\\)</span>&nbsp;is the value of the</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{\\frac{3}{4}(\\PalAa n+1)^{\\text{th}}}\\\\\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\frac{3}{4}(\\PalAa {11}+1)\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\frac{36}{4}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalBc{9^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p>observation.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>So,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Q_3}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalBc{10}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>The positions of these values can be illustrated in the ordered data set as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({1^{\\text{st}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({2^{\\text{nd}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{3^{\\text{rd}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({4^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({5^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{6^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({7^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({8^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{9^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({10^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({11^{\\text{th}}}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa4\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{10}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Q_1}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{Me}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Q_3}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>The box-and-whiskers diagram is given below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/388.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(205,'Interpretation','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Interpretation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/389.jpg\" style=\"width: 80%;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When graphed with real data, box-and-whiskers diagrams can take on many different looks. &nbsp;How the diagram looks depends on the distribution of the underlying data.<br>\r\nExceptionally high and low maximums and minimums can stretch out the whiskers.<br>\r\nDiagram C in the figure above is an example of a very low minimum and diagram D is an example of a very high maximum.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Depending on the data distribution, the box part can be stretched or compressed.<br>\r\nThis is called the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">spread</span>&nbsp;and indicates whether the middle <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({50\\%}\\)</span> of the data is spread out over a large range of values or compressed over a small range of values. &nbsp;The corresponding <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">bell curve</span>&nbsp;for a compressed box diagram would have a sharper and higher peak, while a stretched out box diagram would have a rounder and lower peak.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" height=\"321\" width=\"800\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Compressed box diagram<br>\r\n		gives sharper, higher peak:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Stretched out&nbsp;</span><span>box diagram</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"BodyText\">gives rounder, lower&nbsp;</span><span>peak:</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/390.svg\" style=\"width: 100%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/391.svg\" style=\"width: 100%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/392.svg\" style=\"width: 100%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/393.svg\" style=\"width: 100%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The box can also lie at various positions between the whiskers. This is called the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">skewness</span>. A diagram&nbsp;such as diagram D from the top figure, is a good example of a skewed&nbsp;data set, where the box is close to the minimum value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">Diagram of skewed data set:</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/394.svg\" style=\"width: 50%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/395.svg\" style=\"width: 60%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(206,'Conversion tables','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Conversion tables</h