\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 15%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Length</span>&nbsp;<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{cm}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Convert <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{cm}}\\)</span> to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{mm}}\\)</span></span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(({\\times10})\\)</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/414.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 200px;\"></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Nail</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Pencil</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{5\\Ndp5}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{5\\Ndp5}{\\times10}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10}{\\times10}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{55}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{100}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Second example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Tom is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{165\\:\\text{cm}}\\)</span> tall. &nbsp;How tall is he in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\text{m}}\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You are going from a smaller unit <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{\\text{cm}})\\)</span> to a larger one <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{\\text{m}})\\)</span>. &nbsp;The number of metres will be&nbsp;less than the number of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}\\)</span>. &nbsp;So it will be a division calculation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\:\\PalAa{\\text{cm}}\\)</span> in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\:\\PalAb{\\text{m}}\\)</span>, so you need to divide by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{165}}{100}=\\PalAb{1\\Ndp65}&amp;&amp;\\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{cm}}}{100}=\\PalAb{\\text{m}}\\right) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Tom is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Ndp65\\:\\text{m}}\\)</span> tall.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(207,'Measures surface','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Measures surface</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The area is a measurement of the surface of a shape. &nbsp;The surface area is the area that describes the material that will be used to cover a geometric solid.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The SI&nbsp;unit most often used for area is square metre or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}^2\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To find the area of a rectangle or a square you need to multiply the length and the width of the rectangle or the square. In this case, illustrated below,&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(l\\)</span> is the length while <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(w\\)</span> is the width of the rectangle.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The area <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A\\)</span>&nbsp;is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}A&amp;=l\\times w\\\\ &amp;=lw \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/407.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">One square metre <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1\\text{m}^2)\\)</span> is the area size&nbsp;of a square where each side of the square is one metre in length.<br>\r\n		Note that&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}\\times\\text{m}=\\text{m}^2\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/415.svg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 300px;\"></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The sketch below shows a rectangular metal plate. &nbsp;The plate has a length of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\:\\text m\\)</span> and a width of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\:\\text m\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/416.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The area of the plate is the number of squares, each <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\:\\text{m}^2\\)</span>,&nbsp;that can fit into the plate.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The area&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A\\)</span>&nbsp;is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}A&amp;=l\\times w\\\\ &amp;=5\\:\\text m \\times 3\\:\\text m\\\\ &amp;=15\\:\\text m^2 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The area of the plate is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\:\\text m^2 \\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">That means the number of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\:\\text{m}^2\\)</span>&nbsp;squares that fit into the plate is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span>. &nbsp;You can count them to check.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(208,'Converting','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Converting</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The pictures below illustrate the following&nbsp;two interesting facts about volume:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n		<ul>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align: left;\">The volume of a cube with sides <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1\\:\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAa{1\\:\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAa{1\\:\\text{cm}} \\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^3})\\)</span> is equal to <span class=\"PalAb\">one millilitre</span>:</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/411.svg\"></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/412.svg\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 50%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<ul>\r\n		<li>You can pour <span class=\"PalAb\">one litre</span> of liquid into a cube with sides <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10\\:\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAa{10\\:\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAa{10\\:\\text{cm}} \\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{1\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}^3}\\text{ or } \\PalAa{10^3\\:\\text{cm}^3})\\)</span>:</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/412.svg\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/413.svg\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Convert between litre and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{cm}^3\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The volume of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\:\\ell}\\)</span> is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb V&amp;=l\\times w\\times h\\\\ &amp;=10\\times10\\times10&amp;&amp; ( \\PalAa{\\text{cm}} \\times \\PalAa{\\text{cm}}\\times \\PalAa{\\text{cm}}) \\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{1\\Tsp000}&amp;&amp;(\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^3}) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\:\\ell}\\)</span> equals <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1\\Tsp000\\:\\text{cm}^3}\\)</span> or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10^3\\:\\text{cm}^3}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 1\\:\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^3} &amp;=1\\:\\PalAb{\\text{m}\\ell}\\\\ 1\\Tsp000\\:\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^3} =10^3\\:\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^3} &amp;= 1\\Tsp000\\:\\PalAb{\\text{m}\\ell}=1\\:\\PalAb{\\ell}\\\\ \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">To change from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\ell}\\)</span> to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^3}\\)</span> (or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}\\ell\\)</span>) multiply by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10^3\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">To change from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{cm}^3}\\)</span> (or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}\\ell\\)</span>) to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\ell}\\)</span> divide by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10^3\\)</span> or multiply with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10^{-3}\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Convert between litre and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{m}^3\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The volume of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\:\\ell}\\)</span>&nbsp;is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb V&amp;=l\\times w\\times h&amp;&amp;(10\\:\\text{cm}=0\\Ndp10\\:\\text{m})\\\\ &amp;=0\\Ndp10\\times0\\Ndp10\\times0\\Ndp10&amp;&amp; ( \\PalAa{\\text{m}} \\times \\PalAa{\\text{m}}\\times \\PalAa{\\text{m}}) \\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{0\\Ndp001}&amp;&amp;(\\PalAa{\\text{m}^3}) \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\:\\ell}\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0\\Ndp001\\:\\text{m}^3}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10^{-3}\\:\\text{m}^3}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">To change from&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\ell}\\)</span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{m}^3}\\)</span>&nbsp;divide&nbsp;by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10^3\\)</span>&nbsp;or multiply with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10^{-3}\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">To change from&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{m}^3}\\)</span>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\ell}\\)</span>&nbsp;multiply by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10^3\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(209,'Number line','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Number line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You can visualise <span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span> and <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span> numbers using the number line:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"320\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/442.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is important to understand the number line because it shows you that every number has an opposite.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Why&nbsp;do we need negative numbers? &nbsp;As it turns out, there are many everyday problems where negative numbers are useful, for example:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">We can both gain and lose weight.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Temperature can rise or fall.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Locations on the earth can be above or below sea level.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A number that is <span class=\"PalAb\">greater than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span>&nbsp;is called <span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span>. &nbsp;If it is <span class=\"PalAa\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span> it is called <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span>. &nbsp;<span class=\"PalBc\">Zero</span> is neither positive nor negative. &nbsp;Two integers that are the same distance from the <span class=\"PalBc\">origin</span> in opposite directions are called opposites, for example, <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa5\\)</span>&nbsp;is the opposite of <span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb5\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The arrows on each end of the number line show us that the line stretches to infinity in both the negative and positive direction. &nbsp;We do not have to include a positive sign <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb+)\\)</span> when we write <span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span> numbers. However, we do have to include the negative sign <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa-)\\)</span> when we write <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span> numbers.<br>\r\n<span class=\"PalBc\">Zero</span> is called the <span class=\"PalBc\">origin</span> and is neither negative nor positive.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"4\" style=\"width: 75%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"220\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/443.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"4\" style=\"width: 75%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"220\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/444.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"4\" style=\"width: 75%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"220\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/445.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(210,'Phrases','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Phrases</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Many times mathematical signs are not given, but only words like &quot;...at least...&quot;, &quot;...no more than...&quot; and<br>\r\n&quot;...at the most&hellip;&quot;. &nbsp;How can we write these using only signs?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAb\">At least</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb2\\)</span>&nbsp;means <span class=\"PalAb\">two or more</span>, <span class=\"PalAb\">two included</span>. &nbsp;We write it as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{x\\ge2}\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"170\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/446.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">No more than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">at the most</span>&nbsp;both mean&nbsp;everything <span class=\"PalAa\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">included</span>. &nbsp;We write it as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{x\\le3}\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"170\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/447.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span>&nbsp;means everything <span class=\"PalAa\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">excluded</span>. &nbsp;We write it as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{x&lt;3}\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Note the open circle above the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> on the number line,&nbsp;because <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> is excluded in this case.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"170\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/448.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The words &quot;...<span class=\"Emphasis_1\">between</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span>...&quot; are often confusing. &nbsp;It must be stated clearly whether the endpoints&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span>&nbsp;are included or not.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The number <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAa\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">greater than or equal to</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span>. &nbsp;It is written as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\PalAa\\le x\\PalAa&lt;5\\)</span>.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"170\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/449.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(211,'Ogive','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Ogive</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The graph of the cumulative frequency distribution is better known as the cumulative frequency curve or Ogive. &nbsp;The word Ogive is basically a term used in architecture to describe curves or curved shapes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">An Ogive is a graph that represents the cumulative frequencies of the intervals in a&nbsp;frequency distribution. &nbsp;It shows the data below or above a particular value.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Ogive is pronounced as &quot;O-jive&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Ogive is a graph of a cumulative distribution, which shows data values on the horizontal axis and the&nbsp;cumulative frequencies on the vertical axis. &nbsp;The Ogive is constructed by plotting a point corresponding to the cumulative frequency of each interval.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The Ogive for Radial is given below. &nbsp;Previously we calculated that <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(22\\Ndp5 \\%\\)</span>&nbsp;of Radial&#39;s customers drove&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(46\\Tsp000\\)</span>&nbsp;kilometres or less with a set of tyres. &nbsp;Such information can be presented graphically once the cumulative frequencies are known.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"650\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/423.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(212,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Mean</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The mean is a good summary for values that represent magnitudes, such as test marks and the cost of something.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Emphasis_1\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Mean for raw data</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\overline{x}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^\\PalAa nx_i}{\\PalAa n}\\)</span>&nbsp;where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAa\">number of observations</span> in the data set.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Emphasis_1\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Mean for data in frequency distribution</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\overline{x}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^\\PalAb k f_ix_i}{\\PalAa n}\\)</span>&nbsp;where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n=\\sum_{i=1}^\\PalAb kf_i\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb k\\)</span> is the <span class=\"PalAb\">number of intervals</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Median</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The median is best used when ranking people or things, like heights or when extreme values might affect the mean.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The position of the median <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((Me)\\)</span> is the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa n+1}{2}\\right)^\\text{th}\\)</span> value&nbsp;in&nbsp;a<br>\r\n		data&nbsp;set&nbsp;of size <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n\\)</span> sorted in ascending order.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Mode</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The mode is best used when finding out the most popular dress size or the most popular brand of chocolate.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The mode of a data set is that value which occurs most often.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Distribution</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<ul>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Normal distribution</span></span></li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left; margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Symmetrical with a single central peak at the mean (average) of the data.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left; margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The mean, median and the mode are the same.</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/613.jpg\" style=\"width: 80%; height: 80%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<ul>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Positively skewed distribution</span></span></li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left; margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">mode <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt;\\)</span> median <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt;\\)</span> mean</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/614.jpg\" style=\"width: 80%; height: 80%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<ul>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Negatively skewed distribution</span></li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left; margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">mean &lt; median &lt; mode</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/615.jpg\" style=\"width: 80%; height: 80%;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(213,'Spread around mean','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Spread around mean</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The standard deviation is the measure of spread most commonly used in statistical practice when the mean is used to calculate central tendency.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The standard deviation can be difficult to interpret as a single number on its own.<br>\r\nBasically, a&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">small standard deviation</span> means that the values in a statistical data set are <span class=\"PalAa\">close to the mean</span> of the data set, on average. &nbsp;A&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">large standard deviation</span> means that the values in the data set are <span class=\"PalAb\">farther away from the mean</span>, on average.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The standard deviation&nbsp;measures how concentrated the data is&nbsp;around the mean; the more concentrated, the smaller the standard deviation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The standard deviation measures the spread of data around the mean.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/438.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(214,'Shape','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Shape</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If two sets of data are plotted in bar graphs, the data set with a <span class=\"PalAa\">low standard deviation</span> would be displayed as a <span class=\"PalAa\">tall narrow </span>shape, while a <span class=\"PalAb\">large standard deviation</span> would be indicated by a <span class=\"PalAb\">lower</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">wider </span>shape.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" height=\"450\" width=\"733\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 40%;\"><span style=\"text-align: center;\">Below is a bar graph of data with&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\" style=\"text-align: center;\">small&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\" style=\"text-align: center;\">standard deviation</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 40%;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"580\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/439.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span style=\"text-align: center;\">Below is a bar graph of data with&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\" style=\"text-align: center;\">large&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\" style=\"text-align: center;\">standard deviation</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"400\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/440.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Standard deviation generally does not indicate right or wrong;&nbsp;better or worse.&nbsp; A&nbsp;lower standard deviation is not necessarily more desirable. &nbsp;It is used purely as a descriptive statistic. &nbsp;It describes the distribution in relation to the mean.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(215,'Normal curve','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Normal curve</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The standard deviation was defined as the square root of the variance. &nbsp;But what does it tell us? &nbsp;It tells us how far away the observations are from the mean. The larger the standard deviation, the further away are the data points from the mean.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following schematic presentation shows how many of the data points are between the standard deviation to the left and to the right of the mean.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"510\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/431.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For data sets that have a normal distribution the standard deviation&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\text{SD})\\)</span> can be used to determine the proportion of values that lie within a particular range of the mean value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For such <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">normal distributions</span> it is always the case that:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">About</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{68\\%}\\)</span> of values are <span class=\"PalAa\">less than one standard deviation</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{1\\text{ SD}})\\)</span> away from the mean value.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAb\">About</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{95\\%}\\)</span> of values are <span class=\"PalAb\">less than two standard deviations</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{2\\text{ SD}})\\)</span> away from the mean.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalBc\">About</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{99\\Ndp7\\%}\\)</span> of values are <span class=\"PalBc\">less than three standard deviations</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalBc{3\\text{ SD}})\\)</span> away from the mean.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(216,'Equal parts','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Equal parts</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">median</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((Me)\\)</span>is that value which separates a sorted data set into <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">two</span> equal parts:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/432.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If we divide a sorted data set into <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">four</span> equal sized parts we get <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">quartiles</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"510\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/433.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Q_1}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">first quartile</span>&nbsp;represents&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAa\">value</span>&nbsp;indicating&nbsp;</span>the<span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\"> end of the first <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{25\\%}\\)</span>&nbsp;</span>of the data values.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{Q_2}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p>The <span class=\"PalAb\">second quartile</span> represents the <span class=\"PalAb\">value</span> indicating&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAb\">end of the second</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{25\\%}\\)</span> <span class=\"BodyText\">of the data values&nbsp;(or</span>&nbsp;the value which&nbsp;divides the data set&nbsp;into two equal parts). &nbsp;The second quartile&nbsp;has the same value as&nbsp;the median.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Q_3}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBc\">third quartile</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;represents the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBc\">value</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;indicating&nbsp;the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBc\">end of the third</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{25\\%}\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">of the data values.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(217,'Quartile deviation','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Quartile deviation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/434.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Another measure of dispersion is the range of the middle half of the data.<br>\r\nThe <span class=\"PalAb\">middle</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{50\\%}\\)</span> of the data lies </span>between<span class=\"BodyText\"> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Q_1}\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Q_3}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The measure <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{Q_D}\\)</span>&nbsp;is called the <span class=\"PalAb\">quartile deviation</span> and is the measurement of the dispersion of the data around the median.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{Q_D}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc{Q_3}-\\PalAa{Q_1}}{2}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">As with the median, the quartile deviation does not use all the observations. &nbsp;It ignores outliers since the <span class=\"PalBc\">top <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{25\\%}\\)</span></span> and the <span class=\"PalAa\">bottom <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{25\\%}\\)</span></span> of the data values are not taken into account.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">An outlier is a data point that is significantly different numerically from the other data points in a sample. &nbsp;The term is used in statistical studies and can point to abnormalities in the data set studied, or errors in the measurements taken.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If a measurement falls to the <span class=\"PalBc\">right of</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{Q_3}\\)</span> of a set of data, then we know that it is in the <span class=\"PalBc\">top</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{25\\%}\\)</span> of the data.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If a measurement falls to the <span class=\"PalAa\">left of</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{Q_1}\\)</span> of a set of data, then we know that it is in the <span class=\"PalAa\">bottom</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{25\\%}\\)</span> of the data.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(218,'Ratio of S to mean','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Ratio of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span> to mean</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;coefficient of variation&nbsp;is a statistical measure of the dispersion of data points in a data set around the mean. It is calculated as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\text{Coefficient of variation } &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text{standard deviation}}{\\text{mean}}\\\\ CV&amp;=\\frac{S}{\\overline{x}}\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The coefficient of variation represents the ratio of the standard deviation to the mean. &nbsp;It is a useful statistic for comparing the degree of variation from one data set to another, even if the means are drastically different from each other.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The coefficient of variation provides a way to compare the dispersion of values of samples or&nbsp;populations around their means. &nbsp;The graphics below show&nbsp;two normally distributed populations, both with a mean of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span>. &nbsp;The one on the left has a <span class=\"PalAa\">standard deviation</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{20}\\)</span> and the one on the right has a <span class=\"PalAb\">standard deviation</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{100}\\)</span>, giving a <span class=\"PalAa\">coefficient&nbsp;of variation</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0\\Ndp02}\\)</span> and a <span class=\"PalAb\">coefficient&nbsp;of variation</span> of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{0\\Ndp10}\\)</span> respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\text{mean}&amp;=1\\Tsp000\\\\ \\PalAb{\\text{standard deviation}}&amp;=\\PalAb{20}\\\\ \\PalAb{\\text{coefficient of variation}}&amp;=\\PalAb{0\\Ndp02} \\end{align}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"380\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/436.html\" width=\"630\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\text{mean}&amp;=1\\Tsp000\\\\ \\PalAa{\\text{standard deviation}}&amp;=\\PalAa{100}\\\\ \\PalAa{\\text{coefficient of variation}}&amp;=\\PalAa{0\\Ndp10} \\end{align}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"380\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/435.html\" width=\"630\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">In cases where the means are the same, as in the cases illustrated above,&nbsp;the coefficients of variation provide&nbsp;no more information than the standard deviations themselves.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The coefficient of variation is of more use when populations have different means and standard deviations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The graph below is loosely based on the yearly precipitation at two places in areas with significantly different climates:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Semi-arid, sub-tropical area</span></th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Humid, sub-tropical area</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa{ \\text{mean}}&amp;=\\PalAa{294\\:\\text{mm}}\\\\ \\PalAa{\\text{standard deviation}}&amp;=\\PalAa{83\\:\\text{mm}}\\\\ \\PalAa{\\text{coefficient of variation}}&amp;=\\PalAa{0\\Ndp28} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb{\\text{mean}}&amp;=\\PalAb{1\\Tsp265\\:\\text{mm}}\\\\ \\PalAb{\\text{standard deviation}}&amp;=\\PalAb{268\\:\\text{mm}}\\\\ \\PalAb{\\text{coefficient of variation}}&amp;=\\PalAb{0\\Ndp21} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/437.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Whilst there are marked differences in the mean and standard deviation of the precipitation at the two places, the coefficients of variation are of similar magnitude.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(219,'Add and subtract 1','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Add and subtract 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us meet teenager Steve. &nbsp;His parents have a marks system to help them decide if he can go to a party on Friday night:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">&quot;If you do a chore we will <span class=\"PalAb\">add</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span> points <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{+4})\\)</span>.&quot;<br>\r\n		&quot;If you do not behave, we <span class=\"PalAa\">take away</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa4\\)</span> points <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{-4})\\)</span>.&quot;<br>\r\n		&quot;If you reach <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(30\\)</span> points by Friday, you can go the party.&quot;</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Steve starts on Wednesday with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span> points.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\">Event</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 20%;\">Mom&#39;s<br>\r\n		calculations</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"5\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 2%;\">List of&nbsp;Steve&#39;s points</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Steve starts on Wednesday with&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span>&nbsp;points.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 1%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Steve&#39;s mom discovers his bicycle lying in the driveway in front of the garage.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\PalAa{-4}=16\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\PalAa{-4}=16\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">(undo)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">His little brother confesses that he used Steve&#39;s bicycle and left it there. &nbsp;Mom writes <span class=\"PalAa\">(undo)</span>&nbsp;on the list and <span class=\"PalAa\">subtracts</span> the previous calculation value.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 16\\PalAa-(\\PalAa{-4})&amp;=16\\PalAb{+4}\\\\ &amp;=20 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"11\" style=\"width: 2%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If you <span class=\"PalAa\">subtract</span> a <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span>, you <span class=\"PalAb\">gain</span> points, like <span class=\"PalAb\">adding</span> points;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/647.JPG\" style=\"width: 217px; height: 58px;\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Mom <span class=\"PalAb\">adds</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span> points because Steve takes out the garbage.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\PalAb{+4}=24\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\PalAb{+4}=24\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>(undo)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Dad says that he took out the garbage and writes <span>(undo)</span> on the list.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 24\\PalAa-(\\PalAb{+4})&amp;=24\\PalAa{-4}\\\\ &amp;=20 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"11\" style=\"width: 2%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>If you&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">subtract</span><span>&nbsp;a&nbsp;</span></span><span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>, you </span></span><span class=\"PalAa\">lose</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>&nbsp;points, like </span></span><span class=\"PalAa\">subtracting</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>&nbsp;points;&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span>\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/648.JPG\" style=\"width: 217px; height: 53px;\"></span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Dad sees Steve brushing the dog and writes <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(+4)}\\)</span> on the list.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 24\\PalAb+(\\PalAb{+4})&amp;=20\\PalAb{+4}\\\\ &amp;=24 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\PalAb{+4}=24\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(+4)}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"11\" style=\"width: 2%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If you&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">add</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;a&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">, you&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">gain</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;points, like&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">adding</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;points;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/649.JPG\" style=\"width: 217px; height: 55px;\"></span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Steve throws a piece of wood at his brother. &nbsp;Dad writes <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(-4)}\\)</span>&nbsp;on the list.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 24\\PalAb+(\\PalAa{-4})&amp;=24\\PalAa{-4}\\\\ &amp;=20 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\PalAa{-4}=20\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(-4)}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"11\" style=\"width: 2%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If you&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">add</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;a&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">, you&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">lose</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;points, like&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">subtracting</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;points;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/650.JPG\" style=\"width: 217px; height: 55px;\"></span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Do you think&nbsp;Steve will reach <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(30\\)</span> points by Friday?</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(220,'Add and subtract 2','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Add and subtract 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If a number has <span class=\"PalAb\">no sign</span> it usually means that it is a <span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span> number: <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb5\\)</span> is really <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{+5}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Addition</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Adding</span> a <span class=\"PalAb\">positiv</span>e number is just simple <span class=\"PalAb\">addition</span>:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb+\\text{ and }\\PalAb+\\text{ gives }\\PalAb+\\)</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} ({+5})\\PalAb+(\\PalAb{+3})&amp;=({+8})&amp;\\text{or}\\\\ 5\\PalAb{+3}&amp;=8 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Subtracting</span> a <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span> number is the same as <span class=\"PalAb\">addition</span>:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa-\\text{ and }\\PalAa-\\text{ gives }\\PalAb+\\)</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} ({+5})\\PalAa-(\\PalAa{-3})&amp;=({+8})&amp;\\text{or}\\\\ 5\\PalAb{+3}&amp;=8 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Subtraction</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Subtracting</span> a <span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span> number is just simple <span class=\"PalAa\">subtraction</span>:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa-\\text{ and }\\PalAb+\\text{ gives }\\PalAa-\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} ({+5})\\PalAa-(\\PalAb{+3})&amp;=({+2})&amp;\\text{or}\\\\ 5\\PalAa{-3}&amp;=2 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Adding</span> a <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span> number is the same as <span class=\"PalAa\">subtraction</span>:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb+\\text{ and }\\PalAa-\\text{ gives }\\PalAa-\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} ({+5})\\PalAb+(\\PalAa{-3})&amp;=({+2})&amp;\\text{or}\\\\ 5\\PalAa{-3}&amp;=2 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(221,'Multiply and divide','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Multiply and divide</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What happens to <span class=\"PalAb\">plus</span> signs and <span class=\"PalAa\">minus</span> signs in multiplication and division?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAb+\\times\\PalAb+&amp;=\\PalAb+\\\\ \\PalAb +\\div \\PalAb+&amp;=\\PalAb+ \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Two</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">positives</span> make a <span class=\"PalAb\">positive</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa-\\times\\PalAa-&amp;=\\PalAb+\\\\ \\PalAa-\\div \\PalAa-&amp;=\\PalAb+ \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Two negatives</span> make a <span class=\"PalAa\">positive</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa-\\times\\PalAb+&amp;=\\PalAa-\\\\ \\PalAa-\\div \\PalAb+&amp;=\\PalAa- \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">A</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">a positive</span> make a <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb+\\times\\PalAa-&amp;=\\PalAa-\\\\ \\PalAb +\\div \\PalAa-&amp;=\\PalAa- \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">A positive</span> and <span class=\"PalAa\">a negative </span>make a <span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb3\\times\\PalAb2&amp;=\\PalAb6\\\\ \\PalAa{-3}\\times\\PalAa{-2}&amp;=\\PalAb6\\\\ \\PalAa{-3}\\times\\PalAb2&amp;=\\PalAa{-6}\\\\ \\PalAb3\\times\\PalAa{-2}&amp;=\\PalAa{-6} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What about multiplying three or more numbers together? &nbsp;That is easy, you multiply two at a time and follow the rule. &nbsp;(Keep in mind, dividing&nbsp;is like multiplying with the inverse.)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(222,'Summation','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The summation symbol is an important symbol&nbsp;when working with numbers. It&nbsp;is a very useful sign, because it is the mathematical shorthand sign for adding.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The Greek capital letter for S is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\sum\\)</span> and is pronounced as &quot;sigma&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Sign for sum</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The summation symbol&nbsp;is the mathematical shorthand sign for adding.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 18%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\sum\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What must we add?</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Whatever appears after the sigma is added. &nbsp;Here we will sum <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\sum \\PalBc n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What is the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The values are shown below and above&nbsp;the sigma. &nbsp;In this case&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">starts</span> at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">ends</span> at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span>, so that is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc n=\\PalAa1}^{\\PalAb 4}{\\PalBc n}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Have a look</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So now we add up&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;\\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc n=\\PalAa1}^{\\PalAb 4}{\\PalBc n}\\\\ =\\:&amp;\\PalAa1+2+3+\\PalAb4\\\\ =\\:&amp;10 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Instead of adding numbers, we&nbsp;can also add variables.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose we have the following variables:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_1=4\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_2=9\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_3=2\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_4=5\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_5=8\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculating the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\sum_{i=1}^5{x_i}\\)</span>&nbsp;gives:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc i=\\PalAa1}^\\PalAb5{x_\\PalBc i}&amp;=x_\\PalAa1+x_2+x_3+x_4+x_\\PalAb5\\\\ &amp;=4+9+2+5+8\\\\ &amp;=28 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc i=\\PalAa2}^\\PalAb4{x_\\PalBc i}\\)</span>&nbsp;you will calculate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_\\PalAa2+x_3+x_\\PalAb4\\)</span>. &nbsp;Substitute the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc i\\)</span> in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_\\PalBc i\\)</span> for the specified range. &nbsp;The variable <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc i\\)</span> starts at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa2\\)</span> and ends at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb4\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc i=\\PalAa2}^\\PalAb4{x_\\PalBc i} &amp;=x_\\PalAa2+x_3+x_\\PalAb4\\\\ &amp;= 9+2+5\\\\ &amp;=16 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc i=\\PalAa1}^\\PalAb2{x_\\PalBc i}\\)</span>&nbsp;you will calculate&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_\\PalAa1+x_\\PalAb2\\)</span>. &nbsp;Substitute the value of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc i\\)</span>&nbsp;in&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_\\PalBc i\\)</span>&nbsp;for the specified range. &nbsp;The variable&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc i\\)</span>starts at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span>&nbsp;and ends at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb2\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc i=\\PalAa1}^\\PalAb2{x_\\PalBc i}&amp;=x_\\PalAa1+x_\\PalAb2\\\\ &amp;=4+9\\\\ &amp;=13 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc i=\\PalAa1}^\\PalAb3{x_\\PalBc i}^2\\)</span>&nbsp;you will calculate&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_\\PalAa1^2+x_2^2+x_\\PalAb3^2\\)</span>. &nbsp;Substitute the value of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc i\\)</span>&nbsp;in&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_\\PalBc i^2\\)</span>&nbsp;for the specified range. &nbsp;The variable&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc i\\)</span>&nbsp;starts at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa1\\)</span>&nbsp;and ends at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb3\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\displaystyle\\sum_{\\PalBc i=\\PalAa1}^\\PalAb3{x_\\PalBc i}^2&amp;=x_\\PalAa1^2+x_2^2+x_\\PalAb3^2\\\\ &amp;=4^2+9^2+2^2\\\\ &amp;= 16+81+4\\\\ &amp;=101\\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(223,'Definition','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Definition</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The factorial (denoted by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(!\\)</span>) of a natural number is the product&nbsp;of<br>\r\n		all natural numbers that are less than or equal to that number.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In other words, the factorial of a non-negative integer <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span>, denoted by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n!\\)</span>,&nbsp;is the product of all positive integers less than or equal to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n!=\\PalBc n\\times(\\PalBc n-1)\\times(\\PalBc n-2)\\times\\ldots\\times3\\times2\\times1\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc3!\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is shorthand for&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc3\\times2\\times1\\)</span>. &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc 3!\\)</span> is usually pronounced &quot;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc3\\)</span> factorial&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:8px;\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/651.JPG\" style=\"width: 24px; height: 66px; float: left;\"></span><span style=\"font-size:8px;\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalBc3!&amp;=\\PalBc3\\times2\\times1=6\\\\ \\PalBc2!&amp;=\\PalBc2\\times1=2\\\\ \\PalBc5!&amp;=\\PalBc5\\times4\\times3\\times2\\times1=120 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You can easily calculate the factorial of a natural number from the factorial of the preceding natural number:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n!\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc2\\times1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc2\\times1!\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc3\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc3\\times2\\times1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc3\\times2!\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc4\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc4\\times3\\times2\\times1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc4\\times3!\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(24\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc5\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc5\\times4\\times3\\times2\\times1\\)</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc5\\times4!\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(120\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc9!\\)</span> if you know that <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8!=40\\Tsp320\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalBc9!&amp;=\\PalBc9\\times8!\\\\ \\PalBc9!&amp;=\\PalBc9\\times40\\Tsp320\\\\ &amp;=362\\Tsp880 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So the rule is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n!=\\PalBc n\\times(\\PalBc n-1)!\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This just means that&nbsp;the factorial of any natural number is that number times the factorial of one&nbsp;smaller than that number. &nbsp;Therefore <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc9!=\\PalBc9\\times8!\\)</span>&nbsp;<br>\r\nand <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{130}!=\\PalBc{130}\\times129!\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(224,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What about&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0!\\)</span>&nbsp;(zero factorial)? &nbsp;Zero factorial is interesting. &nbsp;It is generally agreed that:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0!=1\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It may seem funny that multiplying no numbers together gets you one, but it helps to simplify a lot of calculations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Where is factorial used? &nbsp;Factorials are used in many areas of Mathematics, but particularly in combinations and permutations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{8!}{3!}\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us write the factorials out in full:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 8!&amp;=8\\times7\\times6\\times5\\times4\\times3\\times2\\times1\\\\ 3!&amp;=3\\times2\\times1 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\displaystyle\\frac{8!}{3!} &amp;=\\frac{8\\times7\\times6\\times5\\times4\\times3\\times2\\times1}{3\\times2\\times1}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{8\\times7\\times6\\times5\\times4\\:\\times\\not3\\:\\times\\not2\\:\\times\\not1}{\\not3\\:\\times\\not2\\:\\times\\not1}\\\\ &amp;=8\\times7\\times6\\times5\\times4\\\\ &amp;=6\\Tsp720 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\times2\\times1\\)</span> cancelled out, leaving only <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\times7\\times6\\times5\\times4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(225,'Formulas','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Formulas</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The number of permutations of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects&nbsp;out of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}P\\PalBc{_n}=\\PalBc n!\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The number of permutations of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span> objects&nbsp;out of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}P\\PalAb{_r}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc n!}{(\\PalBc n-\\PalAb r)!}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(226,'Formulas','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Formulas</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us look at a summary of the formulas.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Permutations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects and you want to <span class=\"BodyText\">arrange</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span> objects from the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects, then you use permutations:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Permutations -&nbsp;order is important<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}P\\PalAb{_r}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc n!}{(\\PalBc n-\\PalAb r)!}\\)</span>&nbsp; &nbsp; and &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}P\\PalBc{_n}=\\PalBc n!\\)</span><br>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}P\\PalAb{_r}\\)</span>&nbsp;can also be written as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{^n}P\\PalAb{_r}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P(\\PalBc n,\\PalAb r)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}P\\PalAb{_r}\\)</span>&nbsp;is the number&nbsp;of permutations of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects taken <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span> at a time.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Combinations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects and you want to <span class=\"BodyText\">select</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span> objects from the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> objects, then you use combinations:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Combinations -&nbsp;order is not important<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}C\\PalAb{_r}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc{_n}P\\PalAb{_r}}{\\PalAb r!}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc n!}{(\\PalBc n-\\PalAb r)!\\PalAb r!}\\)</span><br>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}C\\PalAb{_r}\\)</span>&nbsp;can&nbsp;also be written as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{^n}C\\PalAb{_r}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(C(\\PalBc n,\\PalAb r)\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left( \\begin{array}{c} \\PalBc n\\\\ \\PalAb r \\end{array} \\right)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{_n}C\\PalAb{_r}\\)</span>&nbsp;is the number&nbsp;of combinations of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span>&nbsp;objects taken&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span>&nbsp;at a time and is sometimes read as &quot;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc n\\)</span> choose <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb r\\)</span>&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:57','2017-10-11 10:04:57','',NULL),(227,'SI System','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">SI System</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is difficult to imagine a world without a system for measuring things. &nbsp;You would not know the distance to another town, the capacity in litres of a fuel tank or whether your body mass is within limits, and so forth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The earliest measuring systems originated in the barter system and units corresponded with things