er;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that it is not taken into account whether there is a duplication of scores around the median.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(241,'Example - Sensitivity','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example - Sensitivity</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The median is not sensitive to extreme scores.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Compare the medians of the following two similar&nbsp;ordered data sets. &nbsp;The two sets are the same, except for the highest score in each case. &nbsp;In&nbsp;the first set the highest score is not extreme, but in the second it is&nbsp;extreme.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the first instance, a&nbsp;survey of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;employees&#39; performance scores out of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;gave&nbsp;the following&nbsp;results, ordered from lowest to highest, with&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({46}\\)</span>&nbsp;as&nbsp;the highest score:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(32\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(32\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{38}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(46\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">median</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is&nbsp;the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">middle number</span><span class=\"BodyText\">. &nbsp;In the case above the median is the number&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{38}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the second instance, a&nbsp;survey of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;employees&#39; performance scores out of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span><br>\r\n<span class=\"BodyText\">gave&nbsp;the following&nbsp;results, ordered from lowest to highest, with the highest score of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{50}\\)</span><br>\r\nas an <span class=\"PalAa\">extreme score</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(32\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(32\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{38}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(39\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{50}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In this case with the <span class=\"PalAa\">extreme score</span>, the <span class=\"PalAb\">median</span> is still the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{38}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(242,'Compare data sets','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Compare data sets</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Another reason for studying the dispersion in a set of data is to compare the spread in two or more sets of data.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When comparing the spread of two separate data sets, named <span class=\"PalAa\">A</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">B</span>, that have approximately the same mean, data set <span class=\"PalAa\">A</span> has a <span class=\"PalAa\">smaller standard deviation</span>. &nbsp;It has a <span class=\"PalAa\">narrower spread</span> of measurements around the mean and therefore usually has comparatively <span class=\"PalAa\">fewer high or low</span> data values. &nbsp;Data set <span class=\"PalAb\">B</span> has a <span class=\"PalAb\">larger standard deviation</span>. &nbsp;It has a <span class=\"PalAb\">wider spread</span> of measurements around the mean and therefore usually has <span class=\"PalAb\">more high and low</span> data values.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">An item selected at random from data set <span class=\"PalAa\">A</span> whose <span class=\"PalAa\">standard deviation</span> is <span class=\"PalAa\">low</span> has a better chance of being <span class=\"PalAa\">close to the mean</span> than an item from data set <span class=\"PalAb\">B</span> whose <span class=\"PalAb\">standard deviation</span> is <span class=\"PalAb\">higher</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(243,'Formulas','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Formulas</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is possible to calculate the mean, variance and standard deviation where we have not been provided with the raw data, but data grouped into intervals, with frequencies associated with each interval.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The assumption we make is that each <span class=\"PalBc\">interval</span> is represented by its <span class=\"PalBc\">midpoint</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The standard deviation is the positive square root of the variance:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Standard deviation</span> is&nbsp;<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=\\sqrt{S^2}\\)</span><br>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The formulas for finding the variance for both types of data are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Raw data variance</span> is &nbsp;<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S^2=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^\\PalAa n (\\PalBc x_i-\\overline{\\PalBc x})^2}{\\PalAa n-1}\\)</span>&nbsp;<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n\\)</span>&nbsp;is the <span class=\"PalAa\">number of observations</span> in the data set.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Data in frequency distribution variance</span> is<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S^2=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^\\PalAa n (\\PalBc x_i-\\overline{\\PalBc x})^2}{\\PalAa n-1}\\)</span>&nbsp;<br>\r\n		<br>\r\n		where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n=\\sum_{i=1}^\\PalAb kf_i\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb k\\)</span> is the <span class=\"PalAb\">number of intervals</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(244,'Variability of data sets','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Variability of data sets</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is often difficult to use the standard deviation formula to compare measurements from different populations. &nbsp;Due to this fact, statisticians produced the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">coefficient of variation</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((CV)\\)</span>. &nbsp;The coefficient of variation expresses the standard deviation as a percentage of what is being measured relative to the sample or population mean.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The coefficient of variation is useful because the standard deviation of data must always be understood in the context of the mean of the data. &nbsp;In contrast, the actual value of the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span> is independent of the unit in which the measurement has been taken, so it is a dimensionless number.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The numerator and denominator of the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span> have the same units, so the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span> itself has no units of measurement. &nbsp;If a data set consists of the monthly salaries of employees, the mean salary will be in rand and the standard deviation will also be in rand, but the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span>&nbsp;will not be.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What we mean when we say that&nbsp;the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span> has no units of measurement,&nbsp;is that when the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span> is calculated, the units cancel out. &nbsp;This can be illustrated as follows, using rand <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\Cur)\\)</span>&nbsp;as unit of measurement:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV=\\displaystyle\\frac{S}{\\overline{x}}=\\frac{\\not\\Cur}{\\not\\Cur}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span> is sometimes expressed as a percentage, in which case the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV\\)</span> is multiplied by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(CV=\\displaystyle\\frac{S}{\\overline{x}}\\times 100=\\%\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The advantage is that one is able to directly compare the variability of two different populations using the coefficient of variation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For comparison between data sets with different units or widely different means, one should use the coefficient of variation instead of the standard deviation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can also use the coefficient of variation if we wish to compare the variability of two or more data sets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The data set for which the coefficient of variation is large indicates<br>\r\n		that the group is more variable and it is less stable or less uniform.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(245,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A stockbroker wants to compare two unit trusts. &nbsp;He has the annual return rates of the two unit trusts for the past ten years available and calculates the mean and variance of each:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 20%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Mean&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\overline{x}}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 20%;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Variance&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{S_x^2}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Fund A</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{16}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 8%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{280\\Ndp34}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Fund B</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{12}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{99\\Ndp37}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We see that the <span class=\"PalAb\">variance</span> for Fund A is <span class=\"PalAb\">higher</span> than that of Fund B and we draw the conclusion that the <span class=\"PalAb\">risk</span> associated with Fund A is <span class=\"PalAb\">higher</span> than that for Fund B.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">However, Fund A displayed a <span class=\"PalAa\">higher</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">mean</span> return over the past ten years than Fund B. &nbsp;This feels intuitively right -&nbsp;an investment having a <span class=\"PalAb\">higher</span> associated <span class=\"PalAb\">risk</span> should have a <span class=\"PalAa\">higher</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">mean</span> rate of return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">But what if Fund A had a <span class=\"PalAa\">mean</span> rate of return of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{21\\%}\\)</span> with the <span class=\"PalAb\">same variance</span>?<br>\r\nWould we then still be able to say that Fund A is subject to higher fluctuation than Fund B?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is only when the two means are close together that we may compare the variances or standard deviations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(246,'Example - More than one','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example - More than one</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A data set may have more than one mode if the most frequently occurring scores occur the same number of times.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A survey of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14\\)</span>&nbsp;employees&#39; performance scores out of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span>&nbsp;had these results, ordered from lowest to highest:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{33}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{33}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{33}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(36\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(37\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(40\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(42\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(45\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us look at the data in a different way:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1501/assets/450.svg\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 350px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are <span class=\"PalAb\">two modes</span>, namely <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{33}\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{39}\\)</span>. &nbsp;Such distributions are called <span class=\"PalAb\">bimodal</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(247,'Activity','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODQwNDE1NTM5NzI1MDI2MiJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-12-15 10:34:36','',NULL),(248,'TEST &amp; OTHER PAGES','\r\n<p>TEST &amp; OTHER PAGES</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(249,'Numbers and working with numbers','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Numbers and working with numbers</h3>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(250,'Index numbers and transformations','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Index numbers and transformations</h3>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(251,'Collection, presentation and description of data','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Collection, presentation and description of data</h3>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(252,'Learning objectives','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Learning objectives</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">On completion of this learning unit you should know and be able to apply:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">the priority rules in solving problems</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This learning unit includes activities, a video, an exercise and assignment questions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 10:04:58','2017-10-11 10:04:58','',NULL),(253,'Order of operations','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Order of operati