ou are registered for the second semester, answer the questions for the second semester.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Submit Assignment 04&nbsp;on&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\">my</em><span class=\"BodyText\">Unisa. &nbsp;The marks will contribute towards&nbsp;your semester mark. &nbsp;You have to obtain the answers for all eight&nbsp;questions of Assignment 04&nbsp;before you&nbsp;submit Assignment 04&nbsp;on&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\">my</em><span class=\"BodyText\">Unisa. &nbsp;Therefore, you have to complete all the study units applicable to&nbsp;Assignment 04&nbsp;before you can submit it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If possible, print this page so that you do not need to go through the whole study unit again to get to&nbsp;the questions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading2\">First semester</h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Unique number:&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">785869</span></h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Due date: 22 March 2016</h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Question 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the following statement concerning the collection of data, and determine the best selection of&nbsp;terms to complete the statement:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The entire group of objects or people about which information is wanted is called the <u>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</u>(A). &nbsp;The&nbsp;representative group that is actually examined in order to gather information, is the <u>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</u>(B). &nbsp;The items&nbsp;which are measured or counted with respect to the variable being studied, are the <u>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</u>(C).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 35%;\">\r\n		<ol>\r\n		<li><span class=\"BodyText\">(A) &nbsp;population</span></li>\r\n		<li><span class=\"BodyText\">(A) &nbsp;whole</span></li>\r\n		<li><span class=\"BodyText\">(A) &nbsp;sample</span></li>\r\n		<li><span class=\"BodyText\">(A) &nbsp;population</span></li>\r\n		</ol>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 32%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">(B) &nbsp;sample<br>\r\n		(B) &nbsp;stratum<br>\r\n		(B) &nbsp;target population<br>\r\n		(B) &nbsp;subgroup</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">(C) &nbsp;sample units<br>\r\n		(C) &nbsp;items of interest<br>\r\n		(C) &nbsp;sample units<br>\r\n		(C) &nbsp;explanatory variables</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Question 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose your population is a list with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(200\\Tsp000\\)</span> residential addresses that you obtained from the town&nbsp;council of a city. &nbsp;You decide to take a random start between <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(50\\)</span> and then take every <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000^{\\text{th}}\\)</span>&nbsp;address. &nbsp;This sampling technique is called:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">systematic sampling</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">stratified random sampling</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">simple random sampling</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">availability sampling</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Questions 3 and 4 are based on the fol