an give an unbelievable amount of information and help you to solve problems more easily.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">The equation of a linear function</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">An equation is&nbsp;defined as linear when its graph presents a linear function, in other words, a <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">straight line</span>. The equation of a linear function is&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)=ax+b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span> are constants.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">The intercepts of a straight line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us look at the general properties of a straight line. We are going to talk about <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-</em> and <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></em>-intercepts.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-intercept</span> of a straight line is the point where it crosses the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span>.<br>\r\n		The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span><span class=\"PalAa\">-intercept</span> of a straight line is the point where it crosses the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span>Example</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/315.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-intercept</span> is the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {(2; 0)}\\)</span>&nbsp;This is where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {y=0}\\)</span>. &nbsp;Sometimes&nbsp;the <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-intercept</span> is defined as the <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-coordinate</span> of the point where the line crosses the&nbsp;<em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-intercept</span> is the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {(0; 4)}\\)</span>. &nbsp;This is where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {x = 0}\\)</span>. &nbsp;Sometimes the <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-intercep</span>t is defined as the <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-coordinate</span> of the point where the line crosses the <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(541,'Values of a and b ','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Values of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equation for the straight line is</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)=\\PalAb ax+\\PalAa b\\)</span></em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where <span class=\"Emphasis_3\"><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb a\\)</span> </em></span> and <span class=\"Emphasis_2\"><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa b\\)</span></em></span> are constants. &nbsp;By constants, we mean that <em><span class=\"Emphasis_3\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb a\\)</span></span></em> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa b\\)</span> are numbers. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/315.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equation for this&nbsp;straight line is</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)=\\PalAb {-2}x+\\PalAa 4\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">From this, we see that if the equation for a straight line is</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)=\\PalAb ax+\\PalAa b\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">then&nbsp;the value of&nbsp;<em><span class=\"Emphasis_3\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb a\\)</span></span></em>&nbsp;is equal to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {-2}\\)</span>&nbsp;and the value of&nbsp;<span class=\"Emphasis_2\"><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa b\\)</span></em></span>&nbsp;is equal to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa 4\\)</span></span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Interactive mathematics model</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The graph below shows the straight line discussed above where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {a=-2}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {b = 4}\\)</span>. &nbsp;Play around with the sliders to change the values of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb a\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa b\\)</span>&nbsp;and observe the effect it has on the graph.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"650\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/2.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(542,'y-intercept','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercept of a straight line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The point where the line cuts the <em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span> is called the <em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-intercept</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/154.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">At this point,&nbsp;where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {x = 0}\\)</span>, the value of <em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span> </em>is the following in general and in this specific example case:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">General case</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Straight line equation</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=a\\PalAb x+b\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {x=0}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa y &amp;=a(\\PalAb 0)+b\\\\ &amp;= a \\times \\PalAb 0 +b \\\\ &amp; = 0+b\\\\&amp;=\\PalAa b \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Conclusion</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Intercept on&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span></span><span>&nbsp;is equal to constant term&nbsp;</span><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa b\\)</span></em><span>&nbsp;in equation for&nbsp;straight line.</span><br>\r\n		The&nbsp;<em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-intercept</span><span> &nbsp;is the point&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(0; b)}\\)</span>.</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example case</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p>Equation of line</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=-2\\PalAb x+4\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span>Substitute&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {x=0}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa y &amp;=-2(\\PalAb 0)+4\\\\ &amp;= -2 \\times \\PalAb 0 +4 \\\\ &amp; = 0+4\\\\&amp;=4 \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p>Conclusion</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The intercept on the&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span> is equal to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa4\\)</span>.</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-intercept</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;&nbsp;is the point&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(0; 4)}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span>The straight line&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = ax + b\\)</span>, cuts the&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span> at the point&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(0; b)}\\)</span><span>. &nbsp;<br>\r\n		Therefore, the line&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = -2x+4 \\)</span><span>, cuts the&nbsp;</span><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span><span>&nbsp;at&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{y = b = 4}\\)</span><span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(543,'x-intercept','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The <em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span></em>-intercept of a straight line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The point where the line cuts the&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is called the&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-intercept&nbsp;</span>or root.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/155.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">At this point,&nbsp;where&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {y = 0}\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, the value of&nbsp;</span><em class=\"Variable\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;can be determined&nbsp;by following the steps given below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">General case</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Straight line equation</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=a\\PalAb x+b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{y=0}\\)</span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa0=a\\PalAb x+b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Subtract&nbsp;<em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span></em><i>&nbsp;</i>both sides&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"margin-top: 0em; margin-bottom: 1em;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa0-b &amp; = a\\PalAb x +b -b \\\\ -b &amp; = a\\PalAb x \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Assuming&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\neq0\\)</span>, divide by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;both sides</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"margin-top: 0em; margin-bottom: 1em;\"><span style=\"line-height: 27px;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} -\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a}&amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{a\\PalAb x}{a}\\\\ -\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a}&amp;=\\PalAb x\\\\ \\PalAb x&amp;=-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a} \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Conclusion</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Intercept on&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em></span><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is equal to </span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a}}\\)</span></em><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;in equation for&nbsp;straight line.</span><br class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-intercept</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;&nbsp;is the point&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a};0)}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example case</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">General case</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=a\\PalAb x+b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Values of variables</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=-2\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=4\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute for equation</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=-2\\PalAb x+4\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 150px;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{y = 0}\\)</span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa0=-2\\PalAb x+4\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 150px;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Subtract&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-4\\)</span>&nbsp;both sides</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa0-4&amp;=-2\\PalAb x+4-4 \\\\-4&amp;=-2\\PalAb x \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 150px;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Divide by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-2\\)</span>&nbsp;both sides</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\displaystyle\\frac{-4}{-2} &amp; = \\displaystyle\\frac{-2\\PalAb x}{-2} \\\\ 2 &amp; = \\PalAb x \\\\ \\PalAb x &amp; =2 \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 150px;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Conclusion</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The intercept on the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is equal to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb2\\)</span>.</span><br class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-intercept</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;&nbsp;is the point&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\left(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a};0\\right)}=\\PalAb{(\\displaystyle\\frac{-4}{-2};0)}=\\PalAb{(2;0)}\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">.</span><span style=\"line-height: 27px;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span>The straight line&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = ax + b\\)</span>, cuts the&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em></span><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span><span>&nbsp;at the point&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a};0)}\\)</span><span>. &nbsp;<br>\r\n		Therefore, the line&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = -2x+4 \\)</span><span>, cuts the&nbsp;</span><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span><span>&nbsp;at&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{x = -\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a} = \\displaystyle\\frac{-4}{-2}=2}\\)</span><span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(544,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>- and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercepts of a straight line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span>For the straight line&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=a\\PalAb x+b\\)</span></span>&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-intercept&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">is where&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=0\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, so then&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{x= -\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a}}\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, and&nbsp;the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">-intercept</span>&nbsp;is where&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=0\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, so&nbsp;then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{y= b}\\)</span></span><span class=\"BodyText\">.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Thus, we can conclude that the line&nbsp; <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=a\\PalAb x+b\\)</span></span>&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">cuts the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span> at the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a};0)}\\)</span> and the <em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span> at the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {(0 ; b)}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/156.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(545,'Two points','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Drawing the graph on a set of axes with two points</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Only two points are needed to determine an equation of a straight line and to draw the graph of a straight line.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are not convinced of this, just mark two points on a piece of paper and try to put more than one straight line through them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To draw a straight line we make use of the general method.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">General method to draw a straight line</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">Step 1</th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Draw your axes and label them.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">Step 2</th>\r\n		<td>Choose the scale of the axes.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">Step 3</th>\r\n		<td>Plot the two given points.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">Step 4</th>\r\n		<td>Draw a line through the two plotted points.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><strong>Example</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Graph the straight line that passes through the points&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1;4)\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((4;2)\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/160.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(546,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">How do we draw the graph of a straight line if we do not have two points but the equation of the line?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on graphing a straight line using the equation of the line:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/295.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(547,'Definition - Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on the slope of a straight line:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/297.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(548,'Ratio of change - Video','\r\n<div id=\"course_code\">FBN1502\r\n</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\" style=\"text-align:center\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on the ratio of change or&nbsp;slope of a line:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/298.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(549,'Negative slope - Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on the negative slope of a straight line:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/299.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(550,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The slope of a straight line: Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The steepness at&nbsp;which straight lines ascend or descend is called<br>\r\n		the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">slope</span>. &nbsp;The slope&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;is the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">ratio</span> of the change in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> values to<br>\r\n		a&nbsp;given change in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> values.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In terms of two arbitrary points&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\\\ P_1\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">with coordinates&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb {x_1};\\PalAa{y_1})\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P_2\\)</span>, with coordinates <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb {x_2};\\PalAa{y_2})\\)</span>, on the straight line, we can write:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{slope} = a = \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{y_2-y_1}}{\\PalAb{x_2-x_1}} \\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is depicted in the following figure:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/113.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Now it is clear that:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is a measure of the steepness of a straight line.&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The greater the change in&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>&nbsp;</em><span class=\"BodyText\">for a given change in&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span></em><span class=\"BodyText\">, the steeper the line.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We also know that:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\" style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a&gt;0\\)</span>,&nbsp;</span></span><span class=\"BodyText\">then the line is ascending&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\" style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">from left to right.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a&lt;0\\)</span>, th</span><span class=\"BodyText\">en the line is descending</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;from left to right.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(551,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The general equation for a straight line or linear function is:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax+b\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: right;\">where</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">is the intercept on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: right;\">and</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">is the slope of the line.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercept is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{a};0\\right)\\)</span>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercept is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((0;b)\\)</span>.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The formula for the slope <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> in terms of two points <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_1;y_1)\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_2;y_2)\\)</span> on the line is:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=\\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Special cases</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 20%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax\\)</span></span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The constant term&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>&nbsp;is zero.<br>\r\n		The line passes through the origin.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 20%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=b\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The case of a zero valued slope.<br>\r\n		Straight line parallel to the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis through any point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x;b)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 20%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=c\\)</span></span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The case of an undefined slope.<br>\r\n		Straight line parallel to the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis through any point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((c;y)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 20%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Parallel lines</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Two or more straight lines.<br>\r\n		The slopes of the lines are the same.<br>\r\n		The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercepts of the lines are different.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(552,'Instructions','\r\n<div id=\"course_code\">FBN1502\r\n</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Exercise instructions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Do an exercise to test your knowledge on linear functions. &nbsp;Make sure&nbsp;you understand the calculations before you proceed to&nbsp;the next learning unit. &nbsp;This exercise does not contribute towards your semester mark or&nbsp;final mark. It is for exercise purposes only.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Instructions</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Fill in the correct answer for each question.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">After completing all the questions, click&nbsp;the &#39;<span class=\"PalAa\">Check answers</span>&#39;&nbsp;button to obtain your&nbsp;score.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Aim to achieve&nbsp;at least&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;for the exercise before looking at the solutions.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If you scored less than&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\%\\)</span>, click&nbsp;the &#39;<span class=\"PalAa\">Clear</span>&#39;&nbsp;button to clear your previous selections.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Answer the questions again and click the &#39;<span class=\"PalAa\">Check answers</span>&#39; button.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If you scored&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;or more, click&nbsp;the &#39;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Show calculations</span>&#39;&nbsp;button&nbsp;</span></span>to see the solutions.</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">When you are done, click&nbsp;the &#39;<span class=\"PalAa\">Continue</span>&#39;&nbsp;button to<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;access the assignment questions.</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">After completing the assignment questions, proceed to&nbsp;the next&nbsp;learning unit.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(553,'Two points','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Determine the equation of a straight line using two points</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The general equation for a straight line is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = \\PalBb ax + \\PalBc b \\)</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;with the slope as&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb a= \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb{y_2-y_1}}{\\PalAa{x_2-x_1}} \\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;for any two&nbsp;</span>points.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">With this&nbsp;knowledge on straight lines, we are able to determine the specific equation for the straight line passing through two given points.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Method to determine equation</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Use general equation for a straight line&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = \\PalBb ax + \\PalBc b \\)</span>&nbsp;and the slope&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\