pe=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute point in equation</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa 3)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalBb 2(\\PalAb 1) + \\PalBc b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate and simplify</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa3\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalBb2\\times\\PalAb1 + \\PalBc b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2+\\PalBc b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2+\\PalBc b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substract <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-2\\)</span>&nbsp;both sides</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2-2+\\PalBc b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3-2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Value of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc b\\)</span>&nbsp;is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc b\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc1\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc b=\\PalBc 1\\)</span>&nbsp;into the equation</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalBb 2x + (\\PalBc 1)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the equation of the line is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalBb 2x + \\PalBc 1\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equation for the line passing through the two points <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1;3)\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((3;7)\\)</span>&nbsp;is therefore&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=2x+1\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><strong>Not</strong><strong>e</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It does not matter which point we call <span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_1 ; y_1)\\)</span></span> and which&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_2 ; y_2)\\)</span></span>. &nbsp;Had we numbered them the other way around above we would have found that&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_1 ; y_1) = (3; 7)\\)</span></span> and <span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_2 ; y_2) = (1; 3)\\)</span></span>. &nbsp;The slope would be still be&nbsp;calculated as before:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb a=\\displaystyle\\frac{3-7}{1-3}=\\displaystyle\\frac{-4}{-2}=\\PalBb2\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We could also just as well have used the point <span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((3; 7)\\)</span></span>&nbsp;instead of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1;3)\\)</span>&nbsp;to find the value of <span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc b\\)</span></span>. &nbsp;Using point&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((3; 7)\\)</span>, we would calculate the value of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc b\\)</span>&nbsp;as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} 7&amp;=2\\times3+\\PalBc b \\\\ 7&amp;=6+\\PalBc b \\\\ 7-6&amp;=6+\\PalBc b-6 \\\\ \\PalBc b&amp;=\\PalBc1 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(554,'Word problems','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Word problems</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Straight line graphs can be used to describe how a lot of things behave in real life. &nbsp;In many cases the two points which you require to draw the line are not given to you, but you must unravel them from the information given.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example question</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Betty&#39;s Phone Service has been calling you to join their service to enjoy low rates. With her plan, for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span> minutes of use per week, you pay <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur90\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;If you use <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(152\\)</span> minutes, your weekly charge is only <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur159\\Cdp00\\)</span>. The weekly charge is a linear function of the number of minutes you use per week</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Determine the equation for the straight line that describes this linear relationship.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The weekly charge is a linear function of the number of minutes used per week.&nbsp;Therefore, the charge per week depends on the number of minutes used per week:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y =f (\\PalAb x) = \\PalBb a\\PalAb x + \\PalBc b\\)</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 20%;\">where</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">dependent</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;variable</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 20%;\">and</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">independent</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;variable.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">Therefore, let</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">represent the <span class=\"PalAb\">number of minutes</span> you use per week</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\">and</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">represent the <span class=\"PalAa\">weekly charge</span> in rands.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following data&nbsp;for&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em>&nbsp;is&nbsp;given:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Number of minutes&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {=x}\\)</span>&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Weekly charge</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {=y}\\)</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 18%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(60\\)</span>&nbsp;minutes</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur90\\Cdp00\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 18%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(152\\)</span>&nbsp;minutes</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur159\\Cdp00\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore, t<span class=\"BodyText\">he two data points that satisfy the linear relationship are&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((60; 90)\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((152; 159)\\)</span>. &nbsp;We need to determine the equation of the straight line that passes through these two points.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Taking <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb {x_1};\\PalAa{y_1})= (\\PalAb{60}; \\PalAa{90})\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb {x_2}; \\PalAa{y_2}) =(\\PalAb{152}; \\PalAa{159})\\)</span>, we can calculate the slope <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb a\\)</span>&nbsp;of the straight line as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\begin{align} \\PalBb a &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{y_2-y_1}}{\\PalAb{x_2-x_1}} \\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{159-90}} {\\PalAb{152-60}}\\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{69}{92} &amp; \\left({\\displaystyle\\frac{\\displaystyle\\div23}{\\displaystyle\\div23}}\\right) \\\\ &amp;=\\PalBb{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The general equation thus reduces to:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=\\PalBb{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}}\\PalAb x+\\PalBc b \\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute the&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span> </em>and&nbsp;<em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em>&nbsp;values of the first point&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{60}; \\PalAa{90})\\)</span>&nbsp;in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=\\PalBb{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}}\\PalAb x+\\PalBc b \\)</span></span><span class=\"BodyText\">. This gives:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa y&amp;=\\PalBb{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}}\\PalAb x+\\PalBc b \\\\ \\PalAa{90}&amp;=\\PalBb{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}}\\times\\PalAb{60}+\\PalBc b \\\\ \\PalAa{90}&amp;=45+\\PalBc b \\\\\\PalAa{90}-45&amp;=45-45+\\PalBc b &amp; \\text{(subtract 45 both sides)} \\\\\\PalBc b&amp;=90-45 \\\\\\PalBc b&amp;=45 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The equation for the line passing through the two points <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((60; 90)\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((152; 159)\\)</span>&nbsp;is therefore&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=\\PalBb{\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}}\\PalAb x+\\PalBc {45} \\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Answer</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equation for the straight line that describes the&nbsp;linear relationship is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\( y={\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{4}} x+{45} \\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(555,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine the equation of the following straight line:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/125.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Identify any two points on the line.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>For this example we select&nbsp;two sets of points, namely</span> Set&nbsp;A&nbsp;and Set&nbsp;B.<span> &nbsp;Note that it is not necessary to use two sets of points. It is done to show that there wi</span>ll be&nbsp;only one value for the slope, no matter which two points on the line are chosen.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Set A</span>:&nbsp;Take&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_1;y_1) = (0 ; 0) \\)</span><span style=\"line-height: 27px;\">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_2;y_2)\\)</span><span style=\"line-height: 27px;\">&nbsp;=&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-3 ; 6)\\)</span><span>.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Set B</span>:&nbsp;Take&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_1;y_1) = (-2 ; 4) \\)</span><span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_2;y_2) = (-1 ; 2)\\)</span><span>.</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine the slope&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;by substituting the two identified&nbsp;points into&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a = \\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} \\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The slope for&nbsp;<span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Set A</span>&nbsp;is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} a &amp; = \\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} \\\\ &amp; = \\displaystyle\\frac{6-0}{-3-0} \\\\ &amp; = \\displaystyle\\frac{6}{-3} \\\\ &amp; =-2 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The slope for&nbsp;<span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Set B</span>&nbsp;is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} a &amp; = \\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} \\\\ &amp; = \\displaystyle\\frac{2-4}{-1--2} \\\\ &amp; = \\displaystyle\\frac{-2}{1} \\\\ &amp; =-2 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that for both sets of points&nbsp;the calculated slope is the same. &nbsp;The general equation of a straight line <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = ax + b\\)</span>&nbsp;is thus reduced&nbsp;to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = -2x + b\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine the constant&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>&nbsp;by substituting any of the two identified points into the equation&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = -2x + b\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substituting the point&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-3;6)\\)</span>&nbsp;from <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Set A</span> gives:</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} y &amp; = - 2 x + b \\\\ 6 &amp; =-2(-3)+b \\\\ 6 &amp; =6+b \\\\ b &amp; =6-6 \\\\ b &amp; =0 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substituting the point&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-1;2)\\)</span>&nbsp;from <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Set B</span> gives:</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} y &amp; = - 2 x + b \\\\ 2 &amp; =-2\\times(-1)+b \\\\ 2 &amp; =2+b \\\\ b &amp; =2-2 \\\\ b &amp; =0 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that for both sets of points&nbsp;the calculated constant <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>&nbsp;is the same. &nbsp;The general equation thus reduces to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = -2x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note also that this step was actually not required. &nbsp;This is because, for a straight line passing&nbsp;through the origin, the value of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>&nbsp;will <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">always</span> be equal to zero.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equation for the line passing through the two points&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((0; 0)\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-3; 6)\\)</span>&nbsp;and through the two points&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-2; 4)\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-1; 2)\\)</span>&nbsp;is therefore:</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = -2x + 0\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = -2x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(556,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equation for a straight line can be determined by using two points on the line, or by using changes in the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>- and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-values. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Using changes in the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>- and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-values is the&nbsp;easier way.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Method using changes in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>- and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-values</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Start with the general equation for a straight line <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax+b\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>, that is the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercept of the line, where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=0\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine whether the slope <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;has a positive or negative value. &nbsp;The slope is positive if the line ascends and negative if the line descends.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Choose any two points on the line. &nbsp;Calculate the slope as the change in y-value divided by the change in x-value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text {change in }y\\text{-value}}{\\text {change in }x\\text{-value}}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute the values of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span> into the general equation for a straight line <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax+b\\)</span>&nbsp;to obtain the specific equation for the line.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine the&nbsp;equation for the straight line in the following graph:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/126.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The general equation for the line is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = ax + b\\)</span>. &nbsp;Since the line goes through the origin, the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercept is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span>, therefore <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=0\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So in this case the equation becomes&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>The&nbsp;</span>slope&nbsp;will be&nbsp;negative&nbsp;<span>because the line descends when you move from left to right on the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis. &nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>So, we know&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;will have a negative value.</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Take any two points on the line, such as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-1;2)\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((-3;6)\\)</span>&nbsp;as indicated on the graph. Calculate the slope&nbsp;<span>as&nbsp;</span>the change in&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-value divided by the change in&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-value.<span>&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text {change in }y\\text{-value}}{\\text {change in }x\\text{-value}} = \\displaystyle\\frac{6-2}{-3-(-1)}=\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{-3+1}=\\displaystyle\\frac{4}{-2}=-2\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=-2\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=0\\)</span>&nbsp;into the general equation for a straight line <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = ax + b\\)</span>. </span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The equation for the straight line is therefore <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=-2x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(557,'Horizontal','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Special case&nbsp;when <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=0\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If the slope of a line is zero, then <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> does not increase, no matter how much <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> increases. How does the&nbsp;zero slope of a line&nbsp;affect&nbsp;the&nbsp;line&#39;s equation and graph?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">A line with zero slope is perfectly flat in the horizontal direction.<br>\r\n		No matter what value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> you have, you get the same <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-value.<br>\r\n		It does not increase or decrease.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Most of the time&nbsp;we think of slope as the amount that <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> changes when <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> changes some amount. Say you are riding your bicycle along a straight path. Suppose that you are not a very experienced cyclist and do not want to break too much of a sweat. Without actually riding downhill, the easiest ride would obviously be on a perfectly flat road. So, what you want is to ascend zero metres, no matter how far you ride. Your bike ride would look&nbsp;something like this:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/29.svg\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Say you ride a distance of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\)</span>&nbsp;kilometre or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span> metres on this flat road. The slope is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 37%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{ \\text{change in } y}{ \\text{change in }x}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 37%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 37%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{0}{1\\Tsp000-0}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 37%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{0}{1\\Tsp000} \\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 37%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The slope is zero, meaning there is no slope at all. You rise not one centimetre no matter how far you ride your bike.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">The important thing to notice is that <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">zero slope</span> means <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">horizontal</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(558,'Through origin','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Special case when <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=0\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the special&nbsp;case for which the constant term is zero, that is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=0\\)</span>.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A straight line <span><em><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax+b\\)</span></span></em></span> has slope <em><span><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></span></span></em> and <em><span><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></span></span></em>-intercept <em><span><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span></span></span></em>. If a straight line passes through the origin,&nbsp;then its <em><span><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></span></span></em>-intercept&nbsp;is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span>, that means <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=0\\)</span>.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The equation of a straight line passing through the origin<br>\r\n		is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax\\)</span>&nbsp;where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> is the slope of the line.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/124.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">This means that the intercept on the <em><span><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span></span></span></em>-axis is also zero</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(559,'Examples','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When a line with zero slope is graphed, the result is a horizontal line. &nbsp;One thing to be aware of is that horizontal lines can be at different </span><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">heights</span><span class=\"BodyText\">. &nbsp;For example, in the sketch below you see three horizontal lines. In each case&nbsp;the slope is zero:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/129.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Notice&nbsp;the equations of the lines on the left-hand side of the sketch. &nbsp;They are all similar in that they all look like <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = \\text{some value}\\)</span>. &nbsp;Just like a flat road, a horizontal line does not progress, or change, in the vertical,&nbsp;or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>, direction. &nbsp;Every point on the line has the same <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>&nbsp;value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/130.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note the horizontal line in the sketch above. &nbsp;The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate of every point on the&nbsp;horizontal line is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>. &nbsp;The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate can have any value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(560,'Slope','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Slope</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The general equation for a straight line is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = ax + b\\)</span>. &nbsp;When the slope of the line is zero, the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> is zero. &nbsp;This causes the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;to drop out of the equation altogether. &nbsp;The equation of the line then becomes&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=b\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Equation of a straight line with slope&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The expression for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;becomes:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{0}{x_2-x_1} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The numerator (top part) of the fraction&nbsp;can only be equal to zero if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y_2=y_1\\)</span></span>. &nbsp;That is, if the&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">function values (values for&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">) are the same. &nbsp;In this case the value of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is not dependent on&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">. &nbsp;It is&nbsp;a constant. &nbsp;The equation of the line becomes:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(ax+b\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\times x+b\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is represented by a straight line parallel to the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis, which is a horizontal line.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/131.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The expression for this line is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = b\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;where&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is the&nbsp;intercept<br>\r\n		&nbsp;on the&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></em><span class=\"BodyText\">-axis. &nbsp;There is no intercept on the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">-axis.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(561,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on the special case of a straight line parallel to the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/296.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(562,'Examples','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Special case of straight line parallel to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis: Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When a line with undefined slope is drawn, it will look vertical, just like a steep cliff. &nbsp;The sketch below shows three vertical lines, all with undefined (infinite) slope.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/134.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Notice that all the lines have similar equations in that they all look like <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\text{some value}\\)</span>. &nbsp;Just like a vertical cliff face, a vertical line does not progress, or change,&nbsp;in the horizontal, or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>, direction. &nbsp;Every point on the line has the same <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/135.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note the vertical line in the sketch above. &nbsp;The&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of every point on the&nbsp;vertical line is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>. &nbsp;The&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate can have any value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(563,'Slope','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Special case of straight line parallel to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis: Slope</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/136.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the vertical line above. &nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">The general equation for a straight line is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y = ax + b\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">. &nbsp;S</span><span class=\"BodyText\">uppose&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_1 ;y_1)\\)</span> and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x_2 ;y_2)\\)</span> are two points on the vertical line above.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In this case we would have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_2 = x_1 \\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;would become:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{y_2-y_1}{0} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Division by zero is not defined. &nbsp;We say that the slope becomes infinite and the line is vertical.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The equation for this line is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x = c\\)</span>&nbsp;where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\)</span>&nbsp;is the&nbsp;intercept<br>\r\n		on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis. &nbsp;There is no intercept on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(564,'Special case: Parallel lines','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Special case of parallel lines</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the special case when two straight lines have the same slope but different <span class=\"Emphasis_1\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span></span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercepts.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Parallel lines are lines that will go on and on forever without ever intersecting. &nbsp;This is because they have the same slope. &nbsp;If you have two lines that have the same slope but different <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercepts, then these lines are parallel to each&nbsp;other.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When two parallel lines are drawn, they must always have the same slope&nbsp;or steepness. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The two lines shown in the graph below are equally steep. &nbsp;They decrease, or slope downward, at the same rate. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/139.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The straight lines <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}x + 4 \\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}x + 2\\)</span>&nbsp;have the same slope, namely&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}\\)</span>, but different intercepts on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis, namely <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>&nbsp;respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Consider two points, one on each of the lines, with&nbsp;the same </span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span><span>-coordinate, namely <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>. &nbsp;To obtain the vertical distance between the two lines, subtract&nbsp;the </span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span><span>-coordinate of the point on the lower line&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(y=-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}x + 2\\right)\\)</span>&nbsp;from the </span><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></em><span>-coordinate of the point on the upper line&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(y=-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}x + 4\\right) \\)</span>:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p>Vertical distance</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 28%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></em><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"BodyText\">-coordinate of&nbsp;<br>\r\n		point on upper line</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">\r\n		<p><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-coordinate of&nbsp;<br>\r\n		point on lower line</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 20%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(\\PalAa{-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}x + 4}\\right)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left(\\PalAb{-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2}x + 2}\\right)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 35%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2} x +4 + \\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2} x -2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"width: 35%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4-2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"width: 35%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This indicates that the vertical distance between the two lines does not depend on the value of <em><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span></em>, it is a constant value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/140.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"line-height: 21.6000003814697px;\">As can be seen in the graph&nbsp;above, no matter what the value of&nbsp;</span><em style=\"line-height: 21.6000003814697px;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span></em><span style=\"line-height: 21.6000003814697px;\">&nbsp;is, the vertical distance between these specific two lines will always be&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span><span style=\"line-height: 21.6000003814697px;\">.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:05','2017-10-11 12:27:05','',NULL),(565,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Not many people can afford to buy a house or brand new car for cash. &nbsp;Most of us have to borrow money from a bank to make such a big purchase. &nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">We usually repay such a loan to the bank over a long period of time in fixed payments which include interest on the amount still owed to the bank.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The loan is said to be amortised when all liabilities,&nbsp;that is both the principal (the amount of the loan) and interest, are paid by a sequence of equal payments made at equal intervals of time.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Typical questions that we may ask about this process are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">What should the amount of the equal payments be?</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">What is the remaining value of the loan still to be repaid at any stage during its repayment? &nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">What is the total interest payable on the loan?</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>These may sound like difficult questions to answer, but if you consider that this way of paying back a loan is just&nbsp;an ordinary annuity, the good news is that you already have the tools&nbsp;to answer these questions!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:06','2017-10-11 12:27:06','',NULL),(566,'Period and payments','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Period and payments</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A mortgage of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 200 \\Tsp 000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>&nbsp;has to be amortised in monthly payments at an interest rate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\%\\)</span> per year, compounded monthly. &nbsp;Four periods for repaying the loan were considered: <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(25\\)</span>&nbsp;years.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The table below shows how much interest you would have to pay depending on the monthly payment and amortisation period chosen.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 16%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Amortisation<br>\r\n		per