an></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 600 \\Cdp 00\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Present value of loan is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;\\text{price of television}\\:-\\:\\text{deposit}\\\\ &amp;=\\:\\Cur 8 \\Tsp 000 \\Cdp 00-\\Cur 600 \\Cdp 00\\\\ &amp;=\\:\\Cur 7 \\Tsp400 \\Cdp 00 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The present value of the loan is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 7 \\Tsp400 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>. &nbsp;This is the amount that he borrows after the deposit is&nbsp;subtracted.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Jonathan purchases an apartment by making a down payment of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 40 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span> and obtains a <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span>&nbsp;year loan for the balance of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 280 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span> at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\%\\)</span> per annum, compounded monthly. &nbsp;What is the price of the apartment and the present value of the loan?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Deposit is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 40 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Price of apartment is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;\\text{present value of loan}\\:+\\:\\text{deposit}\\\\ &amp;=\\:\\Cur 280 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00+\\Cur 40 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\\\ &amp;=\\:\\Cur 320 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The price of the apartment is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 320 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>. &nbsp;He has&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 40 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>&nbsp;which he uses&nbsp;as a deposit and he&nbsp;borrows&nbsp;the rest, namely&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 280 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>.&nbsp;&nbsp;The present value of the loan is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 280 \\Tsp000 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>. &nbsp;This is the amount that he borrows after the deposit is&nbsp;subtracted.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example 3</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Sam wants to buy a new fridge for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 6 \\Tsp500 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>. &nbsp;He agrees to pay a deposit of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(15\\%\\)</span> of the price&nbsp;and a monthly&nbsp;instalment for one year at an interest rate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(11\\%\\)</span> per annum, compounded&nbsp;monthly. &nbsp;What is&nbsp;the amount he&nbsp;borrows? In other words, what is the present value of the loan?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Price of fridge is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 6 \\Tsp500 \\Cdp 00\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Deposit is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;15\\%\\: \\text{of}\\:\\Cur 6 \\Tsp500 \\Cdp 00\\\\ &amp;=\\:\\frac{15}{100}\\times\\Cur 6 \\Tsp500 \\Cdp 00\\\\ &amp;=\\:0.15\\times\\Cur 6 \\Tsp500 \\Cdp 00\\\\&amp;=\\:\\Cur 975 \\Cdp 00 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">He will pay a deposit of</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 975 \\Cdp 00\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Present value of loan is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;\\text{price of fridge}\\:-\\:\\text{deposit}\\\\ &amp;=\\:\\Cur 6 \\Tsp500 \\Cdp 00-\\Cur 975 \\Cdp 00\\\\ &amp;=\\:\\Cur 5 \\Tsp525 \\Cdp 00 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The present value of the loan is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur 5 \\Tsp525 \\Cdp 00\\)</span>. &nbsp;This is the amount that he borrows after the deposit is subtracted.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:06','2017-10-11 12:27:06','',NULL),(573,'Fixed or variable?','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Fixed or variable?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A loan can have a fixed interest rate or a variable interest rate.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Variable interest rate</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A <span class=\"PalAa\">variable interest rate</span> loan is a loan in which the interest rate charged on the outstanding balance varies as&nbsp;market interest rates <span class=\"PalAa\">change</span>. &nbsp;As a result, your payments will vary as well, if&nbsp;your payments&nbsp;consist of&nbsp;a blend of&nbsp;principal and interest payments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Fixed interest rate</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Fixed interest rate loans are loans in which the <span class=\"PalAa\">interest rate</span> charged on the loan will <span class=\"PalAa\">remain fixed</span> for that&nbsp;loan&#39;s entire term, no matter what market interest rates do. &nbsp;This will result in your payments being the&nbsp;same over the entire term. &nbsp;If interest rates fall, you do not stand to benefit as your rates remain fixed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Whether a fixed-rate loan is better for you will depend on the interest rate environment when the loan is&nbsp;taken out and on the duration of the loan.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Interest rates: Fixed or variable?</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When a loan is fixed for its entire term, it will be fixed at the prevailing market <span class=\"PalAa\">interest rate</span> at the time the loan is taken out. &nbsp;Generally&nbsp;speaking, if interest rates are relatively low, but are about to increase, then it will be better to lock&nbsp;in your loan at that fixed rate. &nbsp;Depending on the terms of your agreement, your interest rate on the new&nbsp;loan will remain fixed, even if <span class=\"PalAa\">interest rates</span> climb to higher levels. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">On the other hand, if interest rates&nbsp;are on the decline, then it would be better to have a variable rate loan. As interest rates fall, so will the&nbsp;interest rate on your loan.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This discussion is simplistic, but the explanation will not change in a more complicated situation. &nbsp;It is&nbsp;important to note that studies have found that over time, the borrower is likely to pay less interest overall&nbsp;with a variable rate loan versus a fixed rate loan. &nbsp;However, the borrower must consider the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">amortisation </span>period of a loan. &nbsp;The longer the <span class=\"PalAa\">amortisation </span>period of a loan, the greater the impact a&nbsp;change in interest rates will have on your payments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, <span class=\"PalAa\">variable interest rate loans</span> are beneficial for a borrower in a decreasing interest rate environment,&nbsp;but when interest rates rise, loan payments will rise sharply.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:06','2017-10-11 12:27:06','',NULL),(574,'Video - Part A','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video - Part A</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the first part of this video on calculating payments when interest rates change:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/79.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:06','2017-10-11 12:27:06','',NULL),(575,'Video - Part B','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video - Part B</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch the second part of this video on calculating payments when interest rates change:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/80.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:06','2017-10-11 12:27:06','',NULL),(576,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Amortisation</span> is the process of gradually reducing a debt through instalment payments of principal&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">and&nbsp;interest.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The loan is said to be <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">amortised</span> when all liabilities, that is both the principal (the amount of&nbsp;the loan)&nbsp;and interest, are paid by a sequence of equal payments made at equal intervals of time.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The size of the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">payments</span> is calculated by using the formula for the present value of an annuity.<br>\r\n<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>&nbsp;is known and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(R\\)</span> must be calculated:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(R=P\\times\\left[ \\displaystyle\\frac{i(1+i)^n}{(1+i)^n-1} \\right]\\)</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">amortisation schedule</span> is a table indicating the distribution of each payment in regard to&nbsp;interest&nbsp;and principal reduction. &nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">The table has five columns:</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 20%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Column 1</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Payment interval</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Column 2</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Outstanding principal at beginning of payment interval</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Column 3</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Simple interest due at end of payment interval</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Column 4</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Payment</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Column 5</span></th>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">Principal repaid at end of payment interval</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Interest rates</span> change from time to time. &nbsp;If the interest rate changes, the payments change accordingly. &nbsp;After the change in interest rate, the present value is recalculated for&nbsp;the&nbsp;remaining period of time. &nbsp;The size of the payments is also recalculated according to the new&nbsp;interest rate.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:06','2017-10-11 