ibute towards your semester mark and final mark.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">All the assignment questions for&nbsp;the relevant topics can be accessed once all the relevant learning units of the topics have been&nbsp;completed.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The assignment&nbsp;has to be submitted online via myUnisa.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Refer to the tutorial letter&nbsp;for more information about the assignment.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The assignment&nbsp;consists of multiple choice questions.</span></li>\r\n<li>Click&nbsp;the &#39;Continue&#39;&nbsp;button to<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;access the assignment questions following&nbsp;the s</span>imple interest<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;learning unit.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(669,'Information','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Assignment information</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"BodyText\">\r\n<li>The&nbsp;a<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">ssignment questions following the t</span>ime value of money<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;learning unit&nbsp;contribute towards your semester mark and final mark.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">All the assignment questions for&nbsp;the relevant topics can be accessed once all the relevant learning units of the topics have been&nbsp;completed.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The assignment&nbsp;has to be submitted online via myUnisa.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Refer to the tutorial letter&nbsp;for more information about the assignment.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The assignment&nbsp;consists of multiple choice questions.</span></li>\r\n<li>Click&nbsp;the &#39;Continue&#39;&nbsp;button to<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;access the assignment questions following&nbsp;the t</span>ime value of money<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&nbsp;learning unit.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(670,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">A rand received today is worth more than a rand received at some time in the future because&nbsp;it can be invested to earn interest.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Mathematics of finance deals with dated values of money:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">To move money <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">forward</span>, inflate the relevant sum by multiplying by the accumulation factor&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1+i)^n\\)</span>.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">To move money <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">backward</span>, deflate the relevant sum by multiplying by the accumulation factor&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1+i)^{-n}\\)</span>.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">When one set of financial obligations is replaced of with another equivalent set, the rules for moving money back and forward is applied. &nbsp;Each obligation and payment is evaluated in terms of the new due date. &nbsp;At the new due date all the obligations are set equal to all the payments.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(671,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Interest is the price paid for the use of borrowed money.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Simple interest implies the following:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">You make <span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"PalAa\">one </span></span>investment and leave it to gain the <span class=\"PalAa\">same </span>amount of interest per year,&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">you borrow <span class=\"PalAa\">one</span> amount of money which accumulates the <span class=\"PalAa\">same </span>amount of interest per year.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The formulas used for simple interest are:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=Pin\\)</span>,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P+I\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">and</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P\\times(1+in)\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">where</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I\\)</span></span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the simple interest (in rand) paid for the use of the money at the end of the term;&nbsp;</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the principal, or total amount borrowed (in rand) which is subject to interest. &nbsp;</span><span>This is also known as the present value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((PV)\\)</span> of the loan;</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the accumulated sum (in rand). This is also known as the future value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((FV)\\)</span> of the loan;</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span></span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the rate of interest, that is the fraction of the principal which must be paid at the end&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">of each period (for example, each year) for the use of the principal;</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">and</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span></span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the term or time, that is the number of periods for which the principal is borrowed.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Sometimes the above formulas are rearranged in order to obtain formulas for each variable&nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">respectively. &nbsp;It is called changing the subject of the formula.</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(672,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">For a discount loan the interest and any other related charges are calculated and paid at the time the loan is granted.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The borrower <span class=\"PalAa\">receives </span>the reduced amount, called the <span class=\"PalAa\">present </span>value, and must <span class=\"PalAa\">repay </span>the face&nbsp;value or <span class=\"PalAa\">future </span>value of the discount loan.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The formulas used for simple discount are:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 23%; text-align: right; vertical-align: bottom;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: left; vertical-align: bottom;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} D&amp;=S\\PalBc d\\PalAb n\\\\ P&amp;=S-D&amp;\\text{and}\\\\ P&amp;=S\\times(1-\\PalBc d\\PalAb n) \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">where</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 8%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the simple discount (in rand) paid for the use of the money at the beginning of the term,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the present value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((PV)\\)</span> of the loan,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the face or future value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((FV)\\)</span> of the loan,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc d\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the discount rate, that is the fraction of the future value to be paid at the beginning&nbsp;of the period, and</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb n\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the term of the loan.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(673,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Profit</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Profit is a very important concept for any business.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">profit <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span> <span class=\"PalCd\">total revenue</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Marginal profit</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Marginal profit is the profit that would be made by producing and selling one additional unit of a&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">product or service. Therefore, </span><span class=\"BodyText\">the formula for the extra unit can be written as:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalCd\">marginal revenue</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Marginal profit, marginal revenue and&nbsp;marginal cost</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalCd\">marginal revenue</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&gt;\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, then&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">positive</span>.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalCd\">marginal revenue</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt;\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, then&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">negative</span><span class=\"BodyText\">.</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalCd\">marginal revenue</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, then&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">zero</span><span class=\"BodyText\">.</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Profit maximisation</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Profit maximization is the process by which a firm determines the price and output level that&nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">returns the greatest profit.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">To find the maximum profit, let the <span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span> equal <span class=\"PalBa\">zero</span>, that is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\'(x)=0\\)</span>, and solve for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>. &nbsp;At&nbsp;the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-value where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\'(x)=0\\)</span>, profit is maximised.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(674,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Total cost, fixed cost and variable cost</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Cost is a very important factor in determining the success of a company.&nbsp;&nbsp;Suppose you have the linear&nbsp;total cost function:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{TC}=\\PalBc{40}+\\PalAb{5q}\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The total cost is calculated as:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\text{total cost}}=\\PalBc{\\text{fixed cost}}+\\PalAb{\\text{variable cost}}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The <span class=\"PalAb\">variable cost</span> is calculated as:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\text{variable cost to produce single unit}\\times\\text{number of units produced}= 5\\times q\\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Marginal cost</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> is a function of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{TC}=\\PalAa{f(x)} &amp;&amp; \\text{or}&amp;&amp;\\PalAa{TC}=\\PalAa{C(x)} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Then the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> is equivalent to the derivative of the total cost function:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalBb{MC}=\\PalBb{f\'(x)} &amp;&amp; \\text{or}&amp;&amp;\\PalBb{MC}=\\PalBb{C\'(x)} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">When to use marginal costing</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Marginal cost will be used to determine the change in the total cost which results from producing&nbsp;one additional unit.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Through marginal costing we can ascertain whether our cost of production is rising, falling or constant&nbsp;and thus it helps in formation of a strategic plan for the business.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Marginal cost and exact cost</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{C(x)}\\)</span>&nbsp;is the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> of producing <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> items, the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> function approximates the exact cost&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">of producing the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x+1)^{\\text{st}}\\)</span>&nbsp;item:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalBb{\\text{marginal cost}}&amp;\\approx \\text{exact cost}\\\\ \\PalBb{C\'(x)}&amp;\\approx C(x+1)-C(x) \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(675,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">A <span class=\"BodyTex\">system</span> of linear inequalities is a set of linear inequalities whose common&nbsp;solutions are looked for.<br>\r\n&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li>The <span class=\"BodyTex\">steps for graphing</span> systems of inequalities are:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Graph the boundary line for the first inequality.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Use a test point to determine which half plane to shade.<br>\r\n		Shade the half plane that contains the solutions to the first inequality.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Graph the boundary line for the second inequality.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Use a test point to determine which half plane to shade.<br>\r\n		Shade the half plane that contains the solutions to the second inequality.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 5</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Do this for all the inequalities.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 6</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Analyse your system of inequalities and determine which area is shaded by the solution spaces of <span class=\"BodyTex\">all</span> the inequalities. &nbsp;This area is the solution for the system of inequalities.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 7</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Any point that satisfied all the inequalities at once will be in the area of this overlap.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If the inequality symbol is <span class=\"PalAb\">greater than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((&gt;)\\)</span> or <span class=\"PalAb\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((&lt;)\\)</span>, then you will use a <span class=\"PalAb\">dashed</span> boundary&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">line. &nbsp;This means that the solutions are <span class=\"PalAb\">not</span> included on the boundary line.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">If the inequality symbol is <span class=\"PalAa\">greater than or equal to</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\geq)\\)</span> or <span class=\"PalAa\">less than or equal to</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\leq)\\)</span>, then you will&nbsp;use a <span class=\"PalAa\">solid line</span> to indicate that the solutions are included on the boundary line.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>If the solution space for the system continues forever in at least one direction, it is called an&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyTex\">unbounded solution</span>.<br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>If the solution space for the system has lines on all sides, it is called a <span class=\"BodyTex\">closed</span> or <span class=\"BodyTex\">bounded solution</span>.<br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>If the solution spaces for the individual lines do not overlap, the system has <span class=\"BodyTex\">no solution</span>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(676,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Many simple inequalities can be <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">solved</span> using the techniques of adding, subtracting, multiplying&nbsp;or dividing both sides of the inequality until you are left with the variable on its own.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">We discussed the following <span class=\"BodyText\">rules</span>:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 17%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\PalAa&gt;a\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\PalAb&lt;b\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 17%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\PalAa&gt;a\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">and if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\PalAa&gt;c\\)</span>,</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">then <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\PalAa&gt;c\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 17%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\PalAa&gt;a\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">then <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b+c\\PalAa&gt;a+c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">for any <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 17%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\PalAa&gt;a\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">then <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\times c\\PalAa &gt;a\\times c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\div c\\PalAa&gt;a\\div c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">for any <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\PalAa&gt;0\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 17%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\PalAa&gt;a\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\times c\\PalAb&lt;a\\times c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\div c \\PalAb&lt; a \\div c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\">for any&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\PalAb &lt;0\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 17%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 30%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If you multiply or divide both sides of an inequality by a negative number, reverse the direction of the inequality sign.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Word problems</span>. &nbsp;</span>Sometimes the inequality is not given directly, but instead a description of a real life&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">problem is given. &nbsp;The given sentences need to be translated into an inequality.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If you want to swop the expressions on either sides of an inequality, remember to <span class=\"BodyText\">reverse</span> the&nbsp;inequality sign.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">You cannot <span class=\"BodyText\">divide</span> an inequality <span class=\"BodyText\">by a variable</span> unless you are sure of its sign since you do&nbsp;not know whether you must reverse the sign of the inequality.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(677,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">A <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">system of linear equations in two variables</span> is just a set of two or more&nbsp;equations. &nbsp;The simplest case&nbsp;is&nbsp;two linear equations in two variables. &nbsp;The graph of such a system is a pair of lines in the Cartesian plane.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">solution</span> of a system of two linear equations can be <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">classified</span> as follows:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 33%;\">No solution</th>\r\n		<td>The slopes of the lines are the same, but their<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercepts are different.<br class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		The lines are parallel.<br class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		The lines do not intersect at any point.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">One solution</th>\r\n		<td>The slopes of the lines are different.<br class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		The lines intersect at exactly one point.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">Infinitely<br>\r\n		many solutions</th>\r\n		<td>The slopes of the lines are the same, but their<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercepts are also the same.<br>\r\n		The two equations represent the same line.<br>\r\n		The lines intersect at infinitely many points.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Word problems</span>. &nbsp;Sometimes the equations are not given directly, but instead a description of a real life&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">problem is given. &nbsp;The given sentences need to be translated into more than one equation. &nbsp;If there are two unknown variables then at least two equations are needed to solve the&nbsp;variables.</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(678,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">An <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">equation</span> is a statement in which two algebraic expressions are equal.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">A <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">linear equation</span> is a simple equation of degree one, that is, the highest exponent of the unknown variable is one.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Solving a linear equation in one variable means finding the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">value of the variable</span>. &nbsp;This involves performing the same operations to both sides of an equation to maintain equality while working to isolate the variable on one side of the equation.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Given any equation, if you multiply, divide, add&nbsp;or subtract the same number on both sides, the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">equality</span> of the&nbsp;new equation will hold. &nbsp;You can also raise both sides to the same power and keep equality.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">To get the variable you are solving&nbsp;alone on one side and everything else on the other side, you use <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">inverse</span> operations.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(679,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The general equation for an <span class=\"PalAa\">exponential function</span> is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{y=f(x)=a^x}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a&gt;0\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\neq1\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> is a real constant.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{a&gt;1}\\)</span> the exponential function is an <span class=\"PalAa\">increasing</span> function of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> and&nbsp;<br>\r\nif <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{0&lt;a&lt;1}\\)</span> the exponential function is a <span class=\"PalAb\">decreasing</span> function of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Exponential functions are used to model compound interest, radioactive decay and&nbsp;various types of growth (populations, bacterial or animal).</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">An inverse function is a function that reverses another function:<br>\r\nIf the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">function</span> applied to&nbsp;an input <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span> gives a result of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span>, then applying the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">inverse function</span> to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span> gives the result of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">logarithmic function</span> is completely determined by the corresponding <span class=\"PalAa\">exponential function</span>. &nbsp;They are <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">inverse functions</span>. &nbsp;If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{f(x)=a^x=y}\\)</span> then <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\log_ay=x}\\)</span>&nbsp;with y &gt; 0.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Specific cases of&nbsp;logarithmic functions:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 22%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\log_aa=1\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is because&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^1=a\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 18%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\log_a1=0\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is because&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a^0=1\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 18%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\log_{10}y\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The base is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span> and the logarithm is called<br>\r\n		the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">common logarithm</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 18%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(ln\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The base is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(e\\)</span> and the logarithm is called<br>\r\n		the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">natural logarithm</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 18%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(lg\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The base is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span> and the logarithm is called<br>\r\n		the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">logarithm base <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span></span> in computer science.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(680,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can&nbsp;recognise, even if only intuitively, that the potential uses for the quadratic function are considerable.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is evident that they can be used to model situations in which the dependent variable is expected to&nbsp;peak,&nbsp;or&nbsp;pass through a dip, for&nbsp;some value of the independent variable,&nbsp;for example in demand, supply and profit functions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The general equation for a parabola or quadratic function is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=ax^2+bx+c\\)</span></span>&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\)</span>&nbsp;are constants and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\neq0\\)</span>.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a&gt;0\\)</span> the parabola opens upwards (smiling face) and<br>\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a&lt;0\\)</span>&nbsp;the parabola&nbsp;opens downwards (sad face).</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Changes in the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>&nbsp;affects the placement of the parabola in a horizontal shift&nbsp;(along the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis).</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Changes in the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\)</span>&nbsp;affects the placement of the parabola in a vertical shift&nbsp;(along the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis).</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The coordinates of the vertex of the parabola are&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left( \\displaystyle\\frac{-b}{2a};f\\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{-b}{2a}\\right) \\right)\\)</span>.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts (if any) are found by solving <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=0\\)</span> with</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\displaystyle\\frac{-b-\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\displaystyle\\frac{-b+\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\)</span>.<br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate of the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercept is&nbsp;<span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">&acirc;&euro;&lsaquo;</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(0)=c\\)</span>,&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">so&nbsp;the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercept has coordinates <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((0;c)\\)</span>.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The discriminant&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(d\\)</span>&nbsp;is calculated as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b^2-4ac\\)</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Specific cases of the discriminant:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 18%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(d&gt;0\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p>Two separate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts exist.<br>\r\n		The intercepts are equally far from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of vertex.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(d=0\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p>There is only one <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercept and it is also the vertex.<br>\r\n		The parabola just touches the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis at the vertex.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(d&lt;0\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p>There are no intercepts on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis.<br>\r\n		The parabola also does not touch the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The slope of a parabola is ever-changing in contrast to a straight line which has a constant slope.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(681,'Axes','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Axes of the Cartesian plane</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Compare the pictures below of the Cartesian plane as a map and the Cartesian plane as a grid. &nbsp;Note the similarities and differences.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Cartesian plane as a map</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/26.svg\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 295px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Cartesian plane as a grid</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/27.svg\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 386px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In these two pictures&nbsp;several things are different. &nbsp;Note the following differences:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">In the grid we have put arrows at the end of all the lines. &nbsp;This simply means that the grid goes on forever in all directions.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The compass directions (north, south, east and west) in the map are replaced with positive and negative numbers in the grid. &nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">East and north are positive, while west and south are negative.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Middle Street</span> on the map is now&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span> in the grid.</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> The Cartesian plane has only one vertical axis, known as the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Main Road</span> on the map is now the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span> in the grid. &nbsp;</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The Cartesian plane has only one horizontal axis,&nbsp;known as the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The Town Hall at the centre of town on the map is replaced by the&nbsp;word origin. (You need not write the word&nbsp;in when using the Cartesian plane.) It shows us that the middle point&nbsp;has a special name. This is the place you start from when finding your way through the Cartesian plane. The origin is often labelled <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span>.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">At the origin the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis perpendicularly<br>\r\n		intersect at their respective zero points.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(682,'Quadrants','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Quadrants on the Cartesian plane</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We want to represent the linear function <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)\\)</span> graphically. &nbsp;The function notation&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)\\)</span> means that <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> is a function of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>. &nbsp;The <span class=\"PalAa\">dependent</span> variable is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span> and the <span class=\"PalAb\">independent</span> variable is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A linear function is graphically represented in the Cartesian plane.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span> or horizontal axis is generally used for the <span class=\"PalAb\">independent</span> variable and the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span> or vertical axis for the <span class=\"PalAa\">dependent</span> variable. A scaled set of axes introduced in this way is referred to as a rectangular coordinate system or the Cartesian plane.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis and the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis divide the Cartesian plane into four sections. These areas are called <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">quadrants</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Quadrant 1 (the upper right hand box) is the section where both <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> are positive. &nbsp;Then we rotate counter clockwise to number the other quadrants. </span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">In Quadrant 2, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> is negative and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> is positive.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">In Quadrant 3, both <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> are negative.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">And finally, in Quadrant 4, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> is positive and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> is negative.</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"700\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/103.html\" width=\"700\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\">Quadrant</th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span><span class=\"PalAb\">-axis</span></th>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span><span class=\"PalAa\">-axis</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">1</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Positive</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Positive</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">2</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Negative</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Positive</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">3</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Negative</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Negative</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">4</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Positive</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Negative</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(683,'Summary','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Summary</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/28.svg\"></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Since most business problems deal with positive quantities, we shall be concerned mainly with points in the first quadrant. &nbsp;If&nbsp;we however regard losses as negative profits, deductions as negative additions, deficits as negative income, and so on, we shall also have the occasion to work with points in the other three quadrants.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Whenever reading&nbsp;a graph, you carefully establish the variables represented on each axis and the relevant scales.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Always label the axes clearly. Remember the variables you&nbsp;draw on the axes need not be <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>, but could be any variables, for example <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(A\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(B\\)</span> or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_1\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_2\\)</span>.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">According to the definition of a function, a function assigns one value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> to each value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> for all the values that <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> may assume. &nbsp;Thus an ordered pair of data which we can write as <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x;y)\\)</span> is established. &nbsp;Each of these pairs corresponds to a point in the plane. &nbsp;If we plotted all these points we would obtain what is called a graph of a given function.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">In other words, the graph of the function <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)\\)</span> consists of all ordered pairs <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x;y)\\)</span> which satisfy <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)\\)</span>. &nbsp;We speak of the coordinates <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x;y)\\)</span> of each point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>, and call <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> the abscissa and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> the ordinate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">It is not only points on the graph of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)\\)</span> which may be referred to in this way. &nbsp;Any point in the plane is located by the specification of an ordered pair of numbers <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((x;y)\\)</span>. &nbsp;That is in fact why we refer to a rectangular coordinate system.</span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The linear function&nbsp;is the most elementary, and perhaps the most important, of all functions.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(684,'Practical applications','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Practical applications of quadratic functions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A parabola is the curve that is produced by graphing a quadratic or second-degree equation. &nbsp;Parabolas have many practical applications.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Parabolas occur frequently in the real world. &nbsp;Consider the following examples of parabolas we can find all around us.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Suspension bridge</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The parabola can be seen most&nbsp;visibly when looking up at a suspension bridge. &nbsp;The trace formed by the cables as they suspend from the highest point to the lowest is in the shape of a parabola.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/31.jpg\" style=\"width: 640px; height: 426px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Projectile motion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">During a basketball game, the shots taken by the players trace out a parabola in the air. &nbsp;In fact, this is probably one of the most common applications of the parabola, namely the projectile motion.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/33.jpg\" style=\"width: 640px; height: 426px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Satellite dish</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In addition to the applications mentioned above, parabolic surfaces have technological applications. For example, satellite dishes are in the shape of parabolic surfaces.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/34.jpg\" style=\"width: 640px; height: 480px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Reflector</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Another technological application of the parabolic surface can be found in reflectors. &nbsp;The headlamps of your car, for example, are in this shape. &nbsp;<br>\r\nWhen you are driving on a&nbsp;dark&nbsp;road and have your brights on, it is the parabolic surface of your headlamp reflectors that enable you to see further ahead. &nbsp;The bulb is placed at a special point called the focus of the parabola. &nbsp;The light is shone from the focus and the curved surface shoots the light out of the bottom of the parabola.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/35.jpg\" style=\"width: 640px; height: 608px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(685,'Projectile motion','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Projectile motion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The appearances of parabolic shapes in the physical world are abundant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Normally&nbsp;a thrown object, like a ball, will follow a parabolic path of motion as it leaves the hand of the thrower, flies and returns to earth. &nbsp;From basketballs to high jumpers to shot puts, nearly all objects travel through the air in the same kind of path. &nbsp;This&nbsp;path is called a parabolic curve or a <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">parabola</span>. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can describe the position and speed of the&nbsp;objects&nbsp;at any point of the parabola, or at any point in time, using some simple equations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All parabolas have a common shape. An example is&nbsp;a&nbsp;stream of water from a hose, or fountain, which&nbsp;starts&nbsp;upward, curves&nbsp;as it nears the peak,&nbsp;and straightens&nbsp;out somewhat as it heads back down. &nbsp;It is the same path followed by any thrown object, but it is easiest to see with water.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the following examples of projectile motion, including the flight of a&nbsp;soccer ball, the path of a javelin, and the jump of a&nbsp;dolphin.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/36.svg\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/38.svg\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">\r\n		<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/41.svg\"></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(686,'Equation','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The equation of a quadratic function</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Parabolas are described by quadratic equations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A quadratic equation is one in which the highest power of the independent variable&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;is a square. &nbsp;The general equation of a quadratic function is where the relationship between the <span class=\"PalAa\">dependent</span> variable,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span>,&nbsp;and the <span class=\"PalAb\">independent</span> variable,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>,&nbsp;has the form:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=f(\\PalAb x)=a\\PalAb x^2+b\\PalAb x+c\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">where</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\)</span> are constants</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 20%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">and</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\neq0\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The three values&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\)</span> are also called coefficients.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A coefficient is a number used to multiply with a variable. &nbsp;For example, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3x\\)</span> means &#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span>&nbsp;times <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&#39;, so <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(3\\)</span> is a coefficient. &nbsp;In the same way, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(ax^2\\)</span> means<br>\r\n&#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;times <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x^2\\)</span>&#39;, so <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> is a coefficient.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The coefficient <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c\\)</span>&nbsp;in the quadratic equation is also called the constant.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The term <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\neq0\\)</span> means <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> may not be zero and is read as &#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;not equal to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span>&#39;. &nbsp;If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=0\\)</span>, the expression becomes:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Quadratic equation</span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa ax^2+bx+c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa a=\\PalBa 0\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalBa 0)x^2+bx+c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa 0\\times x^2+bx+c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa 0 x^2+bx+c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(bx+c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 25%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Straight line equation</span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(bx+c\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the term&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\neq0\\)</span>,&nbsp;because&nbsp;if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a=0\\)</span>, the quadratic equation becomes the equation for a straight line.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:07','2017-10-11 12:27:07','',NULL),(687,'Shape of graph','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Shape of the graph of a quadratic function</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The graph of a quadratic function is called a <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">parabola</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A parabola contains a point called a <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">vertex</span>. This is the point at which the curve turns, and is thus also known as the turning point.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p>A parabola can:</p>\r\n\r\n		<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\">\r\n		<tbody>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td><span class=\"PalAa\">open upward</span> (smiling)</td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>\r\n				<p class=\"Image\">or \r\n				<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/43.svg\"></p>\r\n\r\n				<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\">\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td><span class=\"PalAb\">open downward</span> (sad).</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td>\r\n						<p class=\"Image\">\r\n						<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/44.svg\"></p>\r\n						</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n				</table>\r\n				</td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</tbody>\r\n		</table>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">The two forms of a parabola</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Compare the two forms of a parabola illustrated below and note the similarities and differences in characteristics:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\">Parabola opens upward</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAa2x^2-2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/189.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{a&gt;0}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">vertex</span> is the <span class=\"PalAa\">lowest</span> point.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">At vertex the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate is the <span class=\"PalAa\">minimum</span> value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">It is the <span class=\"PalAa\">point</span> at which the curve turns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The function has a <span class=\"PalAa\">minimum</span> value at this point</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" height=\"809\" width=\"867\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAb\">Parabola opens downward</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAb{-2}x^2+2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/190.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{a&lt;0}\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" height=\"191\" width=\"863\">\r\n		<tbody>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n				<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">vertex</span> is the <span class=\"PalAb\">highest</span> point.</span></p>\r\n\r\n				<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">At vertex the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate is the <span class=\"PalAb\">maximum</span> value.</span></p>\r\n\r\n				<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">It is the <span class=\"PalAb\">point</span> at which the curve turns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n				<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The function has a <span class=\"PalAb\">maximum</span> value at this point.</span></p>\r\n				</td>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</tbody>\r\n		</table>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Identifying the form of a&nbsp;parabola without graphing</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">How do we know which one of the two forms we are dealing with without actually drawing the curve?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The answer lies in the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></span>, the coefficient of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x^2\\)</span> (the number in front of the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x^2\\)</span>), as we can see illustrated below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{a&gt;0}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 45%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{a&lt;0}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAa2x^2+0x-2\\)</span><br>\r\n		which is actually <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAa2x^2-2\\)</span>,<br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{a=2}\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=0\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c=-2\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAb{-2}x^2+0x+2\\)</span><br class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		which is actually&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAb{-2}x^2+2\\)</span>,<br class=\"BodyText\">\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{a=-2}\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b=0\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(c=2\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the term <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa a\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAa\">positive</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the term&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb a\\)</span>&nbsp;is <span class=\"PalAb\">negative</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa a\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAa\">positive</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{a&gt;0})\\)</span>, then the parabola <span class=\"PalAa\">opens upward</span>, and if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb a\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAb\">negative</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{a&lt;0})\\)</span>, then the parabola <span class=\"PalAb\">opens downward</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Symmetry of a parabola</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A parabola is symmetric with respect to a vertical line called the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">axis of symmetry</span>. &nbsp;The vertex of the parabola will lie on the axis of symmetry. &nbsp;In the two graphs above, the axis of symmetry is the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(688,'y-coordinate','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Vertex and the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex tells us<br>\r\n		how high or low the parabola sits.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To find the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex, we substitute the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex into the original general equation for the quadratic function, as illustrated below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p>Quadratic function equation</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=ax^2+bx+c\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">-coordinate of the vertex</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_m\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\\left(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 50%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\left(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2+b\\left(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)+c\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 50%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\times\\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{-b}{2a}\\right)^2+b\\times\\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{-b}{2a}\\right)+c\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 50%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{-b^2+4ac}{4a}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">-coordinate of the vertex is calculated as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f\\left(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)=\\displaystyle\\frac{-b^2+4ac}{4a}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/193.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>For the quadratic function or parabola</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(\\PalAb x)=\\PalAb x^2+2\\PalAb x-3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span><span>-coordinate of the vertex is</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{x_m}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}=-\\displaystyle\\frac{2}{2\\times1}=\\PalAb{-1}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{-1}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">into the quadratic function</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(\\PalAb x)\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">to calculate the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(\\PalAb{-1})\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{-1})^2+2(\\PalAb{-1})-3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-1\\times-1+2\\times-1-3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1-2-3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{-4}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the vertex is the point</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{-1};\\PalAa{-4})\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The vertex is the point&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\left( -\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a} ; f\\left( -\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a} \\right) \\right)\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(689,'x-coordinate','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Vertex and the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Vertex or turning point</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The vertex of the graph of a quadratic function is defined as the point where the graph changes from decreasing to increasing or increasing to decreasing. &nbsp;The vertex of a parabola is the turning point.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The vertex of a quadratic function is defined as the point where the graph changes from</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<ul>\r\n		<li>increasing to decreasing if the parabola opens downward or</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n		<ul>\r\n		<li>decreasing to increasing if the parabola opens upward.</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"400\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/191.html\" width=\"220\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Axis of symmetry&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The axis of symmetry is the line that splits the parabola into two separate branches that mirror each other.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The axis of symmetry is a vertical line that goes through the vertex and&nbsp;is defined by &#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\text{ some value}\\)</span>&#39;. &nbsp;The number that replaces &#39;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\text{ some value}\\)</span>&#39;&nbsp;will be the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex defines the axis of symmetry. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex is calculated by the formula <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x_m=-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/192.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 58%; text-align: right;\">For the quadratic function</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x^2+2x-3\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 58%; text-align: right;\">with constants</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span></td>\r\n		<