Aa0)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(692,'Two x-intercepts','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The discriminant and two&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinates of the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts of a parabola are</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\displaystyle\\frac{-b-\\sqrt{\\PalAa{b^2-4ac}}}{2a}\\)</span>&nbsp;and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\displaystyle\\frac{-b+\\sqrt{\\PalAa{b^2-4ac}}}{2a}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The quantity <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{b^2-4ac}\\)</span> in the equations above is known as the <span class=\"PalAa\">discriminant</span> since it discriminates between the different types of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Discriminant&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=b^2-4ac\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are three different types of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts, namely:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Parabola with two <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Parabola with one&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">-intercept</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Parabola with no&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">-intercepts</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Parabola with two&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When the discriminant is positive, the parabola has two&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts, as is illustrated below.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b^2-4ac&gt;0\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can evaluate the&nbsp;square root of the discriminant and determine the two separate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts using the given equations. &nbsp;Note that the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-intercepts are equally far from the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-coordinate of the vertex. &nbsp;In fact they are often written in the form</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x=\\displaystyle\\frac{-b\\pm\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}=-\\displaystyle\\frac{b}{2a}\\PalAb\\pm\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">to emphasise this fact. &nbsp;This means, when <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{b^2-4ac}&gt;\\PalAa{0}\\)</span>&nbsp;that there are always <span class=\"PalAb\">two <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>-values</span> which give the same <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-value (the vertex excluded).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/166.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For the parabola</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span c