/p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCc{x_2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{-b+\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{-(8)+\\sqrt{(16)}}{2(-2)}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{-8+\\sqrt{16}}{2 \\times-2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\displaystyle\\frac{-8+4}{-4}=\\displaystyle\\frac{-4}{-4}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalCc1\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCc x\\)</span><span class=\"PalCc\"><span class=\"PalBc\">-intercepts</span></span> are</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCc{(3;0)}\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCc{(1;0)}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 7</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd y\\)</span><span class=\"PalCd\">-intercept</span> is</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd y\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=f(0)=\\PalCd c\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\PalCd {-6}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd y\\)</span><span class=\"PalCd\">-intercept</span> is</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd{(0;-6)}\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 13%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 8</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%; vertical-align: top;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Draw the graph:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/175.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(697,'Not constant','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The slope of a parabola is not constant</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The slope of a quadratic function cannot be determined in only one calculation. &nbsp;Looking at graphs of parabola, we notice that&nbsp;a parabola has a slope at a point, but it is constantly changing as we&nbsp;move from point to point. &nbsp;This is unlike a straight line which has a constant slope.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is illustrated in the graph below with the use of <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">tangents</span>. &nbsp;A tangent is a straight line that just touches the graph in one point, as illustrated. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The slope of a parabola at a specific point is actually the slope of the tangent to the parabola at that point. &nbsp;The slopes of the tangents vary at different points and hence the slope of a parabola is never the same at different points.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/180.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We will not calculate the slope of a parabola at different points. &nbsp;The main point to note is that the slope is ever-changing from point to point on the parabola, in contrast to the straight line where it is a constant.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(698,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this short video on the rate of change or slope of a parabola:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/300.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(699,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Exponential</span> functions look somewhat similar to <span class=\"PalAa\">quadratic</span> functions in that they involve exponents, but there is a big difference in that&nbsp;the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">variable</span> is now the <span class=\"PalAb\">exponent</span>, rather than the <span class=\"PalAa\">base</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Quadratic functions</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Quadratic functions are functions such as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(\\PalAa x)=\\PalAa x^2\\)</span>where the variable <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span>&nbsp;is&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAa\">base</span> and a&nbsp;fixed number, such as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>,&nbsp;is&nbsp;the exponent.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"412\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/196.html\" width=\"412\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Exponential functions</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Exponential functions, however, are&nbsp;functions such as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(\\PalAb x)=2^\\PalAb x\\)</span>where the base is a fixed number, such as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\)</span>, and the <span class=\"PalAb\">exponent</span> is the variable <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"412\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/197.html\" width=\"412\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(700,'Examples','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Examples</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The best thing about exponential functions is that they are so useful in real world situations. &nbsp;For example, exponential functions are used to model compound interest, radioactive decay and various types of growth (populations, bacterial or animal). &nbsp;This explains the expression <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">exponential growth</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example of&nbsp;compound interest</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">An initial investment of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> with a <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\%\\)</span> annual interest rate&nbsp;compounded annually will grow according to the formula</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}S(n)&amp;=P(1+i)^n\\\\ &amp;=1\\Tsp000(1+0\\Ndp05)^n\\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span> is the number of years the money has been invested. &nbsp;Such an investment will double roughly every <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14\\)</span> years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example of population growth</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The population of a town in 2013 was estimated to be <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(35\\Tsp000\\)</span> people with an annual growth rate of about <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Ndp4\\%\\)</span>. &nbsp;The population will grow according to the formula</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=35\\Tsp000(1\\Ndp024)^x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span> is the size of the population in 2013 and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> is the number of years since 2013.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Using this equation to estimate the population in 2017 to the nearest hundred people, will give</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}y&amp;=35\\Tsp000(1\\Ndp024)^4\\\\&amp;\\approx38\\Tsp500\\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The estimated population in 2017 is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(38\\Tsp500\\)</span> people.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(701,'x &gt; 0; x &lt; 0','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x&gt;0\\)</span>; <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x&lt;0\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the exponential function&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=2^x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To evaluate this function, choose a numerical value for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> and calculate the function&#39;s value at this <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> has <span class=\"PalAa\">positive</span> values, for example if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\PalAa 3\\)</span>, then</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} f(\\PalAa3)&amp;=2^\\PalAa3\\\\ &amp;=2\\times2\\times2\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa8 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> has <span class=\"PalAb\">negative</span> values, for example if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x=\\PalAb{-3}\\)</span>, then</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} f(\\PalAb{-3})&amp;=2^\\PalAb{-3}\\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2^3}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAb{\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{8}} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The results for <span class=\"PalAa\">positive</span>, zero and <span class=\"PalAb\">negative</span> values of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> for the function <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=2^x\\)</span>&nbsp;are given in the following tables:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 35%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 65%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)=2^x\\)</span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 20%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^0=1\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 20%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa 1\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2^\\PalAa1=\\PalAa2\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 20%;\"><sp