an class=\"BodyText\">Considered the exponential functions of the form&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)=a^x\\)</span>&nbsp;where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{a&gt;1}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, look at the graph of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAa2^x\\)</span>&nbsp;shown&nbsp;below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/198.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can&nbsp;see&nbsp;that when <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb {x&lt;0}\\)</span> the function values are between <span class=\"PalAb\">zero and one</span><span class=\"PalBb\">.</span>&nbsp; Also that when <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{x&gt;0}\\)</span> the function values are <span class=\"PalAa\">greater than one</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">However, for exponential functions where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0&lt;a&lt;1\\)</span>, for example&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\left( \\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2} \\right)^x\\)</span>, the graph will look different.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(704,'a &gt; 1;  0 &lt; a &lt; 1 - Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a&gt;1\\)</span>; &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0&lt;a&lt;1\\)</span>: Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the exponential function&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=f(x)=a^x\\)</span>&nbsp;where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a&gt;0\\)</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\neq1\\)</span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;is a real constant.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are two cases for the base&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>, namely if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{a&gt;1}\\)</span>&nbsp;and if <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0&lt;a&lt;1}\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p>If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{a&gt;1}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p>If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0&lt;a&lt;1}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The exponential function is an <span class=\"PalAb\">increasing function</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>. &nbsp;As <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> increases from large negative values to large positive values,&nbsp;the function values constantly <span class=\"PalAb\">increase</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The exponential function is a <span class=\"PalAa\">decreasing function</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>. &nbsp;As <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> increases from large negative values to large positive values, the function values constantly <span class=\"PalAa\">decrease</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" colspan=\"4\" rowspan=\"1\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">In both cases the functions are positive for all values of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;and they all pass through the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((0;1)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 3%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Thus graphically we have the following:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/205.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Exponential functions with base <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{a&gt;1}\\)</span> are known as <span class=\"PalAb\">growth curves</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">On the other hand, exponential functions with base <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{0&lt;a&lt;1}\\)</span> are known as <span class=\"PalAa\">decay functions</span> because of their decreasing property. &nbsp;They are useful to model certain <span class=\"PalAa\">&#39;negative growth&#39;</span>&nbsp;phenomena such as radioactive decay processes, price-demand curves and non-linear depreciation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:08','2017-10-11 12:27:08','',NULL),(705,'Inverse function','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The inverse function</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We need to understand&nbsp;the term inverse function before we look at logarithmic functions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the <span class=\"PalAa\">function <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{f(x)}\\)</span>:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y=\\PalAa{f(x)}=x+2\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 18%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 17%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\