t the inequality.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd{x\\leq2}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Any number that <span class=\"PalCd\">is</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd2\\)</span> <span class=\"PalCd\">or is smaller than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd2\\)</span> fits the inequality,&nbsp;for example&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd2;\\PalCd{1\\Ndp9};\\PalCd{1\\Ndp8};\\PalCd{1};\\PalCd{0};\\PalCd{-1};\\PalCd{-100};\\dots\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/326.svg\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(731,'Variable on right side','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Variable on right side</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you need to solve an&nbsp;inequality, but the variable is on the wrong side of the inequality sign, what do you do?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10&gt;m+3\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve the inequality</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(m+3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Add&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-3\\)</span>&nbsp;both sides</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10-3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(m+3-3\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(7\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(m\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rewrite this inequality</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(m\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(7\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 40%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Reason</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAa\">greater than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>, then <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAb\">less than</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If the variable is on the wrong side of the inequality,<br>\r\n		<span class=\"Emphasis_1\">swop</span> the sides and <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">reverse</span> the inequality sign.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(732,'Multiply or divide by variable','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Multiply or divide by a variable</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can multiply&nbsp;and&nbsp;divide&nbsp;both sides of an inequality by any positive or negative number. &nbsp;However, when we multiply or divide both sides of an inequality by a variable (an unknown value) we need to be more careful.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(hx&lt;4h\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 70%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve the inequality for&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(h\\PalBa x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb &lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4h\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Divide both sides by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(h\\)</span>, but&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{h&gt;0}\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{h&lt;0}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb h\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalCb\">positive</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBb h\\PalBa x}{\\PalBb h}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4\\PalBb h}{\\PalBb h}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Say&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{h=2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{(\\PalBb 2)\\PalBa x}{\\PalBb 2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4(\\PalBb 2)}{\\PalBb 2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBb 2\\PalBa x}{\\PalBb 2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4\\times\\PalBb 2}{\\PalBb 2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc h\\)</span>&nbsp;is <span class=\"PalBc\">negative</span>, <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">reverse</span> the inequality sign</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc h\\PalBa x}{\\PalBc h}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4\\PalBc h}{\\PalBc h}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Say&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{h=-2}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{(\\PalBc {-2})\\PalBa x}{\\PalBc {-2}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4(\\PalBc {-2})}{\\PalBc {-2}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc {-2}\\PalBa x}{\\PalBc {-2}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{4\\times\\PalBc {-2}}{\\PalBc {-2}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">You cannot divide an inequality by a variable unless you are sure<br>\r\n		of its sign since you do not know whether you must reverse the<br>\r\n		sign of the inequality.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You must always ask yourself whether you know for sure the sign of the variable before dividing or multiplying when dealing with an inequality.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(733,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A linear inequality can&nbsp;be formed by converting a word statement to a linear inequality.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Jacob has <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> in his savings account at the beginning of the holiday.<br>\r\nHe wants to have&nbsp;at least <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span> in his account by the end of the holiday.<br>\r\nHe withdraws <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur280\\Cdp00\\)</span> each week for&nbsp;snacks and entertainment. &nbsp;For how many weeks can he withdraw money from his account?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Write an inequality that represents Jacob&rsquo;s situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n\\)</span> be the <span class=\"PalAa\">number of weeks</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Unravel the inequality from the information given:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 70%;\">Information</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"4\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 30%;\">Inequality</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 66%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">He started with <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Tsp000\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">He withdraws money from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Tsp000-\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">He withdraws <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur280\\Cdp00\\)</span> every week.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Tsp000-280\\times \\PalAa n\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">He wants to have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span> left in his&nbsp;account by the end of the holiday.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Tsp000-280\\times \\PalAa n\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(600\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">It must be at least <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;There must be <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span> or more than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span> left in his account.</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 10%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Tsp000-280\\times \\PalAa n\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(600\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">How many <span class=\"PalAa\">weeks</span> can Jacob withdraw money from his account?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve the inequality to find the value of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 70%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve inequality for&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\Tsp000-280\\PalAa n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(600\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 70%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Add&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-2\\Tsp000\\)</span>&nbsp;both sides</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-280\\PalAa n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(600-2\\Tsp000\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 70%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-280\\PalAa n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-1\\Tsp400\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 70%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>&nbsp;Divide by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{-280}\\)</span>, so&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">reverse</span><span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\geq\\)</span></span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{-280\\PalAa n}{\\PalAb{-280}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\leq}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{-1\\Tsp400}{\\PalAb{-280}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 70%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 12%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb\\leq\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(5\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, Jacob can withdraw money from his account for <span class=\"PalAa\">five or less weeks</span> and will still have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span> or more left in his account.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(734,'Key words','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Key words in word problems</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When you are solving word problems, pay close attention to the key words given below. &nbsp;These keywords&nbsp;will help you to write the inequality. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Once the inequality is written, you can solve it using the following steps:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 90%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Read through the entire problem.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Highlight the important information and key words that you need to solve the problem.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 3</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Identify your variable.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write the inequality.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Step 4</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Here are a few key words that we associate with inequalities:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p>Key words</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\">\r\n		<p>Meaning</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 13%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 25%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">at least<br>\r\n		is not less than<br>\r\n		is not smaller than<br>\r\n		minimum</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 32%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">greater than or equal to</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 13%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 25%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">at most<br>\r\n		is not more than<br>\r\n		is not greater than<br>\r\n		maximum</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 32%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">less than or equal to</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\leq\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 13%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 25%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">is more than<br>\r\n		is greater than<br>\r\n		is larger than<br>\r\n		above</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 32%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">greater than</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&gt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 13%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 25%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">is less than<br>\r\n		is smaller than<br>\r\n		below</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 32%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">less than</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt;\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(735,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on linear inequalities in two variables:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/303.mp4\" width=\"600\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(736,'Boundary line','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Boundary line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Using the Cartesian plane is especially helpful for understanding the range of possible solutions for inequalities with two variables. &nbsp;When a linear inequality with two variables is graphed in the Cartesian plane, the full range of possible solutions is represented as a shaded area in the plane.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The boundary line for the inequality is drawn as a <span class=\"PalAa\">solid line</span> if the points on the line itself <span class=\"PalAa\">do satisfy</span> the inequality, as in the cases of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa \\leq\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa \\geq\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The boundary line for the inequality is drawn as a <span class=\"PalAb\">dashed line</span> if the points on the line <span class=\"PalAb\">do not satisfy</span> the inequality, as in the cases of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&lt;\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb&gt;\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(737,'Activity 1 recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Activity 1 recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Making sense of the importance of the shaded region in an inequality is difficult without assigning any context to it. &nbsp;The following example&nbsp;shows one instance where the shaded region helps us understand a range of possibilities.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Cecile and Julia want to donate some money to a local cr&egrave;che. &nbsp;To raise funds, they are selling necklaces and earrings that they have made themselves. &nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">Necklaces</span> cost <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur80\\Cdp00\\)</span> and a <span class=\"PalAb\">pair of earrings</span> cost <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">What is the range of possible sales they could make in order to donate a minimum of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The range of possible sales&nbsp;is&nbsp;given by the inequality</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(80\\PalAa x+50\\PalAb y\\geq1\\Tsp000\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">which can also be written as</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\geq-\\displaystyle\\frac{8}{5}\\PalAa x+20\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The variable <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span> represents the number of <span class=\"PalAa\">necklaces</span> sold and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span> the number of <span class=\"PalAb\">pairs of earrings</span> sold.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The correct graph that represents this inequality is</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/262.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The shaded region represents all the possible combinations of necklaces and earrings that Cecile and Julia could sell in order to make at least <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> for the cr&egrave;che. &nbsp;It is quite a wide range.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that while all points will satisfy the inequality, not all points will make sense in this context. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Take for example the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{6\\Ndp5};\\PalAb{15\\Ndp75})\\)</span>. &nbsp;It satisfies the inequality because</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb y&amp;\\geq-\\displaystyle\\frac{8}{5}\\PalAa x+20\\\\ \\PalAb{15\\Ndp75}&amp;\\geq-\\displaystyle\\frac{8}{5} \\times \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{6\\Ndp5}}{1}+20\\\\15\\Ndp75&amp;\\geq 9\\Ndp6 \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">is true. &nbsp;But while this point does fall within the shaded region, it is hard to expect them to sell <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{6\\Ndp5}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">necklaces</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{15\\Ndp75}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">pairs of earrings</span>. &nbsp;How could&nbsp;they sell half a necklace?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The women can look for whole number combinations in the shaded region to plan how much jewellery to produce.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{8};\\PalAb{15})\\)</span> also falls within the shaded region. &nbsp;If they sell <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{8}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">necklaces</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{15}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">pairs of earrings</span>, their sales are&nbsp;calculated as</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}80\\PalAa x+50\\PalAb y&amp;=80 \\times \\PalAa 8+50 \\times \\PalAb {15}\\\\ &amp;=1\\Tsp390 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Their sales will be <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp390\\Cdp00\\)</span> which is indeed greater than or equal to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(738,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on solving systems of linear inequalities in two variables:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/310.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(739,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">system</span> of linear inequalities is a set of linear inequalities whose common solutions need to be determined.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When solving a system of linear inequalities, you must determine all points that <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">simultaneously satisfy</span> all linear inequalities in the system.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is done by graphing each individual inequality and then finding the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">overlap</span> of the various solution spaces.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Any <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">point</span> that satisfies all the inequalities simultaneously will be in the area of this overlap.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine if the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((3;-1)\\)</span> is a solution of the system of inequalities:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa {x+y}&amp;\\PalAa\\leq\\PalAa6\\\\\\PalAb{2x-y}&amp;\\PalAb&gt;\\PalAb4\\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substituting <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((3;-1)\\)</span> into&nbsp;<br>\r\n		the <span class=\"PalAa\">first inequality</span> gives</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Substituting&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((3;-1)\\)</span><span>&nbsp;into&nbsp;</span><br>\r\n		<span>the <span class=\"PalAb\">second</span></span><span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"PalAa\">&nbsp;</span>inequality</span>&nbsp;<span>gives</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa {x+y}&amp;\\PalAa\\leq\\PalAa6\\\\ \\PalAa (3\\PalAa{)+(}-1\\PalAa)&amp;\\PalAa\\leq\\PalAa6\\\\ 3-1&amp;\\leq6\\\\ 2&amp;\\leq6\\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb{2x-y}&amp;\\PalAb&gt;\\PalAb4\\\\ \\PalAb{2(}3\\PalAb{)-(}-1\\PalAb{)}&amp;\\PalAb&gt;\\PalAb4\\\\ 2\\times3-(-1)&amp;&gt;4\\\\ 6+1&amp;&gt;4\\\\ 7&amp;&gt;4 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is true.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is true.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, the point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((3;-1)\\)</span> is a solution of the system of inequalities.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The graph shows that point <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{(3;-1)}\\)</span> lies in the area of the <span class=\"PalBb\">overlap</span> of the solutions of the inequalities. &nbsp;Therefore, it is a solution of the system of inequalities.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"{SYSVAR:MEDIA_REL}/225.JPG\" style=\"width: 342px; height: 480px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(740,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Apart from systems of two inequalities in two unknowns, it is quite feasible&nbsp;and often necessary in practice, to consider systems with a greater number of inequalities than the number of unknowns. &nbsp;This is illustrated below, where we consider a system of five inequalities in two unknowns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The procedure for solving the system is exactly as before, namely solve each inequality separately and then determine which region is common to all solutions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Solve the following system of inequalities graphically:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{-x+y-3} &amp; \\PalAa \\leq \\PalAa 0\\\\ \\PalAb{x+y-5} &amp; \\PalAb \\leq \\PalAb0 \\\\ \\PalBc{x-3} &amp; \\PalBc \\leq \\PalBc 0 \\\\ x &amp;\\geq0\\\\ y&amp;\\geq0 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We look at the last two of these inequalities first. &nbsp;The inequality <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\geq0\\)</span> simply means the region to the right of and including the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis whereas <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\geq0\\)</span> means the region above and including the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>-axis. &nbsp;Taken together, these two inequalities imply the first quadrant of the Cartesian plane so we can restrict our considerations to this region.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">first inequality</span> is satisfied by all points on, below and to the right of the line</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{-x+y-3} &amp; \\PalAa = \\PalAa0&amp; \\text{or}\\\\ \\PalAa{y} &amp; \\PalAa = \\PalAa{x+3} \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">That is the <span class=\"PalAa\">blue</span> shaded region.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">second inequality</span> is satisfied by all points on, below and to the left of the line</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAb{x+y-5} &amp; \\PalAb = \\PalAb0&amp; \\text{or}\\\\ \\PalAb{y} &amp; \\PalAb = \\PalAb{-x+5} \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">That is the <span class=\"PalAb\">red</span> shaded region.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Finally, the <span class=\"PalBc\">third inequality</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalBc{x-3} &amp; \\PalBc \\leq \\PalBc 0&amp; \\text{or} \\\\ \\PalBc{x} &amp; \\PalBc \\leq \\PalBc 3 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">is satisfied by all points on and to the left of the vertical line <span class=\"math-tex\">(PalBc{x=3})</span>. &nbsp;That is the <font color=\"#078446\">yellow</font>&nbsp;shaded region.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The solution is the <span class=\"PalBa\">overlap</span> region of all these inequalities, that is the <span class=\"PalBa\">brown</span> shaded region&nbsp;shown in the graph below.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/227.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that the solution is called a closed or bounded&nbsp;solution because there are lines on&nbsp;all sides of the solution (i.e. the overlap region as indicated on the graph).</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(741,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Fit For Life running club is&nbsp;trying to raise money for new equipment.<br>\r\nThe men are selling&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">water bottles</span> for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur20\\Cdp00}\\)</span> a bottle and the women are selling <span class=\"PalAb\">sweat bands</span> for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{\\Cur40\\Cdp00}\\)</span> each. &nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">The women expect to sell at least&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span><br>\r\n<span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAb\">sweat bands</span>.&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;Jointly they must raise&nbsp;more than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur8\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">Let</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">represent the number of <span class=\"PalAa\">water bottles</span> sold.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">Let</td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">represent the number of <span class=\"PalAb\">sweat bands</span> sold.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Write a system of inequalities that represents this situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write the inequality representing the income.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 65%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">More than&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur8\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;implies&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&gt;\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\PalAa x+40\\PalAb y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&gt;\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\Tsp000\\)</span>&nbsp;or</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 13%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(2\\PalAa x+4\\PalAb y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&gt;\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(800\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write the inequality representing the sales of the <span class=\"PalAb\">sweat bands</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 65%; text-align: right;\"><span>At least&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">sweat bands</span><span>&nbsp;impli</span><span>es&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq100\\)</span><span>:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Write the inequalities representing positive or zero sales.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 65%; text-align: right;\"><span>Cannot sell a negative number of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">water bottles</span>:</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa x\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 55%; text-align: right;\"><span>Cannot sell a negative number of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">sweat bands</span><span>:</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb y\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\geq\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(742,'No solution','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">System of inequalities with no solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Find the solution of the following system of inequalities:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{x+y}&amp;\\PalAa \\leq \\PalAa{-3}\\\\ \\PalAb{x+y} &amp;\\PalAb \\geq \\PalAb 3 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Drawing the lines and their solution spaces gives:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/234.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There is no place where the individual solution spaces overlap. &nbsp;The lines <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{x+y=-3}\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{x+y=3}\\)</span> never intersect because they are parallel lines with different <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-intercepts.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Since there is no intersection, there is no solution.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(743,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Cost</span>, <span class=\"BodyText\">revenue</span> and <span class=\"BodyText\">profit</span> are the three most important factors in determining the success of a company. &nbsp;A company can have high revenue, but if the costs are higher, it will show no profit and is destined to go out of business when available capital runs out. &nbsp;Managing costs and revenue to maximize profit is the key for any company.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> faced by companies can be divided&nbsp;into two main categories: <span class=\"PalBc\">fixed costs</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">variable costs</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span> <span class=\"PalBc\">fixed cost</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(+\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">variable cost</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"PalBc\">Fixed cost</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Fixed costs are costs that are independent of output. &nbsp;These remain constant throughout&nbsp;production. It is the upfront cost a business must pay to create an infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Examples of fixed costs are rent,&nbsp;buildings and&nbsp;equipment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The best way to identify fixed cost is to produce zero output. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalBc\">Fixed cost</span> is incurred whether or not any output is produced.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Variable cost</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Variable costs may fluctuate during production. &nbsp;During production these costs may change.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Examples of variable costs are labour directly involved in production,&nbsp;raw materials,&nbsp;fuel expenses and&nbsp;packaging.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Variable cost can be calculated using the formula:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalAb\">variable cost</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span> number of units produced <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\times\\)</span><br>\r\n		variable cost&nbsp;to produce a single unit</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(744,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A factory manufactures office desks. &nbsp;The manufacturing costs for a month are given below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">cost of wood and other materials amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur105\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">direct labour costs&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur175\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">variable factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur70\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk&nbsp;and</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">fixed factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;for the month.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate the <span class=\"PalAa\">total</span> monthly <span class=\"PalAa\">cost</span> of the factory.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">variable cost</span> per month is calculated from three costs:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 65%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">wood and other materials per desk</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur105\\Cdp00\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">labour per desk</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur175\\Cdp00\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">variable factory overheads per desk</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur70\\Cdp00\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\overline{\\Cur350\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb q\\)</span> represent the number of desks (quantity) the factory manufactures per month.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">variable cost</span> is&nbsp;therefore&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur350\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk&nbsp;or&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(350\\times \\PalAb q = \\PalAb{350q}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBc\">fixed cost</span> per month is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{\\Cur100\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{TC})\\)</span>&nbsp;is calculated as</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{TC}&amp;=\\PalBc{\\text{fixed cost}}+\\PalAb{\\text{variable cost}}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalBc{100\\Tsp000}+\\PalAb{350q}. \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(745,'Cost as a function','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Cost as a function</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A factory manufactures office desks. &nbsp;The manufacturing costs for a month are given below:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">cost of wood and other materials amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur105\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">direct labour costs&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur175\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">variable factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur70\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk&nbsp;and</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">fixed factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;for the month.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">total</span>&nbsp;monthly&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">cost</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{TC})\\)</span> of the factory is calculated as</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\begin{align} \\PalAa{TC}&amp;=\\PalBc{\\text{fixed cost}}+\\PalAb{\\text{variable cost}}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalBc{100\\Tsp000}+\\PalAb{350q}. \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <span class=\"PalAa\">total </span>monthly <span class=\"PalAa\">cost</span> of the factory is a <span class=\"PalAa\">function of</span> the number of desks manufactured <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb q)\\)</span> and can also be written as</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C(\\PalAb q )=100\\Tsp000+350\\PalAb q.\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A function can be written in many different ways. &nbsp;Using <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span> instead of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb q\\)</span> to represent the number of desks, the <span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span> can be written as</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C(\\PalAb x )=100\\Tsp000+350\\PalAb x.\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of using <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C\\)</span>, we could also use&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa f\\)</span>&nbsp;and write the function as</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa f(\\PalAb x )=100\\Tsp000+350\\PalAb x\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>or use&nbsp;any other letter we want&nbsp;to.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(746,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The concept of marginal cost is very important in the theory of economics.<br>\r\n<span class=\"PalBb\">Marginal cost</span> is the change in <span class=\"PalBc\">total cost</span> that comes from making or producing one additional item.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalBb\">Marginal cost</span> is defined as the cost that results<br>\r\n		from a one unit increase in the production rate.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So if a company has already produced <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(13\\)</span> cars, the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> of the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(14^{\\text{th}}\\)</span> car is only the additional costs the company incurs in making that car.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Expanding scale of production</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A company can have cost advantages by expanding their scale of production.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The cost of producing something can fall as the volume of its output increases. &nbsp;Hence it might cost <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> to produce <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span> copies of a magazine, but only <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur4\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> to produce <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span> copies. &nbsp;The cost in this case has fallen from <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur30\\Cdp00\\)</span> to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur4\\Cdp00\\)</span> a copy, because the main elements of cost in producing a magazine, that is editorial and design, are unrelated to the number of magazines produced.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The aim is to reduce the production cost per unit as production increases.<br>\r\nIn other words:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The cost of producing an additional unit, the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBb\">marginal<br>\r\n		cost,&nbsp;</span>decreases as the volume of production increases.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Optimum production level</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The purpose of analysing marginal cost is to determine at what point a company can operate at an optimum production level.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Companies constantly examine the cost implication of adding one more unit to their production schedules. &nbsp;This is because&nbsp;at some point, the benefit of producing one additional unit and generating revenue from that item will bring the overall cost of producing the product line down.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The key to optimizing manufacturing costs is to<br>\r\n		find this&nbsp;point or level as quickly as possible.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(747,'Three methods','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Three methods to calculate marginal cost</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When asked to compute <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalBb{MC})\\)</span>, the data you need is likely to come in one of three forms.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">In a <span class=\"BodyText\">table</span> which gives you </span><span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> and <span class=\"PalAb\">quantity produced</span>.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">A <span class=\"BodyText\">linear equation</span> relating </span><span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{TC})\\)</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">quantity produced</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb q)\\)</span>. &nbsp;This would be an equation like&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {TC}=400\\PalAb q+20\\)</span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {TC}=50+6\\PalAb q\\)</span>.</span></span><br>\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">A <span class=\"BodyText\">non-linear equation</span> relating total cost <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{TC})\\)</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">quantity produced</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb q)\\)</span>. &nbsp;This would be an equation like <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{TC}=34\\PalAb q^2-24\\PalAb q+9\\)</span>.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Each of these situations has to be dealt with differently.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(748,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Using a table to calculate marginal cost</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost </span>of producing one pen is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Cdp00\\)</span> and the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> of producing two pens is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur9\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> of expanding output by one unit is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur4\\Cdp00\\)</span> only and is calculated as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur9\\Cdp00-\\Cur5\\Cdp00=\\Cur4\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;(or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9-5=4\\)</span>). &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> of the second unit is the difference between the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> of producing&nbsp;two units and the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> of producing one unit.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalCb\">Marginal cost</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalBb{MC})\\)</span> which is really an incremental cost can be written as</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{MC}=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\text{change in } \\PalAa {\\text{total cost } }(\\PalAa{TC})}{\\text{change in } \\PalAb{\\text{number of units produced}}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> of producing four pens is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur16\\Cdp00\\)</span> and the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> of producing five pens is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur21\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> of the fifth unit is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;It is the difference between the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> of producing five units and the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost </span>of producing four units and is calculated as</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalBb{MC} &amp;= \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{TC} \\text{ of producing }5\\text{ units}-\\PalAa{TC} \\text{ of producing }4\\text{ units}}{\\text{change in } \\PalAb{\\text{number of units produced}}} \\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\Cur21\\Cdp00-\\Cur16\\Cdp00}{1}\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur5\\Cdp00\\text{.} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You can easily understand from the table given below how the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> is calculated:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 33%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Units of output</span></span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 33%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span><span class=\"PalAa\">Total cost</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{(\\Cur)}\\)</span></span></span></th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>Marginal cost&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{(\\Cur)}\\)</span></span></span></th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 1\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur5\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur5\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 2\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur9\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur4\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 3\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur12\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur3\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 4\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur16\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur4\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 5\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur21\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur5\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 6\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur29\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 11%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur8\\Cdp00}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(749,'Linear relationship','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Linear relationship between total cost and quantity</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You can calculate <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> when you have a linear relationship between <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\">quantity</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the example of a&nbsp;factory that manufactures office desks. &nbsp;The manufacturing costs for a month are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">cost of wood and other materials amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur105\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">direct labour costs&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur175\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">variable factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur70\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk&nbsp;and</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">fixed factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;for the month.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">total</span> monthly <span class=\"PalAa\">cost</span> of the factory is&nbsp;calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa{TC}&amp;=\\PalBc{\\text{fixed cost}}+\\PalAb{\\text{variable cost}}\\\\ &amp;={100\\Tsp000}+350\\PalAb{q}. \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> is a <span class=\"BodyText\">linear function</span> of the <span class=\"PalAb\">number of desks</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb q)\\)</span>&nbsp;manufactured.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalBb\">Marginal cost</span> is the additional cost we have when we manufactured one more chair. With the equation <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{TC}=100\\Tsp000+350\\PalAb q\\)</span>, our total cost goes up by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur350\\Cdp00\\)</span> whenever we manufacture an additional desk, as shown by the coefficient in front of the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb q\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So we have a <span class=\"BodyText\">constant</span> <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur350\\Cdp00\\)</span> per desk produced.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let us consider <span class=\"BodyText\">linear functions</span>. &nbsp;The equation for a linear function, or straight line, is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa y=a\\PalAb x+b\\)</span>&nbsp;where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;is the slope of the line and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(b\\)</span>&nbsp;is the&nbsp;intercept of the line on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(y\\)</span>-axis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In terms of two arbitrary points on the straight line,&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P_1\\)</span> with co-ordinates <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{x_1};\\PalAa{y_1})\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P_2\\)</span> with co-ordinates <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb{x_2};\\PalAa{y_2})\\)</span>, the slope is defined as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} a &amp;= \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{change in } y}}{\\PalAb{\\text{change in } x}} \\\\ &amp;= \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{y_2-y_1}}{\\PalAb{x_2-x_1}} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/113.html\" width=\"450\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(750,'Slope','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Marginal cost, linear relationship and slope</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Change consists of two components, namely&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">size</span> and <span class=\"BodyText\">direction</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the example of a&nbsp;factory that manufactures office desks. &nbsp;The manufacturing costs for a month are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">cost of wood and other materials amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur105\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">direct labour costs&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur175\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">variable factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur70\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk&nbsp;and</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">fixed factory overheads amount to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;for the month.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span>&nbsp;is the&nbsp;linear function&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{TC}=100\\Tsp000+350\\PalAb q\\)</span>&nbsp;of the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">number of desks</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb q)\\)</span>&nbsp;manufactured. &nbsp;It gives&nbsp;a&nbsp;constant&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur350\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;per desk manufactured.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider the graph of this linear equation&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{TC}=100\\Tsp000+350\\PalAb q\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span> is the change in <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAa{TC})\\)</span>&nbsp;which corresponds to change of one unit in the value of the <span class=\"PalAb\">quantity</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\PalAb q)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalBb{\\text{slope}}&amp;= \\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAa{\\text{change in }TC}}{\\PalAb{\\text{change in }q}} \\\\ &amp;=\\displaystyle\\frac{350}{1} \\\\ &amp;=350 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"BodyText\">value</span> of the <span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span> gives the <span class=\"BodyText\">size</span> of the change. &nbsp;The <span class=\"BodyText\">sign</span> of the <span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span> gives the <span class=\"BodyText\">direction</span> of the change.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In this case the <span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span> is <span class=\"BodyText\">positive</span>, indicating an <span class=\"BodyText\">increase</span>. &nbsp;If the <span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span> has a negative sign it indicates a decrease.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\">\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/62.svg\" style=\"height: 323px; width: 450px;\"></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(751,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on marginal cost and linear relationship:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/311.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(752,'Constant change','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Constant change</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Sweet Tooth, which specialises in home-made chocolates, packs&nbsp;chocolates in <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\text{g}\\)</span> gift&nbsp;packets. &nbsp;The fixed production cost is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur400\\Cdp00\\)</span> per day, while the production cost per <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\text{g}\\)</span>&nbsp;packet amounts to a further <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur9\\Cdp00\\)</span> per packet.<br>\r\nSweet Tooth cannot produce more than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(200\\)</span>&nbsp;packets per day.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Let <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> represent the number of packets of chocolates produced per day.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Determine the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> function&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{C(x)}\\)</span>&nbsp;and the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> function <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{C\'(x)}\\)</span>of Sweet Tooth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">variable cost </span>is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} &amp;\\text{variable cost to produce one packet } \\times \\text{ number of packets produced per day} \\\\ &amp;=9 \\times x\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAb{9x} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBc\">fixed cost</span> per day is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{\\Cur400\\Cdp00}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span>, as a function of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>, is given by:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa{C(x)}&amp;= \\PalBc{\\text{fixed cost}} + \\PalAb{\\text{variable cost}}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalBc{400}+\\PalAb{9x} \\end{align} \\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> is given by the derivative&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb {C\'(x)=9}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Conclusions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>We determined the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span> and <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> function of Sweet Tooth, which specialises in home-made chocolates, as:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalAa{C(x)}&amp;\\PalAa{=400+9x}&amp;\\text{and}\\\\ \\PalBb{C\'(x)}&amp;\\PalBb{=9}. \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <span class=\"PalAa\">cost</span> function is a straight line. &nbsp;The derivative of the function is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(9\\)</span>, which is a constant. &nbsp;For a straight line the slope remains constant.<br>\r\nTherefore the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> remains constant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember, Sweet Tooth cannot produce more than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(200\\)</span> packets of chocolates per day. &nbsp;If it produces <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(150\\)</span> packets per day, the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur9\\Cdp00}\\)</span>. &nbsp;The <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> is always <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur9\\Cdp00}\\)</span> a day no matter how many packets of chocolates they produce (as long as it is not more than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(200\\)</span>).</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalBb\">Marginal cost</span> implies that the change in the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost</span>, resulting from&nbsp;producing one additional packet of chocolates, is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur9\\Cdp00}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that the <span class=\"PalBc\">fixed cost</span> reduced to zero when the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> was calculated.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost </span>is only influenced by the <span class=\"PalAb\">variable cost</span><br>\r\n		and is unaffected by the <span class=\"PalBc\">fixed cost</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is because <span class=\"PalBc\">fixed costs</span>, such as rent or other overheads, generally remain the same, while <span class=\"PalAb\">variable costs</span> will correlate with the number of products manufactured. &nbsp;The number of products manufactured will in turn affect the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(753,'Calculate - Non-linear function: Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on calculating marginal cost and&nbsp;non-linear relationship:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/312.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(754,'Differentiation rules','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Differentiation rules</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Differentiation is the method used to determine the derivative of a function.<br>\r\nThe derivative of a function is used to determine the <span class=\"BodyText\">slope</span> of the graph of a function.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are quite a number of differentiation rules, but we will consider only four of them.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Differentiation rule 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The derivative of any constant term, that is a term which consists of a number only, is zero:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{da}{dx}=0\\)</span>, where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(a\\)</span>&nbsp;is a constant.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=4\\)</span>&nbsp;then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=0\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Differentiation rule 2</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=x^n\\)</span>, then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=nx^{n-1}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)\\)</span>&nbsp;equals&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;to the power of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span>, then <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)\\)</span> (pronounced <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\\)</span> accent <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>) is equal to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span> times <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span> to the power of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span> minus one.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=x^7\\)</span>&nbsp;then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=7x^6\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Differentiation rule 3</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[ af(x) \\right]=af\'(x)\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The derivative of a constant times a function is equal to the constant times the derivative of the function.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=ax^n\\)</span>, then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=anx^{n-1}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=7x^5\\)</span>&nbsp;then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=7\\times5x^4=35x^4\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Differentiation rule 4</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=g(x)+h(x)\\)</span>, then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=g\'(x)+h\'(x)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When a function consists of the sum of two other functions, then the derivative of this function is the sum of the derivatives of the other two functions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=a+g(x)\\)</span>, then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=g\'(x)\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When a function consists of the sum of a constant and another function, then the derivative of this function is zero plus the derivative of the other function.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For example, if&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f(x)=x^2-2x-3\\)</span>&nbsp;then&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(f\'(x)=2x-2\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(755,'Farmer example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Farmer example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A peanut farmer&rsquo;s <span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span> in rand, is given by</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span> represents the <span class=\"PalAb\">number</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">of kilograms </span>of peanuts produced.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The graph of the <span class=\"PalAa\">total cost function</span> is given below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"650\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/264.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can clearly see that the cost function is continuously increasing until it reaches a point where it will be extremely expensive for him to produce another kilogram of peanuts. &nbsp;The <span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span> of the function is not constant and there is no constant rate of change. &nbsp;Thus the <span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span> changes continuously.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The farmer can see how the cost is increasing, but he cannot see how a change in production level will influence the cost. &nbsp;In other words, if he produces at a certain production level, what will it cost to produce one extra kilogram?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">For instance, if the farmer produces <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span> kilograms of peanuts and he is interested in knowing how the cost will change if one extra kilogram is produced, then he wants to determine the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> at a production level of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(1\\Tsp000\\)</span> kilograms.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(756,'Farmer example (Cont.)','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Farmer example (Cont.)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span>A peanut farmer&rsquo;s&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span>&nbsp;in rand, is given by</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {C(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>&nbsp;represents the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">number</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">of kilograms </span>of peanuts&nbsp;produced.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBb\">slope</span>&nbsp;of this <span class=\"PalAa\">cost&nbsp;function</span> is not constant and there is no constant rate of change. The slope changes continuously. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The farmer&nbsp;wants to know if he&nbsp;produces&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;kilograms of peanuts,&nbsp;how will the cost change if one extra kilogram is produced. &nbsp;This means,&nbsp;he wants to determine the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span>&nbsp;at a production level of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span><br>\r\n<span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He uses the following procedure:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 65%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>The <span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span> is</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{ C(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100\\text{.}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>Determine the&nbsp;derivative of the first&nbsp;term:&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{d}{dx}\\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100} \\right)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{2\\PalAb x^{2-1}}{100}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x}{50}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span>Determine the&nbsp;derivative of the second</span><span>&nbsp;term:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{d}{dx}\\left(100 \\right)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>So, if the <span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span> is&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{ C(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100\\text{,}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>then the <span class=\"PalBb\">derivative</span> of the cost function is</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb {C\'(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x}{50}\\text{.}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>Substitute</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>into the <span class=\"PalBb\">derivative</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb {C\'(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x}{50}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>to calculate the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> at a production level of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>:</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb {C\'(\\PalAb {1\\Tsp000})}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb {1\\Tsp000}}{50}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{20}\\text{.}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>This means, for an extra kilogram&nbsp;produced at a production level of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>, the <span class=\"PalAa\">cost</span> will increase by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur20\\Cdp00}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(757,'Farmer recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Farmer example recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A peanut farmer&rsquo;s&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span>&nbsp;in rand, is given by</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>&nbsp;represents the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">number</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">of kilograms </span>of peanuts&nbsp;produced.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBb\" style=\"color: rgb(157,\r\n 24,\r\n 194); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; line-height: 27px;\">slope</span>&nbsp;of this&nbsp;cost&nbsp;function&nbsp;is not constant and there is no constant rate of change. The slope changes continuously.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If the farmer&nbsp;produces&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({400}\\)</span>&nbsp;kilograms of peanuts,&nbsp;how much will it cost to produce one extra kilogram? &nbsp;This means,&nbsp;he wants to determine the&nbsp;marginal cost&nbsp;at a production level of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({400}\\)</span>&nbsp;kilograms.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Calculate the <span class=\"PalAa\">cost</span> and the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{400}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>&nbsp;of peanuts:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle; width: 55%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>The&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span><span>&nbsp;is</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C(\\PalAb x)\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle; width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Cost</span> for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{400}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C(\\PalAb {400})\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb {400}^2}{100}+100\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle; width: 50%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{1\\Tsp700}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"vertical-align: middle; width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>The&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBb\">derivative</span><span>&nbsp;is</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb {C\'}(\\PalAb x)\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x}{50}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalBb\">Marginal cost</span><span>&nbsp;for&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{400}\\)</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb {C\'}(\\PalAb {400})\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb {400}}{50}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb8\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If&nbsp;the farmer produces <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({400}\\)</span> kilograms, then it will cost&nbsp;him an extra <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({\\Cur8\\Cdp00}\\)</span> to produce&nbsp;the next kilogram.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We know this&nbsp;because <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb {C\'}(\\PalAb {400})=\\PalBb8\\)</span>&nbsp;means that at&nbsp;a production level of &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{400}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>, the <span class=\"PalBb\">marginal cost</span> function approximates that it&nbsp;will cost the farmer&nbsp;an extra <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{\\Cur8\\Cdp00}\\)</span> to produce the next kilogram of peanuts.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The graphs of the cost function as well as the marginal cost function are drawn below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\">Cost</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalBb\">Marginal cost</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa C(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBb{C\'}(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x}{50}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"700\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/266.html\" width=\"700\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"700\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/265.html\" width=\"700\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Image\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(758,'Introduction','\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Profit is a very important concept for any business. &nbsp;Profit earned by a business can be used to measure the success of the business. &nbsp;Profit is also an important signal to other providers of finance to a business. &nbsp;Banks, suppliers and other lenders are more likely to provide finance to a business that can demonstrate it makes a profit and can pay debts as they fall due.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Profits earned which are kept in the business are an important source of finance for the business. &nbsp;The moment a product is sold for more than it cost to produce, then a profit is earned which can be reinvested.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Profit can be measured and calculated. &nbsp;So here is the formula:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"BodyText\">profit&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span>&nbsp;total revenue&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\)</span>&nbsp;total costs</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Profit maximization is the process by which a firm determines the price and output level that returns the greatest profit.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(759,'Farmer','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Farmer</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A peanut farmer&rsquo;s&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;in rand, is given by</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {C(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span> represents the <span class=\"PalAb\">number of kilograms</span> of peanuts produced. &nbsp;The cost is in rand.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalCd\">revenue function</span> is given by</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd{R(\\PalAb x)=31\\PalAb x}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">that is, each kilogram of peanuts produced is sold at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur31\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">His profit is the difference between income earned by selling (revenue) and the cost incurred for the production of the peanuts.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span> is now given by</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\PalBc{P(\\PalAb x)}&amp;=\\PalCd{R(\\PalAb x)}-\\PalCd{C(\\PalAb x)}\\\\ &amp;=\\PalCd{31}\\PalAb x-\\PalAa{\\left(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100\\right)}\\\\ &amp;=31\\PalAb x-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}-100\\\\ &amp;=-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+31\\PalAb x-100. \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A graph of the <span class=\"PalBc\">profit function</span> is given below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{P(\\PalAb x)=-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+31\\PalAb x-100}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"400\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/268.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(760,'Farmer','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Farmer</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A peanut farmer&rsquo;s&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span>&nbsp;in rand, is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {C(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100}\\)</span><br>\r\nwhere&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>&nbsp;represents the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">number of kilograms</span>&nbsp;of peanuts produced. &nbsp;The cost is in rand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalCd\">revenue function</span>&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd{R(\\PalAb x)=31\\PalAb x}\\)</span>, that is&nbsp;each kilogram of peanuts produced is sold at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur31\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The farmer&#39;s profit is the difference between income earned by selling (revenue) and the cost incurred for the production of the peanuts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBc\">profit function</span>&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{P(\\PalAb x)=-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+31\\PalAb x-100}\\)</span>, as illustrated in the graph below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"400\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/268.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can clearly see that the profit increases to a point where the profit is at a maximum, after which the profit decreases. &nbsp;The slope of the function is not constant and there is no constant rate of change.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The farmer can see where the <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span> will increase and where it will decrease, but he cannot see how the change in production level will influence the profit. &nbsp;What he wants to determine is the <span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span> at a specific <span class=\"PalAb\">production</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">level</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">The <span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span> is the change in <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span> due<br>\r\n		to a change in the number of <span class=\"PalAb\">units produced</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>This means that if the farmer produces <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({1\\Tsp000}\\)</span> kilograms and he is interested in knowing how the <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span> will change if one extra kilogram is produced, then he wants to determine the <span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span> at a <span class=\"PalAb\">production level</span> of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to know the change in profit at different production levels, the <span class=\"PalBa\">slope</span> of the function at the different production levels must be determined.<br>\r\nThe method used in mathematics to determine this is called <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">differentiation</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The point of calculating marginal profit is that the costs and revenue of each unit are not always consistent. &nbsp;This can have a significant effect on marginal costs and revenue. &nbsp;The marginal calculations are thus based on the specific level of production a company is on at the time of calculation.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:09','2017-10-11 12:27:09','',NULL),(761,'Farmer (Cont.)','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Farmer (Cont.)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A peanut farmer&rsquo;s&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">cost function</span>&nbsp;in rand, is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {C(\\PalAb x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+100}\\)</span><br class=\"BodyText\">\r\nwhere&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span>&nbsp;represents the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">number of kilograms</span>&nbsp;of peanuts produced. &nbsp;The cost is in rand.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The&nbsp;<span class=\"PalCd\" style=\"color: rgb(78,\r\n 127,\r\n 187); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; line-height: 27px;\">revenue function</span>&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalCd{R(\\PalAb x)=31\\PalAb x}\\)</span>, that is&nbsp;each kilogram of peanuts produced is sold at&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur31\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The farmer&#39;s profit is the difference between income earned by selling (revenue) and the cost incurred for the production of the peanuts.<br>\r\nThe&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBc\">profit function</span>&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{P(\\PalAb x)=-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+31\\PalAb x-100}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If the farmer produces&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;kilograms&nbsp;and he is interested in knowing how the <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span> will change if one extra kilogram is produced, then he wants to determine the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBa\" style=\"color: rgb(17,\r\n 150,\r\n 179); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; line-height: 27px;\">marginal profit</span>&nbsp;at a&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">production level</span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">He uses&nbsp;the following procedure:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">Th</span><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">e <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span></span><span class=\"PalBc\">&nbsp;function</span><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;is</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{P(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+31\\PalAb x-100\\text.\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">Determine the&nbsp;derivative of the first&nbsp;term:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{d}{d\\PalAb x}\\left( -\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100} \\right)\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{2\