p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(0\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">So, if the <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span></span><span class=\"PalBc\">&nbsp;function</span><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;is</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{P(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x^2}{100}+31\\PalAb x-100\\text,\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">then the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">derivative</span><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;of the profit function&nbsp;is</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa{P\'(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x}{50}+31\\text.\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb x\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">into the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">derivative</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa{P\'(\\PalAb x)}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb x}{50}+31\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">to calculate the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;at a production level of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\" style=\"color: rgb(187,\r\n 138,\r\n 78); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">kilograms</span><span style=\"color: rgb(102,\r\n 102,\r\n 104); font-family: \'Computer Modern Serif\'; font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 27px; text-align: right;\">:</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa{P\'(\\PalAb {1\\Tsp000})}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalAb {1\\Tsp000}}{50}+31\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%; vertical-align: middle;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa{11}\\text.\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This means, for an extra kilogram produced at a production level of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{1\\Tsp000}\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">kilograms</span>, the <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span> will increase by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa{\\Cur11\\Cdp00}\\)</span>. &nbsp;It is illustrated in the graphs of the <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span> and <span class=\"PalBa\">marginal profit</span> functions drawn below.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalBc\">Profit</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{P(x)=- \\displaystyle\\frac{x^2}{100}+31x-100}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"420\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/269.html\" width=\"630\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalBa\">Marginal Profit</span></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalBa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa{P\'(x)=-\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{50}+31}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"600\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/270.html\" width=\"630\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(762,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Watch this video on marginal functions:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/313.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(763,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A peanut farmer&rsquo;s</span>&nbsp;cost function&nbsp;in rand, is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( {C(x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{x^2}{100}+100}\\)</span></span><br>\r\nwhere&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(x\\)</span>&nbsp;represents the&nbsp;number of kilograms&nbsp;of peanuts pr<span class=\"BodyText\">oduced.<br>\r\nThe&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalBa\">revenue function</span>&nbsp;i<span class=\"BodyText\">s given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBa{R(x)=31 x}\\)</span></span><span class=\"BodyText\">, that is</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;each kilogram of peanuts produced is sold at&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur31\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">. &nbsp;The&nbsp;</span>profit function<span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\({P( x)=-\\displaystyle\\frac{ x^2}{100}+31 x-100}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Therefore, the <span class=\"PalAb\">marginal cost</span>&nbsp;is given by the derivative&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{C\'(x)=\\displaystyle\\frac{ x}{50}}\\)</span>&nbsp;and the <span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span> by the derivative&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{P\'( x)=-\\displaystyle\\frac{ x}{50}+31}\\)</span></span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Observe the linear graphs of the <span class=\"PalBa\">marginal revenue </span>function, the <span class=\"PalAb\">marginal cost </span>function and the <span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span> function illustrated below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"650\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/271.html\" width=\"650\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Marginal profit</span>&nbsp;is the profit that would be made by producing and selling one additional unit of a product or service. &nbsp;Therefore, the formula for the extra unit can be written as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBa\">marginal revenue</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(-\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">marginal cost</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>So, in the case of the&nbsp;peanut farmer, if:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal revenue</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&gt;\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">marginal cost</span>, <span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span>&nbsp;is <span class=\"PalAa\">positive</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal revenue</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(&lt;\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">marginal cost</span><span class=\"BodyText\">,&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is </span><span class=\"PalAa\">negative</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalBa\">marginal revenue</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">marginal cost</span><span class=\"BodyText\">,&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">zero</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In general we can say that since total profit increases when marginal profit is positive and total profit decreases when marginal profit is negative, total <span class=\"PalBc\">profit</span>&nbsp;must reach a <span class=\"PalBc\">maximum</span> where <span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span> is <span class=\"PalAa\">zero</span>,&nbsp;or where marginal cost equals marginal revenue.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is because the producer has collected positive profit up until the intersection of marginal revenue and marginal cost (where zero profit is collected and any further production will result in negative marginal profit, because marginal cost will be larger than marginal revenue).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">A company should continue increasing production<br>\r\n		and sales until the <span class=\"PalAa\">marginal profit</span> falls to <span class=\"PalAa\">zero</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(764,'return_url','\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(765,'Video','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction video</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Watch this video on discount loans:</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Video\"><video controls=\"\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/314.mp4\" width=\"650\"></video></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(766,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">An introduction to simple discount</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A <span class=\"PalAa\">discount loan</span> is a loan on which the interest and financing charges are deducted from the face/future value when the loan is first taken out. &nbsp;The borrower only receives the discounted value after the financing charges and interest are subtracted, but must repay the full amount of the loan.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">A discount loan is a short-term lending arrangement in which the<br>\r\n		interest amount for the entire loan period is calculated on and<br>\r\n		deducted from the face/future value at the time a loan is disbursed. &nbsp;<br>\r\n		The borrower pays off the full face value as arranged.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The discount <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span>, on the face value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span>, is then simply the difference between the face value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span>&nbsp;and discounted value&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(767,'Formula','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">A formula for simple discount</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Discount <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The discount <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span>, on the face value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span>, is the difference between the face value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span>&nbsp;and the discounted value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>. Thus the discount <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span>&nbsp;is given by:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D=S-P\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Finding the discounted or present value is not simply the reverse of finding the future value by the interest formula. &nbsp;Financial institutions introduced a <span class=\"PalAa\">simple discount rate&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(d\\)</span></span>, which is,&nbsp;similar to the interest rate, the fraction of the face value&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span>&nbsp;per time period which must be paid. &nbsp;This&nbsp;rate&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(d\\)</span>&nbsp;is expressed as a percentage.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The discount <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span> is given by:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D=Sdn\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 30%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">where</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the discount</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the face value (the ending amount)</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( d\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the discount rate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\%)\\)</span>, divided by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">is the number of time periods</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Here <span class=\"math-tex\">\\( d\\)</span> is the simple discount rate.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Discounted value&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"PalAa\">How do we determine the discounted value&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>? </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;The discounted (or present) value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span> is the difference between the face value and the simple discount:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The discounted value&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>&nbsp;formula is</span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S-D\\text.\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The discount <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span> formula is</span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S dn\\text.\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D\\)</span>&nbsp;into the formula for&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></span></th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S-(Sdn)\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\times1-S\\times dn\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\times(1-dn)\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 55%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S(1-dn)\\text.\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(768,'Time line ','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Time line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The discounted (or present) value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((P)\\)</span>&nbsp;of the face value&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((S)\\)</span>&nbsp;may be expressed in the form of the following timeline:</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe align=\"middle\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/64.svg\" width=\"625\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note two important aspects:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">This timeline is structurally very similar to the timeline for simple interest.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Since we are working with simple discount&nbsp;and the discount rate is now expressed as a percentage of the future value,&nbsp;not as a percentage of the present value,&nbsp;a negative sign appears in the formula.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This means that the discount <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((D)\\)</span>, calculated &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\times d\\times n\\)</span>, is <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">subtracted</span> from the face value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((S)\\)</span>&nbsp;to obtain the discounted/present value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((P)\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} P&amp;=S-D\\\\ &amp;=S-(Sdn)\\\\ &amp;=S(1-dn) \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(769,'Examples of each','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Examples of simple interest and simple discount</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style1\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<thead>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\">Simple interest</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<th colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"col\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalBc\">Simple discount</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p>Interest is calculated on the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> or <span class=\"PalAa\">principal amount</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 45%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p>Interest is calculated on the <span class=\"PalBc\">future/face value</span>.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p>The loan is an add-on loan in which the interest is <span class=\"PalAa\">added</span> to the <span class=\"PalAa\">principal</span>:</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 45%; text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p>The interest, called the discount or discounted amount, is <span class=\"PalBc\">subtracted</span> from the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> and only the proceeds are received by the borrower:</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P+I\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td class=\"Table_Number\" style=\"width: 45%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P=S-D\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 2%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Happy Homes furniture store wants to borrow&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;for <span class=\"PalAb\">two years</span>. &nbsp;Community Bank offers them a&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(10\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span> loan. &nbsp;National Bank offers them an&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBc\">simple discount</span> loan. &nbsp;The store wants&nbsp;to compare the implications&nbsp;of these two loans.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\">Community Bank</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">offers a</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {10\\%}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">loan.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following is given:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P=\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{i=0\\Ndp10\\text{ per year}} \\)</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{n=2\\text{ years}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The interest Happy Homes will have to pay on the loan is:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} I&amp;=P\\PalAa i\\PalAb n\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\times \\PalAa{0\\Ndp10}\\times \\PalAb 2\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur7\\Tsp600\\Cdp00 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The amount Happy Homes will have to repay after two years is:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} S&amp;=P+I\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00+\\Cur7\\Tsp600\\Cdp00\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur45\\Tsp600\\Cdp00 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalBc\">National Bank offers an&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc {8\\%}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBc\">simple discount</span> <span class=\"PalBc\">loan.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following is given:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P=\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{d=0\\Ndp08\\text{ per year}} \\)</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{n=2\\text{ years}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The amount Happy Homes must borrow in order to receive proceeds of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;now, is:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} P&amp;=S(1-\\PalBc d\\PalAb n)\\\\ S&amp;=\\frac{P}{1-\\PalBc d\\PalAb n}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}{1-\\PalBc {0\\Ndp08}\\times\\PalAb2}\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur45\\Tsp238\\Cdp10 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The discount subtracted from the future value of the loan is:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} D&amp;=S-P\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur45\\Tsp238\\Cdp10-\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur7\\Tsp238\\Cdp10 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp; We now have that:</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P=\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=\\Cur7\\Tsp238\\Cdp10\\)</span><br>\r\n		<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{n=2\\text{ years}}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span>The&nbsp;</span></span><span class=\"PalAa\">equivalent</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span><span style=\"\">&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">rate of this loan can&nbsp;now be determined:</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalAa i&amp;=\\frac{I}{P\\times \\PalAb n}\\\\ \\PalAa i&amp;=\\frac{\\Cur7\\Tsp238\\Cdp10}{\\Cur38\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\times\\PalAb2}\\\\ &amp;=0\\Ndp0952\\\\ &amp;=\\PalAa{9\\Ndp5\\%} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(770,'Comparing','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Comparing simple interest and simple discount</h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Simple interest&nbsp;</span>timeline</h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"260px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/272.html\" width=\"670px\"></iframe></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"PalAb\">Simple discount&nbsp;</span>timeline</h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 50%;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"260px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/273.html\" width=\"670px\"></iframe></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Differences between <span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span> and <span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"PalAb\">simple discount</span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=P \\PalAb{i}\\PalAb{n}\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(D=S \\PalBa d \\PalAa n\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P+I\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P=S-D\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P \\times(1+\\PalAb i \\PalAb n)\\)</span></span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P=S \\times(1- \\PalAa d \\PalAa n)\\)</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A <span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span> rate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{10\\%}\\)</span> (calculated on the discounted/present value) is <span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">not</span> </span>the same as&nbsp;a <span class=\"PalBc\"><span class=\"PalAb\">simple</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">discount</span></span><span class=\"PalAb\"> </span>rate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{10\\%}\\)</span> (calculated on the face/future value).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Similarities between <span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span> and <span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"PalAb\">simple discount</span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Borrower receives money at the <span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">beginning</span> </span>of the term.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Repaid with a single payment at the <span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">end</span> </span>of the term.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(771,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">Money is not free to borrow</span><span class=\"PalAa\">. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">People can always find a use for money,&nbsp;so it costs money to borrow money.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">How much does it cost to borrow money?</span> &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Different places charge different amounts at different times, but they usually charge it as a percentage <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\%)\\)</span>&nbsp;per year of the amount borrowed.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">Interest is the price paid for the use of borrowed money.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Think of interest as the rent you have to pay for using someone else&#39;s money.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Did you know that there is a cost of money even if you are using all of your own money? How? Since you are using your own money instead of putting it into a savings account, you are foregoing the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\%\\)</span> interest you could make on it.<br>\r\nThus, the cost of money in this case is actually <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\%\\)</span>!</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(772,'Borrower','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The borrower</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Interest is paid by the party who uses or borrows the money to the party who lends money. &nbsp;Interest is calculated as a fraction of the amount borrowed (principal amount) in a time period. &nbsp;The fraction, also known as the interest rate, is usually expressed as a percentage per year, but must be reduced to a decimal fraction for calculation purposes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Jane borrowed <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> from the bank for a period of <span class=\"PalAb\">one year</span> at a <span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span> rate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{12\\%}\\)</span> per year. So to borrow the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> for one year will cost:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align}\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\times\\displaystyle\\PalAa{\\frac{12}{100}}&amp;=\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\times\\PalAa{0\\Ndp12}\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur600\\Cdp00 \\end{align} \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The interest is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span> and the simple interest rate is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({12\\%}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Of course Jane will have to pay back the original <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> after one year, so this is what happens:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Today Jane borrows&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;from the bank.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Next year Jane pays back the bank&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;plus&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;interest.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">So, Jane borrows&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, but has to pay back&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp600\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;In this case Jane is the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">borrower</span> and the bank is the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">lender</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(773,'Investor','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The investor</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It can also work the other way around.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Jane invests&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;in a&nbsp;bank that pays <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{12\\%}\\)</span></span><span class=\"PalAa\"><font color=\"#000000\">&nbsp;</font></span><span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;per year&nbsp;for a period of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">one year</span><span class=\"BodyText\">. &nbsp;So to invest the&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;for one year, the interest she will earn is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5 \\ 000,00\\times0\\Cdp12=\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The interest earned is&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Of course the bank will have to pay back the original <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> after one year, so this is what happens:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Today Jane invests&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;in the bank.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Next year the bank pays back Jane&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;plus&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;interest.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Jane</span><span class=\"BodyText\"> receives </span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp600\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\"> from the bank after one year.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In this case the bank is the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">borrower</span> and the Jane is the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">investor</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(774,'How it works','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">How it works</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Jane wants to borrow&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;from the&nbsp;bank for a period of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAb\">two&nbsp;years</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;at a&nbsp;</span><span class=\"PalAa\">simple interest</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;rate of&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{12\\%}\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;per year. &nbsp;</span>Jane pays <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12\\%\\)</span> for the first year and then another <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12\\%\\)</span> for the second&nbsp;year. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is what happens:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Today Jane borrows&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;from the bank.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Next year Jane owes the bank <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00 \\)</span>&nbsp;interest.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">After two years Jane pays back&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;plus&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp200\\Cdp00\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;interest.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00 \\)</span>&nbsp;interest for the first year and&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00 \\)</span>&nbsp;for the second year.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">So, Jane borrows <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>, but has to pay back <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur6\\Tsp200\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>The interest Jane pays for <span class=\"PalAb\">two years</span> is:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\times\\PalAa{0\\Ndp12}\\times\\PalAb 2 =\\Cur1\\Tsp200\\Cdp00 \\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The interest is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur1\\Tsp200\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That is how simple interest works, you&nbsp;pay the same amount of interest every year. &nbsp;In this case it was <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00 \\)</span> for the first year and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00 \\)</span> for the second year.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(775,'The interest amount','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">The interest amount</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Simple interest can be applied in both the following situations:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Make one investment and leave it to gain the same amount of interest per year.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Borrow one amount of money which accumulates the same amount of interest per year.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The interest amount never changes; it remains the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">same</span> for every year.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(776,'Simple Interest Formula','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Simple Interest Formula</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">When and how interest is calculated gives way to different types of interest.<br>\r\n<span class=\"PalAa\">Simple interest</span> is interest which is computed&nbsp;on the principal&nbsp;for the entire term for which it is borrowed or saved. &nbsp;It&nbsp;is therefore due at the end of the term. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is given as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=Pin\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">There are four variables needed when determining simple&nbsp;interest. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;If you know any <span class=\"PalAa\">three </span>of these, the <span class=\"PalAa\">fourth </span>can be determined.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p>where</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p>is the simple interest (in rand) paid for the use of the money at the end of the term;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">is the principal, original</span>&nbsp;or total amount borrowed (in rand) which is subject to interest. &nbsp;This is also known as the present value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((PV)\\)</span> of the loan;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">is the interest rate&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((\\%)\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">, divided by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(100\\)</span>&nbsp;to get a decimal fraction. &nbsp;It</span>&nbsp;is the fraction of the principal which must be paid at the end&nbsp;of each period ( for example, each year) for the use of the principal; and</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p>is the term or time, that is the number of periods for which the principal is borrowed.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(777,'Annum and year','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Annum and year</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Note the use of the word <span class=\"PalAa\"><span>annum&nbsp;</span></span>or <span class=\"PalAb\">year</span>:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 45%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">How long is an annum?</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">It is one year.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 45%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">per annum</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">per year</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 45%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">per annum</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">each year</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 45%;\"><span class=\"PalAa\">annually</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"PalAb\">yearly</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The units used for the rate of interest and the term must be <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">consistent</span>. This means:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If the interest rate is per year (sometimes called per annum), then the term must be in years&nbsp;or a fraction thereof.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">If the interest rate is expressed for a shorter period (for example,&nbsp;per month) then the term must be expressed accordingly (for example, in months).</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">A distinction is sometimes made between the so-called <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">ordinary</span> interest year&nbsp;and the <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">exact</span> interest year. This means:</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAa\">ordinary interest year</span> is based on a <span class=\"PalAa\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(360\\)</span>-day</span> year.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">The <span class=\"PalAb\">exact interest year</span> is based on a <span class=\"PalAb\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(365\\)</span>-day</span> year</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">In an <span class=\"PalAa\">ordinary interest year</span> each month has <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(30\\)</span> days, each quarter <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(90\\)</span> days, and so on.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">In an <span class=\"PalAb\">exact interest year</span> the exact number of days or months of the loan is used.</span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Unless otherwise stated, we shall always work with <span class=\"PalAb\">exact periods.</span></span></span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">Other textbooks may use&nbsp;different symbols for the different variables.<br>\r\nThis should not be source of confusion for you.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(778,'Time line ','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Time line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A very useful way of representing interest rate calculations is with the aid of a so-called</span> <span class=\"PalAa\">time line</span>. &nbsp;For a <span class=\"BodyText\">simple interest rate calculation, the timeline is as follows.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe height=\"270px\" name=\"Asset 274\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/274.html\" width=\"680px\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(779,'Accumulated Sum Formula','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Accumulated Sum Formula</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">At the beginning of the term, the principal <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span> (or present value) is put down (or borrowed).&nbsp;&nbsp;At the end of the term, the amount or accumulated sum <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span> (or future value) is received (or paid back). &nbsp;The accumulated sum includes the interest received.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The accumulated sum at the end of the term <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span>&nbsp;is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">accumulated sum <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span> principal value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(+\\)</span> interest received</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 33%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Let</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 7%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">be the accumulated sum,</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">be the principal value</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%; text-align: right;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">and</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I\\)</span></td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"BodyText\">be the interest received.</span></td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">We arrive at a formula for the accumulated sum as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The accumulated sum is calculated as</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P+I\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The interest is calculated as</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(Pin\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Substitute&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I\\)</span>&nbsp;into the formula</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P+Pin\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rewrite the two terms</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\((P\\times1)+(P\\times in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the first term is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\times 1\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">and the second term is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\times in\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The common factor of the terms is</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Factorise the terms by taking out&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\)</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\times(1+in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P(1+in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the formula for the accumulated sum is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P(1+in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">There are four variables needed when determining the accumulated sum. &nbsp;If you know any three of these variables, the fourth can be determined.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The accumulated sum is also known as the maturity value, the future value or the accrued principal. &nbsp;The date, at the end of the term, on which the debt is to be paid is known as the due date or maturity date.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(780,'Change Subject of Formula','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Calculate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>: Changing the subject of the formula</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Sometimes, we do not only consider the basic formula</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=Pin\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">but also rearrange it, in order to obtain formulas for each variable respectively in terms of the others. &nbsp;We call this &quot;changing the subject of the formula&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the activity on the next page you will be given the formula <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=Pin\\)</span> .The values of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I\\)</span>, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span>, will be given and you will have to calculate the value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(781,'Present Value','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Calculate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span>: Present Value</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">It is possible to obtain the </span><span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span><span class=\"BodyText\"> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span> or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(PV\\)</span> from the basic formula for the accumulated sum or future value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span>&nbsp;in the following way:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 65%;\">\r\n		<p>Basic formula for the accumulated sum</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P(1+in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p>Divide by the factor&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1+in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{S}{(1+in)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{P(1+in)}{(1+in)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{S}{(1+in)}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 60%;\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%; text-align: center;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\div(1+in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">How do we interpret this result?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span> is the amount which must be borrowed now to accrue to the sum <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span> after a term <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span> at interest rate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span> per time unit. &nbsp;As such it is known as the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> of the sum <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Stated formally,&nbsp;the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> of a debt <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S\\)</span> on a date prior to the due date is the value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P\\)</span> or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(PV\\)</span> of the debt on the date in question, and is given by the formula</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(P=S\\div(1+in)\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">where <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span> is the rate of interest and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span> &quot;the time to run to maturity&quot;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(782,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Calculate&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span>:&nbsp;Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">How long will Lucy have to wait before her <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp500\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;invested at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(6\\%\\)</span> simple interest per year accumulates to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp100\\Cdp00\\)</span>?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can&nbsp;manipulate the simple interest formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=Pin\\)</span>&nbsp;and the accumulated sum formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P+I\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following is given in the question:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} P&amp;=\\Cur2\\Tsp500\\Cdp00\\\\ S&amp;=\\Cur3\\Tsp100\\Cdp00\\\\ i&amp;=6\\%=\\frac{6}{100}=0\\Ndp06\\text{ per year} \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We need to calculate the time period <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"BodyText\">First method</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The time is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} n&amp;=\\frac{S-P}{Pi}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{\\Cur3\\Tsp100\\Cdp00-\\Cur2\\Tsp500\\Cdp00}{\\Cur2\\Tsp500\\Cdp00\\times0\\Ndp06}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{\\Cur600\\Cdp00}{\\Cur150\\Cdp00}\\\\ &amp;=4 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the time period is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span> years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Second method</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Alternatively, the time can be calculated&nbsp;as in the following way.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The interest earned is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} I&amp;=S-P\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur3\\Tsp100\\Cdp00-\\Cur2\\Tsp500\\Cdp00\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur600\\Cdp00 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the interest earned is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur600\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">From the basic interest formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=Pin\\)</span>, we&nbsp;can change the subject of the formula to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n=\\displaystyle\\frac{I}{Pi}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can now calculate the time as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} n&amp;=\\frac{I}{Pi}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{\\Cur600\\Cdp00}{\\Cur2\\Tsp500\\Cdp00\\times0\\Ndp06}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{\\Cur600\\Cdp00}{\\Cur150\\Cdp00}\\\\ &amp;=4 \\end{align}\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Again, we find that the time is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(4\\)</span> years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Conclusion</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that these two methods do not differ much from each other.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the first case the formula for simple interest&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P(1+in)\\)</span> is manipulated to&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n=\\displaystyle\\frac{S-P}{Pi}\\)</span>, which is actually the same as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n=\\displaystyle\\frac{I}{Pi}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In the second case the interest <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((I)\\)</span> is calculated first and then </span>substituted into the formula <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(n=\\displaystyle\\frac{I}{Pi}\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(783,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Calculate <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span>: Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A client borrows money from a micro lender who offers short-term loans.<br>\r\nThe client&nbsp;borrows <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp175\\Cdp00\\)</span> and has to repay <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp349\\Cdp00\\)</span> after six months.<br>\r\nWhat yearly simple interest&nbsp;rate does the micro lender use to calculate the interest?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can&nbsp;manipulate the simple interest formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=Pin\\)</span>&nbsp;and the accumulated sum formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(S=P+I\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following is given in the question:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} P&amp;=\\Cur2\\Tsp175\\Cdp00\\\\ S&amp;=\\Cur2\\Tsp349\\Cdp00\\\\ n&amp;=6\\text{ months}=0\\Ndp5\\text{ year} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We need to calculate the interest rate&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span>. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Calculate&nbsp;interest</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The interest <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I\\)</span>&nbsp;is calculated as:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} I&amp;=S-P\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur2\\Tsp349\\Cdp00-\\Cur2\\Tsp175\\Cdp00\\\\ &amp;=\\Cur174\\Cdp00 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Calculate&nbsp;interest rate</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(I=S-P\\)</span>&nbsp;and therefore the formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i=\\displaystyle\\frac{I}{Pn}\\)</span>&nbsp;can be rewritten as&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i=\\displaystyle\\frac{S-P}{Pn}\\)</span>&nbsp;in the following way: </span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} S&amp;=P(1+in)\\\\ S&amp;=P+Pin\\\\ S-P&amp;=Pin\\\\ \\frac{S-P}{Pn}&amp;=\\frac{Pin}{Pn}\\\\ \\frac{S-P}{Pn}&amp;=i\\\\ i&amp;=\\frac{S-P}{Pn} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">So, the interest rate&nbsp;</span><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span><span class=\"BodyText\">&nbsp;is calculated as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} i&amp;=\\frac{S-P}{Pn}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{\\Cur2\\Tsp349\\Cdp00-\\Cur2\\Tsp175\\Cdp00}{\\Cur2\\Tsp175\\Cdp00\\times0\\Ndp5}\\\\ &amp;=\\frac{\\Cur174\\Cdp00}{\\Cur1\\Tsp087\\Cdp50}\\\\ &amp;=0\\Ndp16 \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore, the interest rate is&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(16\\%\\)</span>&nbsp;per year.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(784,'Introduction','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Introduction</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Would you prefer <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> <span class=\"PalBa\">today </span>or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> in <span class=\"PalAb\">five years</span>?<br>\r\nObviously, <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> today.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You already recognize that there is time value to money.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(785,'Time and money','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Time and money</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">A rand received today is worth more than a rand received tomorrow:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">This is because a rand received today can be invested to earn interest.</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">The amount of interest earned depends on the rate of return that can be&nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">earned on the investment.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Time value of money quantifies the value of a rand through time.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Definition\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p class=\"Definition\">A rand received today is worth more than a rand promised at some time in the future.</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In a financial transaction involving money due on different dates, every sum of money should have an attached date, the date on which it falls due.<br>\r\nIt means that the mathematics of finance deals with <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">dated values</span>. &nbsp;This is one of the most important facts in the mathematics of finance.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(786,'Present and future values','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Present and future values</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To understand the time value of money, we need to consider the present and future value concepts. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If <span class=\"math-tex\">\\( P\\)</span> is invested at an interest rate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i\\)</span> per period for a term of length <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb n\\)</span> <span class=\"PalAb\">periods</span>, it accumulates to</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalBc S=\\PalAa P(1+i)^\\PalAb n\\)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">and we call <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P\\)</span> the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S\\)</span> the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> of the investment.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Sometimes&nbsp;we are given the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S\\)</span> and wish to know the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P\\)</span>. &nbsp;To do this&nbsp;we can rearrange the above formula as follows:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\begin{align} \\PalBc S&amp;=\\PalAa P(1+i)^\\PalAb n\\\\ \\PalAa P\\times(1+i)^\\PalAb n&amp;=\\PalBc S\\\\ \\PalAa P &amp;=\\PalBc S\\div(1+i)^\\PalAb n\\\\ \\PalAa P &amp;=\\PalBc S\\times(1+i)^{-\\PalAb n} \\end{align}\\)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">In this&nbsp;latter case&nbsp;of finding the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> of some <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span>, the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa {PV}\\)</span> is often referred to as the discounted value of the future sum&nbsp;and the factor <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1+i)^{-\\PalAb n}\\)</span> is termed the discount factor.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This must not be confused with simple discounting&nbsp;for which a discount rate is defined. &nbsp;The rate used in compound discounting is simply the relevant interest rate. &nbsp;It would indeed be possible to introduce a compound discount rate, but this is not used in practice since it does not have a readily understood meaning.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The important concepts are those of <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> and <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span>&nbsp;and the fact that the process of determining present value is often referred to as discounting.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(787,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You want to have an amount of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> in your account one year from now. &nbsp;You can earn <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\%\\)</span> interest per year, compounded monthly. &nbsp;Calculate the amount that you need to invest now.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Invested for one year</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>We have that the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{S=\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span>&nbsp;and the interest rate&nbsp;written as a decimal&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(i=0\\Ndp08\\)</span>&nbsp;compounded monthly, for a one year term of &nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb{n=12}\\)</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAb\">time periods</span>. &nbsp;We need to calculate the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P\\)</span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The money needed now is:</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalAa P\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc S}{(1+i)^{\\PalAb n}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">\r\n		<p>or</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\( \\PalAa P\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S(1+i)^{-\\PalAb n}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\displaystyle\\frac{\\PalBc {\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}}{\\left(1+\\displaystyle\\frac{0\\Ndp08}{\\PalAb{12}}\\right)^{\\PalAb {12}}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({\\PalBc {\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}}\\times{\\left(1+\\displaystyle\\frac{0\\Ndp08}{\\PalAb{12}}\\right)^{-\\PalAb {12}}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 15%; text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 25%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur9\\Tsp233\\Cdp61}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 10%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right; width: 15%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur9\\Tsp233\\Cdp61}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You need to invest <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({\\Cur9\\Tsp233\\Cdp61}\\)</span> now.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Invested for two years</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Now suppose you were offered <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> after one year&nbsp;or <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp830\\Cdp00\\)</span> after two&nbsp;years. &nbsp;The interest you can earn is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\%\\)</span> per year, compounded monthly. &nbsp;Which one&nbsp;would you choose? &nbsp;Most people would probably take the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> after one year&nbsp;because it is money in their hands.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Take the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> after one year and invest it for another year at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\%\\)</span>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">\r\n		<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P(1+i)^\\PalAb n\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\({\\PalAa {\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}}\\times{\\left(1+\\displaystyle\\frac{0\\Ndp08}{\\PalAb{12}}\\right)^{\\PalAb {12}}}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 35%;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		<td style=\"width: 5%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(=\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{\\Cur10\\Tsp830\\Cdp00}\\)</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">At the end of two years you will have <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({\\Cur10\\Tsp830\\Cdp00}\\)</span>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We see that the two values are the same,&nbsp;since you have taken the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> and invested it for another year at <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(8\\%\\)</span> after which it had&nbsp;also accumulated to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\({\\Cur10\\Tsp830\\Cdp00}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Note that the dated values are not equivalent at some other rate of interest.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(788,'Time line','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Time line</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following time diagram illustrates the dated values equivalent to a given dated value of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur10\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe class=\"Image\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"410px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/287.html\" width=\"610px\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The following time diagram illustrates dated values equivalent to a given dated value <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(X\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><span class=\"PalCc\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"410px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/288.html\" width=\"610px\"></iframe></span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(789,'Forwards and backwards','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Forwards and backwards</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider an amount of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> which is due eight months from now.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Moving forwards</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"310px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/289.html\" width=\"610px\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose you do not have money to repay the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> after eight months and rather want to repay it after a year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you move <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> forwards, for example from month eight to month twelve, you will pay more than<br>\r\n<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;You will pay interest on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> because you pay back the debt later than originally planned.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The amount of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa{\\Cur100\\Cdp00}\\)</span> at month eight is the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P\\)</span>. &nbsp;You want to determine the amount at month twelve which is the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S\\)</span>. &nbsp;The value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb n\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAb\">four</span> because the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> is moved forwards by four months.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You can calculate the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> using the formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S=\\PalAa P(1+i)^\\PalAb n\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Moving backwards</h3>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"310px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/290.html\" width=\"610px\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose you obtained money from winning a competition and rather want to repay the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> at the end of month&nbsp;six.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you move <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> backwards, for example from month eight&nbsp;to month six, you will pay less than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;You will save on interest because you pay back the debt earlier than originally planned.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The amount of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{\\Cur100\\Cdp00}\\)</span> at month eight&nbsp;is the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S\\)</span>. &nbsp;You want to determine the amount at month six&nbsp;which is the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P\\)</span>. &nbsp;The value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb n\\)</span> is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb 2\\)</span> because the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Cdp00\\)</span> is moved backwards by two months.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You can calculate the <span class=\"PalAa\">present&nbsp;value</span>&nbsp;using the formula&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P=\\PalBc S(1+i)^{-\\PalAb n}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(790,'Rules','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Rules</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">We can formulate two simple rules regarding moving money forwards and backwards:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Style_Steps\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rule 1</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To move money <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">forwards</span> (determine a <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span>), inflate the relevant sum by&nbsp;<span class=\"Emphasis_1\">multiplying</span> by the accumulation factor <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1+i)^\\PalAb n\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<th scope=\"row\" style=\"width: 15%;\">\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Rule 2</span></p>\r\n		</th>\r\n		<td>\r\n		<p><span class=\"BodyText\">To move money <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">backwards</span> (determine a <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span>), deflate the relevant sum by&nbsp;<span class=\"Emphasis_1\">dividing</span> by the accumulation factor&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1+i)^\\PalAb n\\)</span>. &nbsp;That is equivalent to multiplying by a<br>\r\n		discount factor of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\((1+i)^{-\\PalAb n}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The point is that the mathematics of finance deals with dated values of money. &nbsp;This fact is fundamental to any financial transaction involving money due on different dates. &nbsp;In principle&nbsp;every sum of money specified should have an attached date. &nbsp;Fortunately&nbsp;in practice&nbsp;it is often clear from the context what the implied date is.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(791,'Recap','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Recap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Consider an obligation of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>&nbsp;which&nbsp;falls due in three years. &nbsp;Interest is credited quarterly at an interest rate of&nbsp;<span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12\\Ndp5\\%\\)</span> per annum.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"310px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/292.html\" width=\"700px\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Moving backwards</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose you want to repay the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> at the end of month six (two quarters from now).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you move <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> backwards from quarter twelve to quarter two, you will pay less than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;You will save on interest because you pay back the debt earlier than originally planned.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The amount of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc{\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00}\\)</span> at quarter twelve is the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S\\)</span>. &nbsp;You want to determine the amount at quarter two which is the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P\\)</span>.<br>\r\nThe value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb n\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAb\">ten</span>&nbsp;because the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> is moved backwards by ten quarters.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You calculate the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalAa\" style=\"color: rgb(78,\r\n 127,\r\n 187);\">present</span><span class=\"PalAa\">&nbsp;value</span>&nbsp;using <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P=\\PalBc S(1+i)^{-\\PalAb n}\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Moving forwards</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Suppose you do not have money to repay the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> after three years and want to repay it after four years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If you move <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> forwards, from quarter 12 to quarter 16, you will pay more than <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;You will pay interest on the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> because you pay back the debt later than originally planned.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The amount of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> at quarter 12 is the <span class=\"PalAa\">present value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAa P\\)</span>. &nbsp;You want to determine the amount at quarter 16 which is the <span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span> <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S\\)</span>. &nbsp;The value of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalAb n\\)</span> is <span class=\"PalAb\">four</span> because the <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur50\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> is moved forwards by four quarters.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">You calculate the&nbsp;<span class=\"PalBc\">future value</span>&nbsp;using <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\PalBc S=\\PalAa P(1+i)^\\PalAb n\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(792,'Example','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">From time to time&nbsp;a debtor (the person who owes money) may wish to replace his/her set of financial obligations with another set. &nbsp;On such occasions&nbsp;he/she must negotiate with his/her creditor (the person who is owed money) and agree upon a new due date and&nbsp;a new interest rate. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This is generally achieved by evaluating each obligation in terms of the new due date&nbsp;and equating the sum of the old and the new obligations on the new date. &nbsp;The resultant equation of value is then solved to obtain the new future value which must be repaid on the new due date.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Example</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Mr More Money owes <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> due in one year&#39;s time and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> due in two years time. &nbsp;Money is worth <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(12\\%\\)</span> per annum, compounded monthly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">He decides to reschedule his payments by paying <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> six months from now&nbsp;and the rest fifteen months from now. &nbsp;What will his last payment be?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Solution method</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">This example illustrates the replacement of one set of financial obligations with another equivalent set. &nbsp;Also note that in time value of money, <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">payments</span> equal <span class=\"Emphasis_1\">obligations</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">First, we represent the money on the timeline:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Image\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"260px\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"/FBN1502/assets/275.html\" width=\"700px\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Second, we determine each payment on the new due date of 15 months hence.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Obligations</span>: There are two obligations, namely <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur5\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Payments</span>: There are two payments, namely <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> and <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur x\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(793,'Replacing financial obligations','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Replacing financial obligations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The replacement of one set of financial obligations with another equivalent set is really just a case of:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">applying the rules for moving money back and forward,</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">keeping a clear head and</span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">remembering that&nbsp;at all times that&nbsp;only amounts that may be added together (or subtracted) are those with a common date.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(794,'page-locked','\r\n<p>Sorry you must complete the previous page before this page will be unlocked</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(795,'add_topics','\r\n<form action=\"../topics_add.php\" method=\"post\">Topic: <input name=\"topic_name\" type=\"text\"><br>\r\nOrder: <input name=\"ordering\" type=\"text\"><br>\r\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Add Topic\">&nbsp;</form>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(796,'Activity','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODU3NjI5Nzg1Njg1NDc5OCJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-12-15 10:34:47','',NULL),(797,'Activity','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODU3NjM5OTMwODU1NDgxMiJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-12-15 10:34:47','',NULL),(798,'Increase payment','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Increase payment</h3>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">The activity was probably a big eye-opener for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Most people do not realise what they really are paying in interest on a big long-term loan. &nbsp;It is also quite interesting to see what a big difference a little extra on your payment can make.</p>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(799,'Activity (Cont.)','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODU3NjUwOTQzOTE1NDgyMiJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-12-15 10:34:48','',NULL),(800,'Activity','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODU3NjYwNjUyMDM1NDgzMiJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-12-15 10:34:48','',NULL),(801,'Exercise','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ3MDk1MTU4NTk1ODQ2MTY4NyJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-12-15 10:34:48','',NULL),(802,'Questions','\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading2\">Assignment 02, Questions 4&nbsp;to 6</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">Submit Assignment 02&nbsp;</span><span class=\"BodyText\">on&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\">my</em><span class=\"BodyText\">Unisa. &nbsp;The marks will contribute towards&nbsp;your semester mark. &nbsp;You have to obtain the answers for all eight questions of Assignment 02&nbsp;before you&nbsp;submit Assignment 02&nbsp;on&nbsp;</span><em class=\"BodyText\">my</em><span class=\"BodyText\">Unisa. Therefore, you have to complete all the study units applicable to&nbsp;Assignment 02&nbsp;before you can submit it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">If possible, print this page so that you do not need to go through the whole study unit again to get to&nbsp;the questions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"Table_Skeleton\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading3\">First semester</h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n	<tr>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Unique number:&nbsp;<span class=\"BodyText\">675065</span></h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n		<td style=\"text-align: right;\">\r\n		<h3 class=\"Heading3\">Due date: 23 February 2016</h3>\r\n		</td>\r\n	</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Emphasis_1\">Questions 4, 5 and 6 are based on the following information:</span><br>\r\nAndrew bought a bachelor flat for <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur240\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span>. &nbsp;He made a down payment of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur100\\Tsp000\\Cdp00\\)</span> and obtained a <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(20\\)</span>&nbsp;year mortgage bond for the balance at an interest rate of <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(19\\Ndp5\\%\\)</span> per annum, compounded monthly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Question 4</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The size of his monthly payments are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur3\\Tsp983\\Cdp20\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp924\\Cdp11\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp323\\Cdp53\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur28\\Tsp096\\Cdp70\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">None of the above</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Question 5</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">The outstanding principal at the beginning of the second year, rounded to the nearest rand, is:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur139\\Tsp951\\Cdp00\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur139\\Tsp363\\Cdp00\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp266\\Cdp00\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur139\\Tsp421\\Cdp00\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">None of the above</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">After eight years the interest rate drops to <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(18\\%\\)</span> per annum, compounded monthly and the&nbsp;present value of the loan is <span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur128\\Tsp951\\Cdp39\\)</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"Heading3\"><span class=\"BodyText\">Question 6</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"BodyText\">His new monthly payments are:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur11\\Tsp822\\Cdp26\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur30\\Tsp880\\Cdp62\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp191\\Cdp04\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\"><span class=\"math-tex\">\\(\\Cur2\\Tsp543\\Cdp34\\)</span></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span class=\"BodyText\"><span class=\"Bullet_List_2\">None of the above</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-10-11 12:27:10','',NULL),(803,'Calculate I - Activity','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODUwMDEzODg2NDI1MzM5NCJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-12-15 10:34:48','',NULL),(804,'Activity','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODUwMDIwMDYzODM1MzQwOCJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"800px\"></iframe></div>','',1,1,'2017-10-11 12:27:10','2017-12-15 10:34:48','',NULL),(805,'Activity 1','<div class=\"iframeCover\"><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" class=\"ckeditorframe\" scrolling=\"yes\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://dev.unisaonline.net/e-content/tao-client/show?launch_url=https://dev.unisaonline.net/tao/ltiDeliveryProvider/DeliveryTool/launch/eyJkZWxpdmVyeSI6Imh0dHA6XC9cL3VuaXNhdGVzdDIuY2xvdWRhcHAubmV0XC90YW9cL3VuaXNhLnJkZiNpMTQ2ODUwMDI2MzE3ODI1MzQxNiJ9\" type=\"text/html\" width=\"